{"title_page": "Honolulu Rail Transit", "text_new": "{{short description|Rapid transit system in Honolulu County, Oahu, Hawaii}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width                       = auto\n| name                            = Honolulu Rail Transit Project\n| logo                            = Hart-wordmark.svg\n| logo_width                      = 200px\n| image                           = Honolulu rail project construction in Waipahu near Fort Weaver Road 2015-07-29.jpg\n| image_width                     = 250px\n| caption                         = Project construction in [[Waipahu]], July 2015\n| type                            = [[Light metro]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bogonovich |first1=Mike |title=Automated Light Metro for Honolulu |url=https://ascelibrary.org/doi/abs/10.1061/9780784412862.014 |website=https://ascelibrary.org/ |publisher=[[American Society of Civil Engineers]] |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Sandy |title= Honolulu Negotiates With Feds Over Light Metro Line |url=https://nextcity.org/daily/entry/honolulu-light-metro-line-sydney-adding-metro-twin-cities-light-rail |accessdate=25 September 2019 |agency=Next City}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Light rail? Heavy rail? Subway? Rail transit modes fall on a continuum |url=https://ggwash.org/view/71583/light-rail-heavy-rail-subway-rail-transit-modes-fall-on-a-continuum |accessdate=25 September 2019 |agency=Greater Greater Washington |date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| system                          = \n| locale                          = [[Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n| start                           = [[Kapolei|East Kapolei]]\n| end                             = [[Ala Moana Center]]\n| stations                        = 21\n| routes                          = 1\n| status                          = Under construction\n| open                            = *Phase I: Late 2020 <br/> (East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium)\n*Phase II: 2022 <br/> (Aloha Stadium to Middle Street)\n*Phase III: Late 2025 <br/> (Middle Street to Ala Moana Center)<ref name=NaInoa-2>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22716/20190415-na-inoa-hawaiian-station-names.pdf |title=N\u0101 Inoa |date=April 15, 2019 |publisher=honolulu.gov |accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| owner                           = [https://www.honolulutransit.org/ HART]\n| operator                        = \n| character                       = Almost entirely [[Elevated rail|elevated]]\n| stock                           = [[Hitachi Rail Italy]] [[AnsaldoBreda Driverless Metro|(Driverless Metro)]]\n| linelength                      = {{convert|20|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = 2\n| gauge                           = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on|first=imp}}\n| daily_ridership                 = \n| electrification                 = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]<ref>{{cite web |title=TP -1: Core Systems Description Honolulu High -Capacity Transit Corridor Project |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14720/TP-1CSDescr.pdf |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| map_state                       = collapsed\n| map                             = {{Honolulu Rail Route}}\n| map_name                        = Route diagram\n| website                         = {{URL|www.honolulutransit.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Honolulu Rail Transit''' Project (also known as the '''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project''') is an urban rail [[rapid transit]] system under construction in [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|Honolulu County]], [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]], U.S. The mostly-elevated system features design elements from both [[Passenger rail terminology|heavy rail]] systems and [[light metro]]s,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mangieri|first1=Gina|title=Could light rail help train reach Ala Moana and beyond?|url=http://khon2.com/2016/05/19/could-light-rail-help-train-reach-ala-moana-and-beyond/|accessdate=October 28, 2016|publisher=KHON2|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref> with a [[commuter rail]]-like design incorporated into trains and suburban stations.  It will become the first large-scale publicly run metro system in the United States to feature [[platform screen doors]] and driverless trainsets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansaldohonolulurail.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5&Itemid=5|title=The Honolulu Rail Project - Based on the Copenhagen Driverless Metro System|first=|last=Administrator|website=ansaldohonolulurail.com}}</ref> The first phase of the project, linking [[Kapolei, Hawaii|East Kapolei]] and [[Aloha Stadium]], is scheduled to open in late 2020. Its second phase continuing the line across urban Honolulu to [[Ala Moana Center]] is due to open in December 2025.\n\nFor more than 20 \nyears, debate over the development of a rail system in Honolulu has been a major point of contention in local politics, especially leading into the 2008, [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2012|2012]], and [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2016|2016]] election cycles. Proponents of the system say it will alleviate worsening [[traffic congestion]], already among the worst in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"worsttraffic\">{{cite web|title=Honolulu ranked worst in country for traffic|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18599683/honolulu-ranked-worst-in-country-for-traffic|publisher=Hawaii News now|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>  They assert that the urban agglomeration in south Oahu is ideally suited to rail as it is constrained by mountains to a narrow strip along the coast, which will be well served by a single rail line and which has the fourth highest population density in the US. Freeway advocate [[Panos Prevedouros]] has questioned its cost effectiveness compared to alternatives<ref name=\"worsttraffic\"/> and claims that it will have marginal impact on future congestion and that new roads will therefore still be required.<ref>{{cite web|title=What Can We Do About the Rail? Nothing. Tackle Traffic Congestion!|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/01/what-can-we-do-about-the-rail-nothing-tackle-traffic-congestion/|publisher=Honolulu City Beat|accessdate=August 31, 2017|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref> The rest of the rail opponents mostly object to its cost.\n\nThe project is financed by a surcharge on local taxes as well as a $1.55&nbsp;billion grant from the [[Federal Transit Administration|Federal Transit Administration (FTA)]].  After major cost overruns, the tax surcharges were extended in 2016 by five years to raise another $1.2&nbsp;billion; however that additional funding was only sufficient for construction out to Middle Street in [[Kalihi]].  The FTA stated that its contribution is contingent to completion of the line all the way to Ala Moana Center and will not be increased.<ref name=\"CRAIGT.KOJIMA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/fta-says-no-to-stopping-rail-at-middle-street-additional-funding/ |first=Craig T. |last=Kojima |title=Feds to city: No more money for rail, no stopping at Middle Street |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> After much wrangling, the state legislature in 2017 approved $2.4&nbsp;billion in additional taxes to allow the city to complete the project according to the original plan.<ref name=\"Nanea.Kalani\">{{cite news | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/01/breaking-news/rail-bail-out-bill-goes-to-ige-after-house-approves/ |author=Nanea Kalani |title=Rail bail-out bill goes to Ige after House approves|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=September 1, 2017 |accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the final {{convert|4.3|mi|km|adj=on}} section through downtown Honolulu, which is expected to be the most difficult to build, is just starting.  The contractor selection process for this section was restarted in September 2017 and is expected to take eighteen months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rail officials start over on selecting builder for last stretch|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/07/hawaii-news/rail-officials-start-over-on-selecting-builder-for-last-stretch/?HSA=af10a21d7a7762a176d7320f3ad163e48af2b7c4|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=September 25, 2017|date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> The first major contract for that section, a $400 million contract to relocate utilities to clear the path of the line, was awarded in May 2018.<ref name=HSA-180507/>\n\nThe final cost has grown from preliminary projections of $4&nbsp;billion in 2006<ref name=\"2006cost3billion\" /> to between $9&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\">{{cite web|title=The Estimated Cost Of Honolulu Rail Just Dropped By $1 Billion|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/the-estimated-cost-of-honolulu-rail-just-dropped-by-1-billion/|accessdate=September 25, 2017|date=September 18, 2017}}</ref> and $10&nbsp;billion by 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caldwell says state lawmakers\u2019 rail-funding plan falls short|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/08/24/breaking-news/caldwell-says-state-lawmakerss-rail-funding-plan-falls-short/|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref>  Critics have called for a \"forensic audit\" to establish the cause of the increase.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hard Reality Of Honolulu Rail Costs|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/08/the-hard-reality-of-hart-costs/|website=Honolulu Civil Beat|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=City rail audit won\u2019t look for fraud?|url=http://www.grassrootinstitute.org/2017/08/city-rail-audit-wont-look-for-fraud/|website=Grassroot Institute|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rep Tupola Backs Forensic Audit for HART|url=http://www.hawaiifreepress.com/ArticlesMain/tabid/56/ID/20121/Rep-Tupola-Backs-Forensic-Audit-for-HART.aspx|website=Hawai`i Free Press|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=August 15, 2017}}</ref>  The tax increase legislation passed in 2017 also requires the State auditor carry out an audit of the project's accounts<ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\" /> and to consider alternatives for completing the system.<ref name=\"bringdowntoearth\" />\n\n==History==\nPlans for a [[mass transit]] line to connect Honolulu's urban center with outlying areas began in the 1960s,<ref name=\"Blaisdell\">{{Citation |title=Blaisdell hails Oahu mass transit project |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |pages=A12 |date=May 24, 1966}}</ref> but funding was not approved until 2005.<ref name=\"13 years\">{{citation |last=Reyes |first=B.J. |title=Council gives transit go-ahead 13 years after initial rejection |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/story2.html |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  The controversy over the rail line was the dominant issue for local politics leading into the 2008 Honolulu elections,<ref name=\"Referendum\">{{citation |last=Carlson |first=Ragnar |title=Hail to the chief |date=September 3, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |accessdate=October 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928114114/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |archivedate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> and culminated in a city charter amendment which left the final decision to a direct vote of the citizens of Oahu.<ref name=\"Charter\">{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Voters can derail $4B project |date=October 19, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601215930/http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |archivedate=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref>  Construction of the rail line was approved with 53% of voters in favor,<ref name=\"53% S\">{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |date=November 10, 2008 |title=Voters on route drive rail victory |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081110_Voters_on_route_drive_rail_victory |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> and ground broke on project construction on February 22, 2011.<ref name=\"Groundbreaking\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail ready to break ground |date=February 12, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110212_rail_ready_to_break_ground.html |accessdate=February 12, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Ground Broken\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=It's a go! |date=February 23, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=130 |issue=23 |page=A1 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110223_Its_a_go.html |accessdate=February 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Previous projects ===\nFor more than 50 years, Honolulu politicians have attempted to construct a rail transit line.  In 1966, then-mayor [[Neal S. Blaisdell]] suggested a rail line as a solution to alleviate traffic problems in Honolulu, stating, \"Taken in the mass, the automobile is a noxious mechanism whose destiny in workaday urban use is to frustrate man and make dead certain that he approaches his daily occupation unhappy and inefficient.\"<ref name=\"Blaisdell\" />\n\n[[Frank Fasi]] was elected to office in 1968, and started planning studies for a rail project,<ref>{{citation |title=Fasi To Start Rail Transit Study |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser |page=A1 |date=February 16, 1969}} (Note: At this time, the ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin'' and ''Honolulu Advertiser'' published Sunday editions jointly under the name ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser''.)</ref> named Honolulu Area Rapid Transit (HART), in 1977.<ref>{{citation |last=Tune |first=Jerry |title=A Transit Line with a HART |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=July 7, 1977 |pages=A12}}</ref>  After Fasi lost the 1980 reelection to [[Eileen Anderson]], President [[Ronald Reagan]] cut off funding for all upcoming mass transit projects, which led Anderson to cancel HART in 1981.<ref>{{Citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Reagan stops HART in its tracks |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |date=February 19, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Mayor to abandon HART, beef up buses |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |pages=A1 |date=May 5, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Glauberman |first=Stu |title=Mayor Calls HART Study to Abrupt Halt |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1 |date=May 5, 1981}}</ref>  Fasi defeated Anderson in their 1984 rematch and restarted the HART project in 1986,<ref>{{citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Transit system plan revived |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A3 |date=August 14, 1986}}</ref> but this second effort was stopped in a 1992 vote by the [[Honolulu City Council]] against the necessary tax increase.<ref name=\"13 years\" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Mariani |first=Jeanne |title=Rail line dead \u2013 for now |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1 |date=September 23, 1992}}</ref>\n\nFasi resigned in 1994 to run for [[governor]], with [[Jeremy Harris (politician)|Jeremy Harris]] winning the [[By-election|special election]] to replace him.  Harris unsuccessfully pursued a [[bus rapid transit]] project as an interim solution until he left office in 2004.<ref>{{citation |last=Dicus |first=Howard |title=Harris: 'Honolulu must build fixed rail' |newspaper=Pacific Business News |url=http://pacific.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2004/01/26/daily64.html |date=January 30, 2004 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  His successor, [[Mufi Hannemann]], began the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project (HHCTCP), the island's fourth attempt to build a mass transit system operating in a dedicated right-of-way.\n\n=== Studies ===\n[[File:City and County of Honolulu Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor HCTC 63 Survey Marker Honolulu, Oahu, HI.jpg |thumb|right|upright|Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor [[survey marker]] in the sidewalk at the corner of Kapiolani Blvd and Keeaumoku Street in Honolulu]]\nThe City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services released the first formal study related to the HHCTCP on November 1, 2006, the ''Alternatives Analysis Report''. The report compared the cost and benefits of a \"fixed guideway system\", along with three alternatives. The first expanded the existing bus system to match [[population growth]]. A second option called for a further expansion to the bus system, with improvements to existing roads. The third alternative proposed a two-lane [[Overpass|flyover]] above the [[Interstate H-1|H-1 freeway]] between [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]] and Honolulu International Airport, continuing over [[Hawaii Route 92|Nimitz Highway]], and into downtown Honolulu.  The report recommended construction of the fixed guideway, and is considered the city's official justification for building a rail line.<ref name=\"AA Report Released\">{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Council panel backs rail as mass-transit solution |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=November 3, 2006 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/11/03/news/story07.html |accessdate=October 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (November 1, 2006), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Alternatives Analysis Report'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Toc_Chapter1.pdf Chapter 1]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter2.pdf Chapter 2]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter3_to_End.pdf Chapter 3 to 7]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>\n\nA second planning document, the ''Draft Environmental Impact Statement'' (DEIS), studied possible natural and social impacts of the construction and operation of the HHCTCP. The DEIS was completed and cleared for public release by the [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA) on October 29, 2008. After minor changes were made to comply with state law, the document was distributed via the city's official project website four days later.  The DEIS indicated that impacts of the rail project would include land acquisition from private owners on the route, displacement of residents and businesses, aesthetic concerns related to the elevated guideway, and noise from passing trains.<ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/executive%20summary%20drafteis.pdf Draft Environmental Impact Statement Executive Summary]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (PDF), retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>\n\nThe city was criticized for timing the release only two days before the 2008 general election. City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]], running as a mayoral candidate against [[incumbent]] Hannemann, suggested that the city deliberately withheld key information to early voters who had already cast their ballots for the mayoral candidates, and a city charter amendment related to the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City releases portion of rail report |date=October 31, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081031_City_releases_portion_of_rail_report |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Shikina |first=Robert |title=Kobayashi rails against city for timing of report |date=November 3, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081103_kobayashi_rails_against_city_for_timing_of_report |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>  The anti-rail advocacy group Stop Rail Now criticized the report for not further discussing bus rapid transit and toll lanes, options studied earlier by the city in its Alternatives Analysis.<ref>{{citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |last2=Roig |first2=Suzanne |title=Hawaii rail transit cost now at least $4.34B |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |date=November 3, 2008 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/03/ln/hawaii811030342.html |accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (2008-11), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Draft Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/front.pdf Cover to Contents]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf Chapter 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143036/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf Chapter 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103144257/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%203.pdf Chapter 3]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 1)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140420/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-end.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 2)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%205.pdf Chapter 5]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf Chapters 6\u20138] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143502/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf References to Index] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414182019/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf |date=April 14, 2010 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf Appendix A (Conceptual Alignment Plans and Profiles)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_b_1108.pdf Appendix B (Conceptual Right-of-Way Plans)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf Appendix C (Construction Approach)] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5lwKtq3qH?url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf |date=December 11, 2009 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_d_1108.pdf Appendix D (Record of Agency Correspondence and Coordination)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf Appendix E (Record of Public and Stakeholder Correspondence and Coordination)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103142549/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, retrieved on January 5, 2009</ref>\n\nThe third and final official planning document, the ''Final Environmental Impact Statement'' (FEIS), was approved and cleared for public release by the FTA on June 14, 2010. The FEIS addresses and incorporates public comments received regarding the DEIS.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Final study for rail line gets feds' OK |date=June 15, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100615_Final_study_for_rail_line_gets_feds_OK.html |accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref>  The FTA subsequently declared the environmental review process complete in a record of decision issued on January 18, 2011.<ref name=\"FTA RoD\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail gets OK to break ground |date=January 19, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110119_Rail_gets_OK_to_break_ground.html |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Impact on Honolulu mayoral elections ===\nThe importance of the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project in the 2008 mayoral election led one observer to describe the vote as a \"referendum on rail transit\".<ref name=\"Referendum\" />  Two challengers emerged as rivals to incumbent [[Mufi Hannemann]]: City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]] and [[University of Hawaii]] professor [[Panos D. Prevedouros]]. Kobayashi supported a \"rubber-tired\" mass transit system, as opposed to the conventional steel-wheel-on-steel-rail system chosen by the Hannemann administration. Prevedouros, on the other hand, opposed any type of mass transit project, favoring construction of a reversible tollway over the H-1, similar to the Managed Lane option which the Alternatives Analysis studied and rejected as unworkable, and reworking existing road systems to ease congestion.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Mayoral debate turns raucous |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 10, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/10/news/story01.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  No candidate won a majority of votes in the September 20 non-partisan primary, forcing a runoff between Hannemann and Kobayashi;<ref>{{citation |last=Borreca |first=Richard |last2=Au |first2=Laurie |title=Hannemann and Kobayashi reset sights for Nov. 4 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 21, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/21/news/story01.html |accessdate=October 20, 2008}}</ref> Hannemann successfully retained his post with 58% of the vote in the November 4 general election.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Hannemann win re-election with 58% |date=November 5, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081105_Hannemann_wins_re-election_with_58 |accessdate=November 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2008, the Stop Rail Now advocacy group announced their intent to file a petition with the city to place a question on the 2008 [[ballot]] to create an ordinance that read: \"Honolulu mass transit shall not include trains or rail\".<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Rail critics utilize power of pen |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/04/22/news/story01.html |date=April 22, 2008 |accessdate=October 20, 2008}}</ref>  Stop Rail Now attempted to submit the petition with 49,041 signatures to City Clerk Denise De Costa on August 5, but was initially denied after De Costa claimed the city charter did not allow the petition to be submitted less than 180 days before a general election, as the wording of the petition called for a special election.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Lawsuit looms over validity of anti-rail petition |date=August 5, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/05/news/story03.html |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/rc030404.pdf Section 3-404] (PDF), [http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ Revised Charter of Honolulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907150738/http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ |date=September 7, 2008 }}, retrieved on February 25, 2009</ref>  Stop Rail Now filed a lawsuit to force the city to accept the petition, and the courts ruled in Stop Rail Now's favor on August 14.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City clerk rushing to certify anti-rail effort |date=August 20, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/20/news/story07.html |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>  Stop Rail Now's petition drive ultimately failed on September 4 when De Costa deemed only 35,056 of the signatures valid, well short of the 44,525 required.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/04/news/story03.html |title=Anti-rail group's effort denied by courts, clerk |date=September 4, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the possibility that Stop Rail Now's petition would fail, the City Council had however voted on August 21 to place a proposed amendment to the city charter on the ballot, asking voters to decide the fate of the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |date=August 21, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |accessdate=November 12, 2008}}</ref> Mayor Hannemann signed the proposal the following day.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |date=August 22, 2008 |title=Mayor vows to put transit on ballot |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/22/news/story04.html |accessdate=November 12, 2008}}</ref> The City Council's proposed amendment was not intended to have a direct legal effect on the city's ability to continue the project, but was meant as a means for Oahu residents to express their opinions on its construction.<ref name=\"Charter\" />  The charter amendment was approved with 53% of votes cast in favor of rail and 47% against. Majorities of voters in Leeward and Central Oahu, the areas that will be served by the project, voted in favor of the amendment, while the majority of those living outside the project's scope in Windward Oahu and [[East Honolulu, Hawaii|East Honolulu]] voted against it.<ref name=\"53% S\" /> In mid-2010, Hannemann resigned as major to run for governor and Kirk Caldwell assumed the position of interim mayor.<ref name=\"Dayton2019-01-11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/01/11/hawaii-news/premature-contracts-increased-rail-cost-by-354m/?HSA=eb247f207a1158b53d1b48d5858ca2997cc4061a|title=Premature contracts increased rail cost by $354M|date=January 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Dayton|first=Kevin|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2016|2016 Honolulu mayoral elections]] the main three candidates again took opposing views on rail. Honolulu City Council Member [[Charles Djou]], former mayor [[Peter Carlisle]], and incumbent [[Kirk Caldwell]] all ran for mayor with the stated goal of finishing rail. However, Republican Djou ran on drastically cutting spending on rail by cutting funding on buying cars on the rail before its completion, and hiring mainland consultants.<ref>Charles Djou, \"Rail\" (http://djou.com/issues/rail/)</ref> Kirk Caldwell also stated that spending on rail should be cut, but instead by shortening the rail to end at Middle Street.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32242522/caldwell-wants-to-shorten-rail-to-15-miles-ending-route-at-middle-street|title=Mayor wants to shorten rail route, ending at Middle Street|last=Mendoza|first=Jim|date=June 16, 2016|work=Hawaii News Now|access-date=March 11, 2017|last2=Lincoln|first2=Mileka|language=en|last3=Davis|first3=Chelsea}}</ref> Carlisle was the only candidate in full support of funding the rail system and stated that rail has gone too far to be stopped.<ref>Grace Lee, \"Mayoral candidate Peter Carlisle says rail project cannot be stopped\" (http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31997123/mayoral-candidate-peter-carl-isle-says-rail-project-cannot-be-stopped)</ref> Kirk Caldwell won the election, and promptly went on to adopt Carlisle's position that rail should be completed.\n\n===Delays and cost overruns===\nConstruction on the HHCTCP rail line was originally scheduled to begin in December 2009 but did not occur on that date owing to delays in the project review process and delays in obtaining federal approval of the environmental impact statement.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Honolulu rail behind schedule, with construction start unclear |date=January 3, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/03/ln/hawaii1030376.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Honolulu Mayor Peter Carlisle at Rail Groundbreaking 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|left|Honolulu mayor [[Peter Carlisle]] speaking at the project's groundbreaking ceremony]]\nIn January 2010, Republican Governor [[Linda Lingle]] publicly recommended that the city alter plans for the rail line after news reports on FTA documents where the federal agency raised issues over declining tax revenues in connection with a [[Late-2000s recession|global economic recession]],<ref>{{citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |last2=Pang |first2=Gordon Y.K. |title=Honolulu's rail costs put state at financial risk, governor says |date=January 9, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/09/ln/hawaii1090342.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> and commissioned a study by the state to review the project's finances in March.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Time short for Lingle's call on rail |date=August 26, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100826_Time_short_for_Lingles_call_on_rail.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  The state financial study, publicly released on December 2, 2010, indicated that the project would likely experience a $1.7&nbsp;billion overrun above the $5.3&nbsp;billion projected cost, and that collections from the General Excise Tax would be 30% below forecasts.  Then Mayor Peter Carlisle (Democrat) dismissed the study as \"damaged goods,\" and \"a pre-determined anti-rail rant.\"  He also pointed to several conclusions as \"erroneous\" and \"inaccurate\" before concluding that \"spending a third of a million dollars for this shoddy, biased analysis is an appalling waste of our tax dollars.\"<ref name=\"LingleReport2010\">{{cite web|title=Carlisle dismisses Lingle's rail report|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/2010/12/carlisle-honolulus-rail-project.html|website=Pacific Business News|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=December 3, 2010}}</ref> Lingle's Democratic successor, [[Neil Abercrombie]], publicly stated that the financial analysis would not affect his decision to approve or disapprove of the project, saying that the state's responsibility is limited to the environmental review process, and that decisions regarding the project's finances belong to the city and the FTA.<ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Abercrombie to weigh rail EIS |date=November 5, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20101105_Abercrombie_to_weigh_rail_EIS.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  Governor Abercrombie subsequently approved the project's final environmental impact statement on December 16, 2010.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Governor signs off on review of rail |date=December 17, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20101217_Governor_signs_off_on_review_of_rail.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  The Honolulu City Council held a hearing on January 12, 2011 about the state's financial review, but the hearing was not attended by any state officials, who had been invited to testify.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=State skips hearing on rail finance studies |date=January 13, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20110113_State_skips_hearing_on_rail_finance_studies.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, the FTA issued a \"record of decision\", indicating that the HHCTCP had met the requirements of its environmental review and that the city was allowed to begin construction work on the project.<ref name=\"FTA RoD\" />  The record of decision allowed the city to begin negotiating with owners of land that will be purchased for the project, to begin relocating utility lines to make way for construction of the line and stations, and to purchase [[rolling stock]] for the rail line.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=If they build it, will developers come? |date=February 20, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110220_If_they_build_it_will_developers_come.html |accessdate=February 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=LaFrance |first=Adrienne |title=Rail Groundbreaking: Phony or For Real? |date=February 21, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/02/21/9126-rail-groundbreaking-phony-or-for-real/ |accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>  A ground-breaking ceremony was held on February 22, 2011 in Kapolei, at the site of the future East Kapolei station along Kualakai Parkway.<ref name=\"Groundbreaking\" /><ref name=\"Ground Broken\" />\n\nIn March 2012, [[Daniel Grabauskas|Dan Grabauskas]] was hired on a three year contract as CEO and Executive Director of HART.<ref name=\"HonoluluGov2012-03-01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.honolulu.gov/csd-news-2012/5840-03-01-12-daniel-grabauskas-named-hart-executive-director.html|title=Danial Grabauskas Named HART Executive Director|date=March 1, 2012|work=City and County of Honolulu: Department of Customer Services|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> In 2014 HART CEO Dan Grabauskas blamed lawsuits, launched in 2011, for some of the cost overruns after bids to construct the first nine stations exceeded the budget by $100&nbsp;million.  His claims were disputed by the plaintiffs in one of the cases who said HART could have put the stations out to tender and that HART had deliberately delayed the legal proceedings so a judgement would only be delivered after a significant proportion of the line had been completed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu rail CEO blames cost overruns on legal challenges, but critics say it is incompetence|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-ceo-blames-cost-overruns-on-legal-challenges-but-critics-say-it-is-incompetence|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Burial issues===\nLike most major infrastructure work in Hawaii, construction of the rail line is likely to uncover historic human remains, notably in its downtown Honolulu section. The Oahu Island Burial Council (part of the State Historic Preservation Division, within the State of Hawaii Department of Land and Natural Resources) refused to sign a programmatic agreement on October 21, 2009, over concerns about likely  burial sites located along the line's proposed route over Halekauwila Street in [[Kakaako|Kaka{{okina}}ako]].  Three construction projects in the area since 2002 have each encountered unforeseen human remains that led to delays, and [[archaeologist]] Thomas Dye stated, \"The council is absolutely right that you should expect to find burials on Halekauwila Street\".<ref name=\"2009-10 Burials\">{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Burial council won't sign rail pact |date=October 20, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/20/ln/hawaii910200360.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Burial Council's core contention is the city's decision to conduct an archaeological survey of the rail line's route in phases, meaning construction on a majority of the line will be complete by the time the survey in the Kaka{{okina}}ako area is performed, which in turn increases the likelihood that any remains discovered will be moved instead of being allowed to remain ''in situ''.<ref>{{citation |last=Conrow |first=Joan |title=grave matters |date=May 26, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |accessdate=January 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119140503/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |archivedate=November 19, 2011}}</ref> In response to the Burial Council's concerns, the city agreed to begin conducting an archaeological survey of the area in 2010, two years earlier than originally planned.<ref name=\"2009-10 Burials\" /> The state Department of Land and Natural Resources later signed the city's programmatic agreement on January 15, 2011, over the continuing concerns of the Burial Council.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=City plan accounts for problematic burial sites |date=January 16, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110116_City_plan_accounts_for_problematic_burial_sites.html |accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe city's decision to conduct the archaeological survey in phases subsequently led to a lawsuit filed on February 1, 2011, by the [[Native Hawaiian Legal Corporation]] on behalf of cultural practitioner Paulette Kaleikini. The suit, which named both the city and the State of Hawaii as defendants, contended  that state law requires the full length of the rail line to have an archaeological survey conducted before any construction takes place, and seeks to void the environmental impact statement and all construction permits issued for the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Lawsuit claims rail endangers burial sites |date=February 1, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=129 |issue=364 |page=B1 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110202_Lawsuit_claims_rail_endangers_burial_sites.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Kaleikini's lawyers filed on February 18 a request for an injunction to stop work on the project until the case is resolved.<ref name=\"Ground Broken\" />  The suit was initially dismissed on March 23, 2011, after Circuit Court Judge Gary Chang ruled that state and federal laws allow the archaeological surveys to be conducted in phases.<ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Judge Rejects Suit Challenging Rail Survey |date=March 24, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110324__Judge_rejects_suit_challenging_rail_survey.html |accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref> Kaleikini's lawyers subsequently appealed to the Hawaii Supreme Court, which heard oral arguments in the case on May 24, 2012.<ref>{{citation |last=Hervey |first=Tiffany |title=Buried Truth |date=June 27, 2012 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |accessdate=July 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025223421/http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |archivedate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>  The court ruled on August 24, 2012, that it agreed with plaintiff Kaleikini that the archaeological survey needed to be completed before construction could take place, and that the State Historic Preservation Division did not comply with state law when it approved the project. The case has now been [[Remand (court procedure)|remand]]ed to Circuit Court.<ref>{{citation |last=Grube |first=Nick |title=Rail Derailed? Hawaii Supreme Court Rules Against Honolulu |date=August 24, 2012 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2012/08/24/16937-rail-derailed-hawaii-supreme-court-rules-against-honolulu/ |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>  On December 27, 2012, the [[United States District Court for the District of Hawaii]] granted the plaintiffs' injunction, and ordered that all construction-related activities in segment 4 of the archaeological survey be halted until compliance with the Hawaii Supreme Court decision made earlier this year is met.  This ruling does not affect construction activities in the first three segments, nor does it affect construction planning, design, or engineering in segment 4, which is the final segment to be built. The Phase 4 area encompasses the downtown area and its immediate environs, including [[Chinatown, Honolulu|Chinatown]], Mother Waldron Park, and Beretania Street. Judge Tashima, the only sitting judge on the case, ruled on condition of the injunction that the city is required to file periodic status updates on their compliance with the judgment. The injunction will then terminate 30 days after defendants file a notice of final compliance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schwind |first=Paul |title=Honolulu Rail Remedy \u2013 Phasers On Minimal |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-remedy-phasers-on-minimal/123 |work=Web |publisher=Hawaii Reporter |accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Social impact ===\nThe development of this project has been a major point of contention among environmental, indigenous, and residential interest groups, as the [[United States Department of Transportation]]  is accountable for nationwide compliance with Title VI of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>Lowe, Kate. March 2014. \u201cBypassing Equity? Transit Investment and Regional Transportation Planning.\u201d Journal of Planning Education and Research. vol. 34, no. 1. 30-44.</ref> Specifically, residents of the [[North Shore (Oahu)|North Shore]], [[Wai\u2018anae Coast]], and Central and East regions of Oahu, home to mostly middle and lower-class communities{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}, together with those of upper class Hawaii Kai and Windward Oahu, pay a higher excise tax without ultimately reaping the benefits of the Rail Transit project. Indigenous Hawaiians constitute large percentages of the communities scattered along the southwest coast of the island, where residents generally exist under the national poverty line, but the project may possibly serve wealthier, \u201clocal\u201d Hawaiian residents while bypassing the poorer [[Native Hawaiians|indigenous Hawaiian community]].<ref>Trask, Haunani-Kay. From a Native Daughter: Colonialism and Sovereignty in Hawai\u2019i. Common Courage Press, Monroe, ME. 1993.</ref> Numerous studies have identified various benefits, including increased home values and increased median household income, that fall upon residences located near a rail transit station; public transit implementation thus constitutes a measure of public and private investment in a community.<ref>Karner, Alex and Richard A. Marcantonio. April 2018. \u201cAchieving Transportation Equity: Meaningful Public Involvement to Meet the Needs of Underserved Communities.\u201d American Society for Public Administration, Section on Transportation Policy and Administration. Vol. 23, no. 2. 105-126.</ref>\n\n==Financing==\n=== Initial General Excise Tax (GET) surcharge===\n[[File:Mufi Hannemann.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Former Honolulu mayor [[Mufi Hannemann]]]]\n\nAfter winning the 2004 election, Hannemann announced that construction of a rail line was an administration priority.<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Director prioritizes rail transit |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=January 1, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/01/01/news/index5.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  The following May and upon prompting by the city, the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] passed a bill (Act 247) to allow counties a one-half percent increase in the Hawaii General Excise Tax (GET), from 4% to 4.5%, to fund transportation projects. According to the bill, increased revenue would be delivered to counties implementing the raised tax to fund general public transportation infrastructure throughout Hawaii, and to pay for mass transit in the case of the City and County of Honolulu.<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=City measure touts rail tax |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=May 5, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/05/05/news/index5.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\">{{citation|author=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation |date=July 29, 2005 |url=http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |title=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation Announcement 2005-11 |accessdate=June 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lwKtdvx1?url=http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |archivedate=December 11, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Money collected from the initial 4% GET would remain state revenue.\n\nRepublican governor [[Linda Lingle]] initially threatened to [[veto]] the bill, believing that money destined for county governments should be collected by the individual counties.<ref name=\"GET Success SB\">{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Late deal avoids transit veto |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/07/12/news/index1.html |date=July 12, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hawaii Reporter 1\">{{citation |last=Zimmerman |first=Malia |title=Surrounded By Democrats at the Capitol, Hawaii's Republican Governor Rescinds Decision to Veto Tax Increase Measure |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |newspaper=Hawaii Reporter |date=July 12, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809153228/http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |archivedate=August 9, 2007}}</ref> After compromising with legislative leaders and Mayor Hannemann, however, she allowed the bill to become law. On July 12, 2005, the bill was enacted as Act 247 of the Session Laws of Hawaii 2005, without the Governor's signature.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" /><ref name=\"GET Success SB\" /><ref name=\"Hawaii Reporter 1\" /><ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |last2=Dingeman |first2=Robbie |title=Deal puts transit tax back on track |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |date=July 12, 2005 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jul/12/ln/507120343.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>  A month later, the [[Honolulu City Council]] authorized the one-half percent GET increase,<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Transit project to raise taxes |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/index1.html |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref> and Hannemann signed the measure into law on August 24.<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Mayor signs tax, calls for multi-faceted traffic solutions |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/24/news/index7.html |date=August 24, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref> Act 247 required Honolulu to use the funds only for the construction and operation of a mass transit system, and barred its use for public roads and other existing transit systems, such as [[TheBus (Honolulu)|TheBus]]. Since no other county authorized the excise tax increase before the deadline of December 31, 2005, the Hawaii GET remains at 4% for Hawaii's three other counties.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" /><ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Excise tax increase begins tomorrow |date=December 31, 2006 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/12/31/news/story05.html |accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref> The increase went into effect on January 1, 2007, and was due to expire on December 31, 2022.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" />\n\nThe Legislature considered a bill in the 2009 legislative session that would have redirected income from the half-percent increase back to the state to offset a $1.8&nbsp;billion projected shortfall in the following three fiscal years.<ref name=\"2009 GET\">{{citation |last=Wu |first=Nina |title=Legislature battles to avert $1.8B deficit |date=January 22, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090122_Legislature_battles_to_avert_18B_deficit |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last1=DePledge |first1=Derrick |last2=Boylan |first2=Peter |title=Governor emphasizes Hawaii's deficit woes as Legislature opens |date=June 21, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/22/ln/hawaii901220369.html |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Hawaii State Legislature |title=2009 Regular Session, Senate Bill 1626 Status |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |accessdate=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615111105/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |archivedate=June 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Hawaii State Legislature |title=Senate Bill 1626 Senate Draft 1, Relating to Taxation |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |accessdate=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610135634/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |archivedate=June 10, 2011 }}</ref>  The bill was opposed by Mayor Hannemann and other city leaders who believed that redirecting the money would jeopardize federal funding for the project,<ref>{{citation |last=Nakaso |first=Dan |title=Stimulus could revive Honolulu, mayor says |date=January 24, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/24/ln/hawaii901240322.html |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref> and was eventually dropped after U.S. Senator [[Daniel Inouye]] indicated to the Legislature that he shared the city's concerns.<ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Legislature keeping its tax-raising options open |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Mar/11/ln/hawaii903110398.html |date=March 11, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Borreca |first=Richard |title=Lawmakers fear revenue slump |date=March 11, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090311_Lawmakers_fear_revenue_slump |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== GET surchange extensions and \"Hotel Tax\" surcharge===\nIn January 2016 the Council extended the GET for another five years to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding to cover a budget blowout.  The Council also required that the money raised by the extension go into a contingency fund and to pay for disability access to the system.  HART was required to provide quarterly financial reports to the Council.<ref>{{cite web|title=City Council approves tax surcharge extension for Honolulu rail project|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31076942/rail-tax-extension-approved|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=September 2, 2017|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2017 the Legislature, after meeting for a week in a special session on rail financing, approved further taxes to raise $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project.  The taxes include a further three-year extension to the 0.5 percent General Excise Tax surcharge, which will now expire in 2030, and a thirteen-year, 1.0 percent surcharge on the existing 9.25 percent statewide Transient Accommodation Tax (TAT) which is charged to tourists.   Efforts to pass a funding bill in May 2017 had failed and the impetus for the special session was a FTA deadline of September 15 for a funding plan to cover the shortfall.<ref name=\"Sep17taxespassed\">{{cite web|title=$2.4 Billion Rescue Bill For Honolulu Rail Wins Final Approval|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/2-4-rescue-bill-for-honolulu-rail-wins-final-approval/|website=Honolulu City Beat|accessdate=September 2, 2017|date=September 2, 2017}}</ref>  The bill also grants the state government oversight over the project including the appointment of two non-voting representatives on the HART board and calls for an audit of HART by the state auditor.  It was signed into law by the governor on September 5.<ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\">{{cite news|title=Honolulu rail bailout becomes law with Ige\u2019s signature |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/05/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-bailout-becomes-law-with-iges-signature/ |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser |accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Federal Transit Administration's request for recovery plan===\nIn mid 2016 the FTA requested that HART develop a \"recovery plan\" by August 7, 2016.  Also in June a separate report by Jacobs Engineering, the project management contractor, said under a worst-case scenario the final cost would $10.79&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"Jacobsworstcase\">{{cite web|title=New 'worst-case scenario' report reveals full 20-mile rail route could cost $10.79B|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32297303/new-worst-case-scenario-report-reveals-full-20-mile-rail-route-could-cost-1079b|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 group called \"Salvage the Rail\" published a plan, based on Option 2A from six alternatives proposed by the FTA to HART in 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2016/06/a-rail-system-option-that-offers-the-best-fit-for-honolulu/ |title=A Rail System Option That Offers The Best Fit For Honolulu |publisher=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]] |date=June 29, 2016 |author=Ray Tsuchiyama}}</ref> that would terminate the elevated section at Middle Street and run at street level to the terminus along a route one block inland from the HART plan.  The system would need to be reconfigured to use new driver-operated low floor vehicles, lowering the platforms on the stations already constructed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salvage the Rail: Group renews call to bring rail to street level|url=http://www.kitv.com/story/34272479/salvage-the-rail-group-renews-call-to-bring-rail-to-street-level|website=Island News KITV4|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=February 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MODIFYING HONOULU AREA RAPID TRANSIT (HART) FOR STREET LEVEL OPERATION IN DOWNTOWN HONOLULU (January 2017)|url=http://www.salvagetherail.org/uploads/9/7/4/0/97405512/report_modifying_hart_for_street_level_operation_in_downtown_honolulu_january_2017_rev_feb_1.pdf|website=Salvage The Rail|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>  Proponents say it would save $3&nbsp;billion and four years of construction, as well as avoid disturbing burial sites under the downtown area.\n\nAfter a lodgement extension was granted by the FTA, HART submitted its recovery plan in April 2017 which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable option.  An alternative \"Plan B\" to build only 14 stations within the already funded $6.5&nbsp;billion budget, was ruled out because of lower ridership, legal risks, insufficient contingency and other reasons.  The new project cost was $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing charges are included it could be over $10&nbsp;billion.  An updated schedule for opening said the section from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium will open at the end of 2020 and operation of the full route by December 2025.<ref name=\"HARTcommitted\">{{cite news|title=HART committed to rail project\u2019s original route in recovery plan submitted to FTA|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2017/05/01/hart-committed-to-rail-project-s-original-route-in.html|accessdate=August 15, 2017|publisher=Pacific Business News|date=May 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\">{{cite web|title=HART Recovery Plan|url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan|publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation|accessdate=August 15, 2017|format=PDF|date=April 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831140644/http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 HART submitted an updated recovery plan to the FTA with a new estimate price of $9.02&nbsp;billion. The plan still includes $8.165&nbsp;billion in construction costs, but has reduced financing costs of $858&nbsp;million following state legislation granting both prolonged and new taxes to fund the project.<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\" />  The State Auditor has been tasked to consider alternatives for completing the system, as part of its audit of HART.<ref name=\"bringdowntoearth\">{{cite web|title=Bring Honolulu Rail Down To Earth|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/bring-honolulu-rail-down-to-earth/|website=Honolulu Civic Beat|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=September 27, 2017}}</ref> As of January 2018 the FTA has not formally accepted the new recovery plan but has asked HART for more details including how it came up with its tax-revenue forecasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu Rail Recovery Plan Remains A Work In Progress|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2018/01/honolulu-rail-recovery-plan-remains-a-work-in-progress/|publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat|accessdate=January 11, 2018|date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the FTA served HART with two subpoenas.  The first asked the agency to send investigators documents relating to its real estate acquisition program.  HART said some of the documents show it overspent on relocating residents and businesses along the rail route, which may have cost up to $4 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Feds serve Honolulu's rail agency with 2nd subpoena |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/government-issues/news/733170/feds-serve-honolulu-s-rail-agency-with-2nd-subpoena?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M}}</ref> The second sought the minutes from all board of directors meetings from 2011 through 2018, including the board-members\u2019 private discussions in executive sessions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Honolulu rail project subpoenaed by feds for third time |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/news/733197/honolulu-rail-project-subpoenaed-by-feds-for-third-time?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the FTA accepted the recovery plan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/05/breaking-news/fta-approves-honolulu-rail-recovery-plan/ |title=FTA approves Honolulu rail recovery plan |author=Dayton, Kevin |date=September 5, 2019 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Honolulu Rail Project Groundbreaking Dignitaries 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|left|City and state politicians at the project's groundbreaking ceremony]]\n\nThe project constructs an almost entirely elevated rapid transit line from the eastern edge of [[Kapolei]], near the [[University of Hawaii-West Oahu]] campus, to Ala Moana Center (East of Honolulu downtown).  The line passes through communities along southern Oahu, via [[Honolulu International Airport]] and [[downtown Honolulu]].  It will have twenty-one stations and run from Kapolei to Honolulu, passing through [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]], Pearl City, [[Waimalu, Hawaii|Waimalu]], [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], and [[Halawa, Hawaii|Halawa]]. Originally, the line was to fork near Aloha Stadium into two routes, one passing further south via Honolulu International Airport, and the other through Salt Lake, before reuniting at Middle Street in Kalihi. The city council initially decided to build the Salt Lake route before the airport route, as a result of horse-trading with City Councilmember [[Romy Cachola]], whose constituents included Salt Lake residents and whose vote was needed to pass the decision.<ref>{{citation |last=Consillio |first=Kristen |title=Rail route changes trigger harsh words |date=November 17, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081117_rail_route_changes_trigger_harsh_words |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Rail Route to Go Via Salt Lake |date=February 22, 2007 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/02/22/news/story01.html |accessdate=January 18, 2008}}</ref> After the city charter amendment on rail transit passed, the City Council reconsidered the decision, and decided to re-route the rail line to pass by [[Pearl Harbor]] and the airport, without a Salt Lake alignment.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=New rail route OK'd |date=January 29, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090129_New_rail_route_OKd |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"2009routechange\">{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Council changes transit route to serve airport |date=January 29, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/29/ln/hawaii901290352.html |accessdate=January 29, 2002}}</ref> The airport route is 4% more expensive, but is expected to have significantly higher ridership since it will ferry workers to both the airport and the [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam|Pearl Harbor military base]]. The only at-grade trackage will be a {{convert|0.6|mi|adj=on}} section near [[Leeward Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sneider |first1=Julie |title=Honolulu transit leaders eye late 2020 start to city's first passenger-rail system |url=https://www.progressiverailroading.com/passenger_rail/article/Honolulu-transit-leaders-eye-late-2020-start-to-citys-first-passenger-rail-system--58258 |accessdate=17 December 2019 |agency=Progressive Railroading |date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|11}}, the western portion of the line ({{stn|East Kapolei}} \u2013 {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}) is scheduled to open in late 2020, and the full line ({{stn|East Kapolei}} \u2013 {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}) is scheduled to open in late 2025.<ref name=RailFAQ>{{cite web |author=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=Rail Facts |url=http://honolulutransit.org/inform/rail-facts?catid=0 |accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref> The project is divided into four segments or sections, with overlapping construction periods and revenue service dates.<ref name=Sections/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:100%;\"\n|+HART Route sections and schedule\n|-\n| colspan=7 | [[File:Honolulu Rail Transit map with extensions.svg|800px]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Section name<ref name=Sections/> !! Length !! colspan=2 | Terminii !! Opening !! Ref.\n|-\n! style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 1 !! style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;\" | ''West Oahu-Farrington''\n| {{convert|6.9|mi}}\n| {{stn|East Kapolei}} || {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-116 |title=West Oahu-Farrington Highway Guideway Contract for Design-Build Construction Contract No. SC-DTS-1000137 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-112 |title=West Oahu Station Group -FD Contract No. SC-HRT-1200116 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-827 |title=West Oahu Stations Group Construction Contract |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-122 |title=Farrington Hwy Station Group Design Contract No. SC-HRT-11H0013 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-526 |title=Farrington Highway Station Group Construction Contract |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-476 |title=Farrington Highway Station Group II |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 2 !! style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;\" | ''Kamehameha Highway''\n| {{convert|3.9|mi}}\n| {{stn|Pearl Highlands}} || {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-123 |title=Kamehemeha ''{{sic}}'' Highway Guideway Design Build Contract No. CT-HRT-11H00195 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-124 |title=Kamehameha Highway Station Group Design Consultant Contract No. CT-HRT-130022 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-974 |title=Kamehameha Highway Stations Group Construction Contract No. CT-HRT-1600152 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 3 !! style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;\" | ''Airport''\n| {{convert|5.1|mi}} \n| {{stn|Aloha Stadium}} || {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-117 |title=Airport Segment Guideway and Utilities Contract No. SC-HRT-1200038 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-106 |title=Airport Station Group Design Consultant Contract No. SC-HRT-1200038 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-1007 |title=Airport Guideway and Stations Design-Build Contract No. CT-HRT-1600385 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 4 !! ! style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;\" | ''City Center''\n| {{convert|4.1|mi}} \n| {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}} || {{stn|Ala Moana Center}} \n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-121 |title=City Center Section Utilities & Guideway Contract No. SC-HRT-1200149 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=7 | <br/>The following extension sections are not funded and have no scheduled completion date:<br/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''West Kapolei extension''\n|  \n| {{stn|West Kapolei}} || {{stn|East Kapolei}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''UH M\u0101noa extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}<br/>or {{stn|Iwilei}} || {{stn|University of Hawaii at Manoa}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/><ref>{{cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16821/20130930-final-supplemental-eis-4f.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project: Final Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation and Amended Record of Decision |date=September 2013 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''Waik\u012bk\u012b extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Ala Moana Center}} || {{stn|Lili\u02bbuokalani Avenue}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''Salt Lake extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Aloha Stadium}} || {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|}\n\nThe long term plan includes four extensions: two extensions east, from [[Ala Moana Center|Ala Moana Shopping Center]] to the [[University of Hawaii-Manoa]] campus and to [[Waikiki]], one extension west from East [[Kapolei]] to [[Kalaeloa]], and the link through [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]] which was dropped from the initial plans.<ref name=\"Map\">City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%201.pdf Rail Transit Map (Part 1: Kapolei-Ewa)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%202.pdf (Part 2: Waipahu-Aiea)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%203.pdf (Part 3: Stadium-Kalihi)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%204.pdf (Part 4: Kalihi-UH-Manoa/Waikiki)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, retrieved January 5, 2009</ref><ref name=\"RG 2009-10\">{{cite journal |title=First contract awarded for Honolulu light rail |date=October 26, 2009 |journal=[[Railway Gazette International]] |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/first-contract-awarded-for-honolulu-light-rail.html |accessdate=October 26, 2009}}</ref> In 2010 it was estimated the extensions could be completed after the initial four-section project, possibly as early as 2030.<ref name=HART-extensions>{{cite report |chapterurl=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16805/20110701-final-eis-chapter-02.pdf#page=48 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-594 |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project: Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |date=June 2010 |publisher=Department of Transportation Services, City and county of Honolulu |chapter=2: Alternatives Considered |pages=2\u201348 |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> None of these extensions is currently funded, but in November 2017 the rail authority took a first step towards preserving a corridor for the extension between Ala Moana Center and the University of Hawaii at Manoa.<ref name=\"ManoaExtension\">{{cite newspaper |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/11/18/hawaii-news/rail-authority-looks-to-preserve-corridor-for-uh-manoa-option/ |url-access=subscription |accessdate=December 12, 2017 |title=Rail authority looks to preserve corridor for UH Manoa option |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |date=November 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen complete, the trains will carry more than 6,000 people per hour,<ref name=\"qaa\">{{cite web |author=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/honolulu%20rail%20transit%20brochure.pdf |title=Q&A: Honolulu Rail Transit |accessdate=January 5, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117201255/http://www.honolulutransit.org/pdfs/QA_100808.pdf |archivedate=January 17, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><!--The previous statement was that 20 trains would run per hour, an average 3 minute headway. The cited source states that each train can carry more than 300 passengers each, and more than 6,000 passengers will be carried per hour, which works out to 20 trains per hour via original research.--> from 4&nbsp;am to midnight.<ref name=RailFAQ/> It is estimated the trains will serve 119,600 daily riders.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/94176bf9f55a41d2a272684dede9e8e0/Hawaii-scrambles-to-keep-train-project-from-going-off-rails |title=Hawaii scrambles to keep train project from going off rails |author=Bussewitz, Cathy |date=August 26, 2017 |work=AP News |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\nOn October 21, 2009, the city announced Kiewit Pacific Co. had won the $483&nbsp;million contract to build the first two sections of the line (the {{convert|7|mi|adj=on}} long Farrington and {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} long Kamehameha sections), bidding $90&nbsp;million under the expected price. The stations were tendered separately.<ref name=\"RG 2009-10\"/><ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=1st Honolulu Rail Contract Goes to Kiewit Pacific at $483M |date=October 22, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/22/ln/hawaii910220359.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the rail line started from suburban areas in Kapolei and Ewa, and progresses east towards the urban center in Honolulu. There will be 112 columns from [[East Kapolei station|East Kapolei]] to Ewa.<ref>Tim Sakahara, \"[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project],\" ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2014, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref> The choice to start from Kapolei was made because the first phase must include a baseyard for trains, which is more cheaply built away from the center, and also because the city chose to delay construction in the urban center to later phases of the project due to associated major impacts to existing infrastructure and unpopular traffic delays.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=First phase of rail would end in Pearl City |date=February 25, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Feb/25/ln/hawaii802250354.html |accessdate=March 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TheBus (Honolulu) WP 20150721 17 10 58 Rich.jpg|thumb|left|Precast bridge segments supported by cylindrical piers were used to construct most of the guideway (2015)]]\nTo speed construction, the elevated trackway is built using [[precast concrete]] [[box girder]] [[Segmental bridge|bridge segment]]s.<ref name=Aspire15/> This method was first used for [[MARTA]] in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://aspirebridge.com/magazine/2013Summer/SegTransit_Sum13_Web.pdf |title=Rail Transit Bridges |author=Cox, William R. |date=Summer 2013 |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> The trackway was designed by [[FIGG Bridge Engineers]] (who were responsible for the superstructure, referring to the box girder segmental bridge) and [[HNTB]] (substructure, referring to the columns). It is supported on single piers, each {{convert|6|to|7|ft}} in diameter at the base and {{convert|30|ft}} high, flaring at the top to support the lower section of the box girder; the piers are themselves supported by drilled shafts from {{convert|7|to|8|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=Aspire15>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.aspirebridge.com/magazine/2015Summer/Project-HonoluluRailTransitProject.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (Sgements 1 and 2) |author=Rodriguez, Jose |date=Summer 2015 |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nCasting of the box girder segments began in 2014 at a rate of 13 segments per day; in total, 5,238 segments will be required for the first {{convert|10|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} phase.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.asbi-assoc.org/projects/project.cfm?articleID=3FB7A851-B3D3-C35F-B6CAB78D7E8F50A7&categoryIDs=44A57F74-F1F6-B13E-81940961706FF0A9 |title=The Honolulu Rail Transit Project Honolulu, Hawaii - Construction Update |date=Fall 2014 |volume=59 |magazine=Segments |publisher=American Segmental Bridge Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> The segments are cast locally in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/25280006/rail-systems-new-concrete-casting-yard/ |title=Rail system's new concrete casting yard |author=Daysog, Rick |date=April 18, 2014 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> Each segment weighs {{convert|50|ST|MT}} and measures (L\u00d7W\u00d7H, with length measured along the direction of the rails) {{convert|11|\u00d7|30|\u00d7|7|ft}},<ref name=CoC-presentation>{{cite report |url=http://www.cochawaii.org/wp-content/uploads/Daniel-Grabauskas.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Update |date=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Honolulu Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> and the deck ranges in thickness from {{convert|8|to|15|in}}.<ref name=Aspire15/> Once the piers were erected, a pier bracket ram was placed and a [[launching gantry]] was used to bridge the span between adjacent piers; a deck-mounted crane lifted the precast segments onto the gantry, which supported them while they were tensioned together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://somerseteng.com/project-gallery/honolulu-rail-transit/ |title=Honolulu Rail Transit |publisher=Somerset Engineering |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> In total, 430 of the 438 spans in Phase 1 were assembled using precast box girder segments, at an average rate of 1 to 2 days per span.<ref name=Aspire15/>\n\n[[File:HART Rail Construction (18599627918).jpg|thumb|right|Balanced cantilever construction over [[Interstate H-1]] in 2015]]\nFor the eight long spans required to bridge the {{jct|state=HI|H|1|noshield=1}}/{{jct|state=HI|H|2|noshield=1}} Waiawa interchange in Pearl City, a balanced cantilever construction method was used instead. This covers the segments from Pier 252 to Pier 256.<ref name=CoC-presentation/> Instead of precast segments, Kiewit used segments cast in-place, starting from the piers set in the freeway medians and working towards adjacent piers. The yellow-painted traveling forms at each end were used to cast each segment, then moved to the fresh end to cast the next segment. Each segment required {{convert|8000|lb}} of rebar and {{convert|48|cuyd}} of concrete, and weighed {{convert|105|ST|MT|abbr=on}}. 73 segments were required.<ref>{{youtube |id=Hums3p_LkjY |title=Time Lapse - Balanced Cantelevered Work over H1/H2 Merge}}</ref> The final pour for the balanced cantilever was performed in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-projects-balanced-cantilever-work-over-h-1-in-pearl-city-finishing-up/ |title=Rail project's balanced cantilever work over H-1 in Pearl City finishing up |date=September 17, 2016 |work=KHON 2 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Rail outside of Pearl Harbor (47934029428).jpg|thumb|left|Airport section underway near [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam]] (2019)]]\nThe third section of the route to be completed is the {{convert|5|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} Airport section east from Aloha Stadium to Middle Street that includes four stations, including the [[Honolulu International Airport station]]. [[AECOM]] won the contract to design the Airport section in 2012 with a $38.8&nbsp;million bid.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.aecom.com/press-releases/aecom-announced-today-that-it-has-been-awarded-a-us38-8-million-contract-to-design-the-airport-segment-of-the-honolulu-rail-transit-project-in-hawaii/ |title=AECOM announced today that it had been awarded a US$38.8-million contract to design the airport segment of the Honolulu Rail transit Project in Hawaii. |date=January 27, 2012 |publisher=AECOM Technology Corporation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The construction contract was awarded to a joint venture of Shimmick-Traylor-[[Granite Construction|Granite]] (STGJV) in August 2016, who bid $874.8&nbsp;million;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/hawaiis-8b-hart-project-is-chugging-along/30535 |title=Hawaii's $8B HART Project Is Chugging Along |author=Tobias, Lori |date=August 31, 2016 |work=Construction Equipment Guide |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32484731/hart-awards-airport-rail-construction-bid/ |title=Successful Airport-Middle Street rail segment bid totals $875M |author=Lincoln, Mileka |date=July 19, 2016 |work=Hawaii News Now |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> construction started in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.enr.com/articles/42730-funding-boost-shores-up-troubled-honolulu-rail-project |title=Funding Boost Shores Up Troubled Honolulu Rail Project |author=Parsons, Jim |date=September 13, 2017 |work=Engineering News-Record |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Airport section consists of 214 total spans which are also being constructed using precast concrete box girder bridge segments, like the earlier Farrington and Kamehameha sections, but for the Airport section, the segments are lifted and supported by an overhead [[gantry crane]] while they are tensioned.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://finleyengineeringgroup.com/projects/honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation-hart-airport-guideway-stations/ |title=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) Airport Guideway & Stations |publisher=Finley Engineering Group |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Both a conventional overhead gantry and an articulating gantry are being used during the guideway assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mcnarybergeron.com/portfolio/honolulu-rail-transit-project-hart/ |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (HART) |publisher=McNary Bergeron & Associates |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> More than 2700 precast segments are required for the Airport section, which also includes more than 230 columns for the piers and 5400 permanent [[sound wall]]s. For the pier foundations, shafts up to {{convert|350|ft}} deep were drilled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.traylor.com/projects/airport-guideway-and-stations-design-build-contract/ |title=Airport Guideway and Stations Design-Build Contrat |publisher=Traylor Bros., Inc. |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Where the guideway contacts the supporting piers, custom bearings have been installed to accommodate movement ranging from {{convert|2|to|19|in}} and rotation of 0.015\u20130.03 radians.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rjwatson.com/Projects/hart-airport-guideway-disktron-bearing-installation/ |title=HART Airport Guideway and Stations Project \u2013 Honolulu, Hawaii |publisher=RJ Watson Inc |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth and final segment of the route, the {{convert|4|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} City Center section terminating at {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}, may be completed under a [[public-private partnership]]. It is estimated the City Center section will cost $1.6&nbsp;billion to complete.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/post/hart-looking-private-partners-complete-last-16b-city-center-rail-segment |title=HART Looking For Private Partners to Complete Last $1.6B City Center Rail Segment |author=Yoshioka, Wayne |date=May 14, 2018 |work=Hawai\u2018i Public Radio |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Under the proposed public-private partnership, the City Center section will be procured under a design-build-finance-operate-maintain (DBFOM) contract, which will award the successful bidder the right to operate and maintain the entire system for a period of 25 years after completing the City Center section. The City of Honolulu would retain oversight over operations and maintenance, public information, and responsibility for fare vending and enforcement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://honolulu.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=3&clip_id=1000&meta_id=85914 |title=Public-Private Partnership Development Program {{!}} Program Structure |date=April 16, 2019 |publisher=Executive Matters and Legal Affairs Committee, City and County of Honolulu |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> A contract for $400&nbsp;million was awarded to clear utilities in the City Center section in May 2018.<ref name=HSA-180507>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/07/hawaii-news/hart-awards-400-million-contract-to-relocate-utilities-to-make-way-for-honolulu-rail/ |title=HART awards $400 million contract to relocate utilities to make way for Honolulu rail |date=May 7, 2018 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Stations ===\nLocal construction company Nan, Inc. won contracts to build six of the nine western stations in 2015; the West Oahu Station Group contract (for {{stn|East Kapolei}}, {{stn|UH-West Oahu}}, and {{stn|Ho'opili}}) was worth $56.1&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-18504/20150716-nr-hart-awards-construction-contract-for-west-oahu-rail-stations.pdf |title=HART awards construction contract for West Oahu rail stations |date=July 16, 2015 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> and the Kamehameha Highway contract (for {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}, {{stn|Pearlridge}}, and {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}) was worth $116&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/12/23/hawaii-news/nan-inc-wins-deal-for-last-trio-of-transit-stations/ |url-access=subscription |title=NAN Inc. wins deal for last trio of transit stations |first=Marcel |last=Honor\u00e9 |date=December 23, 2015 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The Farrington Highway Station Group contract (for {{stn|West Loch}}, {{stn|Waipahu}}, and {{stn|Leeward Community College}}) was awarded in 2015 to Hawaiian Dredging for $79&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16596/20150610-fhsgcc-rfb-hrt-798316-award-letter.pdf |title=Farrington Highway Stations Group Construction Contract No. CT-HRT-1500236 |date=June 10, 2015 |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The STGJV were awarded the contract to build the four Airport section stations ({{stn|Pearl Harbor Naval Base}}, {{stn|Honolulu International Airport}}, {{stn|Lagoon Drive}}, and {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}) as part of their $875&nbsp;million contract for the Airport section.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2018/09/20/its-coming-rail-work-kicks-off-airport-leg/ |title=It's coming: Rail work kicks off airport leg |author=Mendoza, Jim |date=October 26, 2017 |work=Hawaii News Now |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Hawaiian Station Naming Working Group (HSNWG), an expert working group, was named by the Honolulu City Council Resolution 09-158 on April 29, 2009 to develop [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] names for each station of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) system.<ref name=NaInoa-1>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21609/20180215-na-inoa-hawaiian-station-names.pdf |title=N\u0101 Inoa |date=February 2018 |publisher=honolulu.gov |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/ride/route-map |title=Honolulu Transit Route Map |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honolulutransit.org/media-center/planning/528-hawaiian-names |title=Hawaiian Names for Rail Stations |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> HSNWG proposed Hawaiian names for the nine rail stations on the [[Ewa District, Hawaii|Ewa]] end of the rail system (stations west of and including Aloha Stadium) in November 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21439/20171122-hawaiian-station-naming-program.pdf |title=Hawaiian Station Naming Program |date=November 22, 2017 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> and HART adopted the proposed names on February 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21921/HART%20New%20Release%20-%20Hawaiian%20Station%20Name%20Approval.pdf |title=HART Board of Directors unanimously approve Hawaiian names for first nine rail stations |date=February 22, 2018 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> On April 17, 2019, HART released a list of Hawaiian names proposed by HSNWG for the remaining 12 rail stations on the eastern end of the rail system, between Pearl Harbor and Ala Moana Center.<ref name=NaInoa-2/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/04/18/hawaii-news/newswatch/honolulu-rail-transit-authority-seeks-feedback-on-hawaiian-names-for-train-stations/ |title=Honolulu rail transit authority seeks feedback on Hawaiian names for train stations |author=Wu, Nina |date=April 18, 2019 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The 12 names were released for public comment, and the HSNWG will review comments before presenting a final list of names to the HART Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22715/HART%20Release%20(Station%20Hawaiian%20Names-Aloha%20Stadium%20to%20Ala%20Moana.pdf |title=Hawaiian names recommended for HART's rail stations |date=April 17, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22717/HSN-Program-Overview-2019.pdf |title=Hawaiian Station Naming Program |date=March 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:125%;\" | List of HART stations\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Name !! rowspan=2 | Section<ref name=Sections>{{cite web |url=https://planning.hawaii.gov/wp-content/uploads/HART-presentation.pdf#page=2 |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Overview |date=October 2016 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17073/20120525-ahupuaa-map.pdf |title=Ahupaa Map |date=25 May 2012 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" | Image !! rowspan=2 | Platform !! rowspan=2 | Opened !! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! Hawaiian !! English\n|-\n! {{stn|Kualaka\u2018i}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/579-kualaka-i-station-1-page |title=Kualaka\u2018i Station #1 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|East Kapolei}}\n| rowspan=7 style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;\" | '''West O'ahu / Farrington'''<br/>{{convert|6.9|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kapolei, Hawaii|Kapolei]], [[Makakilo, Hawaii|Makakilo]], and [[Ewa Beach|\u02bbEwa Beach]]. Designated [[park-and-ride]] station.<ref name=design>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/ride/design |title=Station Design and Features |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! {{stn|Keone\u2018ae}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/580-keoneae-station-page |title=Keone\u2018ae Station #2 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|University of Hawaii West O'ahu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[University of Hawaii\u2013West Oahu|Keone\u2018ae campus]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n! {{stn|Honouliuli}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/581-honouliuli-station-page |title=Honouliuli Station #3 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Ho'opili}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Ewa Villages, Hawaii|Honouliuli]]\n|-\n! {{stn|H\u014d\u2018ae\u2018ae}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/582-hoaeae-station-page |title=H\u014d\u2018ae\u2018ae Station #4 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|West Loch}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[West Loch Estate, Hawaii|West Loch]], [[Ewa Beach|\u02bbEwa Beach]], and [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Pouhala}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/583-pouhala-station-page |title=Pouhala Transit Center Station #5 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Waipahu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]] and [[Waikele, Hawaii|Waikele]]\n|-\n! {{stn|H\u0101laulani}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/386-halaulani-station-6-page |title=H\u0101laulani Station #6 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Leeward Community College}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Leeward Community College]] and [[Waikele, Hawaii|Waikele]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2 | {{stn|Waiawa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/584-waiawa-station-page |title=Waiawa Station #7 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}\n| rowspan=2 | \n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 |  2020 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves Pearl Highlands, Pearl Highlands Center, and [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;\" | '''Kamehameha Highway'''<br/>{{convert|3.9|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Kalauao}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/586-kalauao-station-page |title=Kalauao Center Station #8 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Pearlridge}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Pearlridge Center]], [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]], [[Waimalu, Hawaii|Waimalu]], and [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | {{stn|H\u0101lawa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/587-halawa-station-page |title=H\u0101lawa Station #9 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}\n| rowspan=2 |\n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 | 2020 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Aloha Stadium]], [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], Salt Lake, and [[Moanalua]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n| rowspan=5 style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;\" | '''Airport'''<br/>{{convert|5.1|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Makalapa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/588-pearl-harbor-naval-base-station-page |title=Pearl Harbor Naval Base Station #10 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Pearl Harbor Naval Base}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam]], and [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Lelepaua}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/589-honolulu-international-airport-station-11-page |title=Honolulu International Airport #11 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Honolulu International Airport}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Daniel K. Inouye International Airport]] and [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]]\n|-\n! {{stn|\u0100hua}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/590-lagoon-drive-station-12-page |title=Lagoon Drive Station #12 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Lagoon Drive}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves Lagoon Drive and [[Mapunapuna, Hawaii|Mapunapuna]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Kahauiki}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/591-middle-street-station-13-page |title=Middle Street Station #13 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}\n| rowspan=2 |\n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 | 2022 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Also known as Hauiki. Serves [[Kalihi]] and [[Honolulu Harbor]]\n|-\n| rowspan=9 style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;\" | '''City Center'''<br/>{{convert|4.1|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Mokauea}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/592-kalihi-station-14-page |title=Kalihi Station #14 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Kalihi}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kalihi]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Niuhelewai}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/593-kapalama-station-15-page |title=Kapalama Station #15 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Kap\u0101lama}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kalihi]], [[Kap\u0101lama]], and [[Honolulu Community College]]\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u016bwili}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/594-iwilei-station-16-page |title=Iwilei Station #16 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Iwilei}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Iwilei]] and [[Kalihi]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Holau}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/595-chinatown-station-page |title=Chinatown Station #17 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Chinatown||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Also known as H\u014dlau or Ho\u2018olau. Serves [[Chinatown, Honolulu|Chinatown]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Kuloloia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/596-downtown-station-18-page |title=Downtown Station #18 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Downtown||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Downtown Honolulu]], [[Aloha Tower]], and Capitol District\n|-\n! {{stn|Ka\u2018\u0101kaukukui}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/597-civic-center-station-19-page |title=Civic Center Station #19 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Civic Center||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves the Ward, [[Ward Centers]], and Maikiki\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u016bkulu\u0101e\u2018o}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/599-kakaako-station-20-page |title=Kakaako Station #20 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|K\u0101k\u0101\u2018ako}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kaka\u02bbako]], Maikiki, and Ward\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u0101lia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/600-ala-moana-center-station-21-page |title=Ala Moana Center Station #21 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Ala Moana, Honolulu|Ala Moana]], Ala Moana Center, [[Kapi\u02bbolani, Honolulu|Kapi\u02bbolani]], Mano, and [[Waikiki]]\n|}\n\n===Rail Operations Center===\nThe Rail Operations Center (ROC; also known as the Maintenance and Storage Facility) is the {{convert|43|acre|adj=on}} railyard, operations, and maintenance facility, divided into four buildings. It is in Pearl City<!--{{coord|21.390694|-157.988123}}-->, between the campuses of [[Leeward Community College]] and [[Waipahu High School]], just west of {{stn|H\u0101laulani}}. The design has been awarded [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Silver certification.<ref name=SRG>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21774/20180511-hrtp-system-resource-guide.pdf#page=9 |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project: System Resource Guide |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe buildings on the ROC campus are:\n* Operation & Servicing Building (OSB) \u2013 housing primary vehicle maintenance facilities and the Operations and Control Center, where operators will monitor and control vehicle movement\n* Maintenance of Way Building (MOW) \u2013 housing equipment used to inspect and repair tracks\n* Train Wash Facility (TWF) \u2013 an automated facility to clean vehicle exteriors\n* Wheel Truing Building (WTB) \u2013 a maintenance facility for vehicle wheels\n\nThe contract for the ROC was awarded to the Kiewit/Kobayashi Joint Venture in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16112/MSF-Contract%20Package-10A0449.pdf |title=Agreement for Design-Build Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1000449 |date=June 30, 2011 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> The contract was initially awarded at a cost of $195&nbsp;million; when the ROC was completed in July 2016, the actual incurred costs were $274&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-19156/201607-monthly-progress-report-low-res.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Monthly Progress Report |date=July 2016 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\n== Rolling stock ==\n[[File:Honolulu Rail Transit First Trainset 2017-02-18.jpg|thumb|right|First trainset for the rail project on public display in February 2017]]\n\nThe line will use {{convert|256|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} four-car train sets, each with the capacity to carry about 780 passengers, similar in weight to [[light rail]] systems elsewhere in the United States (such as the [[MAX Light Rail|MAX]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]), as opposed to heavier, and thus more expensive, lines found on rapid transit systems like the subways and elevated systems of [[Chicago 'L'|Chicago]] and [[New York City Subway|New York City]].<ref name=\"Rolling Stock 2011\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Have a seat |date=March 22, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110322_Have_a_seat.html |page=A1, A6 |volume=130 |issue=50 |accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> However, the stations will be standalone structures and will be substantially bigger than typical light rail stations. Physically, the Honolulu system will have a good deal in common with light rapid transit systems such as [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]] in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]] or the [[Copenhagen Metro]], as well as the [[Docklands Light Railway]] in London. The system will be the first metro system in the United States to feature [[Platform screen doors#Automatic platform gate|platform gates]] and will be driverless.<ref name=\"station-design-offi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx|title=Home|website=honolulutransit.org|access-date=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728211528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx|archive-date=July 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRolling stock for the line will initially include 80 cars in 20 four-car train sets.<ref>http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17047/20140218-hart-train-vehicle-fact-sheet.pdf</ref> \nEach car will be {{convert|64|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} long, weigh {{convert|72,000|lb|kg|sigfig=2|abbr=on|adj=on}}, and have 36 seats with a listed total capacity of 195 people.<ref name=\"Rolling Stock 2011\" />  The cars will be powered by a third-rail electrification system.<ref>{{citation |author1=U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration |author2=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |date=June 2010 |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |pages=2\u201330 |url=http://honolulutransit.org/library/files/02.pdf |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Contract and delivery===\nThe contract for the rail cars (named the Core Systems Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services contract) was signed on November 28, 2011 by HART and Ansaldo Honolulu, a joint venture between [[AnsaldoBreda]] and [[Ansaldo STS]].<ref name=CT-DTS-1100194>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14729/Agreement.pdf |title=Agreement for Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1100194 |date=November 28, 2011 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> AnsaldoBreda and Ansaldo STS previously collaborated on the construction and operation of vehicles for the [[Copenhagen Metro]]<ref>{{citation |last=Brown |first=Robert |title=FACT CHECK \u2014 Carlisle: Ansaldo's Copenhagen Line One of World's Best |date=April 15, 2011 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/fact_checks/2011/04/15/10342-fact-check-carlisle-ansaldos-copenhagen-line-one-of-worlds-best/ |accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Brescia Metro]]. Both companies were later purchased by [[Hitachi Rail]] in 2015<ref>{{cite news|title=Hitachi agrees to buy Ansaldo STS and AnsaldoBreda|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/hitachi-agrees-to-buy-ansaldo-sts-and-ansaldobreda.html|accessdate=February 25, 2015|work=Railway Gazette|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> and Ansaldo Honolulu was subsequently renamed to Hitachi Rail Honolulu (HRH). Under the $1.4&nbsp;billion contract, HRH is responsible for designing and fabricating the rail cars ($574&nbsp;million), a test to validate train performance ($167&nbsp;million), and operations and maintenance (O&M) during the first five years of revenue service ($339&nbsp;million), with an option to continue O&M services for HART for an additional five years ($318&nbsp;million) provided the review of the first five years is favorable.<ref name=CT-DTS-1100194/>\n\nThe two unsuccessful bidders for the rail car contract, [[Bombardier Transportation]] and [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo Corporation of America]], filed protests over the award.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=2 bidders protest city's rail decision |date=April 12, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110412_2_bidders_protest_citys_rail_decision.html |accessdate=April 12, 2011|volume=130 |issue=71}}</ref>  Both protests were rejected during the administrative process, but Bombardier sought judicial review of their bid protest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |title=Disqualified Honolulu Rail Bidder Bombardier Files New Appeal |date=October 14, 2011 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/10/14/13270-disqualified-honolulu-rail-bidder-bombardier-files-new-appeal/ |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref>  The administrative decision against Bombardier's protest was affirmed by both the state Circuit Court and the Intermediate Court of Appeals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abramson |first=Mark |title=Hawaii Appeals Court upholds ruling in Bombardier rail lawsuit |date=October 17, 2012 |work=Pacific Business News |publisher=American City Business Journals |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2012/10/17/hawaii-appeals-court-upholds-ruling-in.html |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>''[http://www.courts.state.hi.us/docs/opin_ord/ica/2012/oct/CAAP-11-0000756.pdf Bombardier Transportation (Holdings) USA Inc. v. Director, Department of Budget and Fiscal Services, City and County of Honolulu]'', 128 Haw. 413 (App.), {{West |P|289|3|1049|Haw. App.|2012|}}</ref>\n\nThe first two cars arrived in Hawaii in March 2016,<ref name=IRJ-1603>{{cite news |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/metros/first-honolulu-metro-trains-delivered/ |title=First Honolulu metro cars delivered |author=Barrow, Keith |date=March 29, 2016 |work=International Railway Journal |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/03/24/business/business-breaking/first-train-cars-arrive-in-honolulu-for-rail-transit-project/ |title=First train cars arrive in Honolulu for rail transit project |author=Honor\u00e9, Marcel |date=March 24, 2016 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> and the first train was unveiled to the public at the Rail Operations Center on May 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.hitachi.us/press/honolulu-new-transit-system-rail-cars |title=Honolulu Gets First Look at New Transit System Rail Cars |date=May 2, 2016 |publisher=Hitachi USA |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> To meet \"Buy America\" requirements for federally-subsidized transit projects, the bodyshells are fabricated at the Hitachi Rail Italy plant in [[Reggio Calabria, Italy]], then shipped to HRI's [[Pittsburg, California]] plant for final assembly.<ref name=IRJ-1603/> The Pittsburg factory has since been partially leased to Bombardier Rail, who will assemble cars for [[BART]] there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sf.streetsblog.org/2019/06/14/bart-train-plant-moving-to-pittsburg/ |title=BART Train Plant Moving to Pittsburg, CA |author=Rudick, Roger |date=June 14, 2019 |work=Streetsblog SF |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Hitachi Rail Italy reported defects were discovered in the welds in the extruded aluminum beams of twenty-seven car shells, four of which were already in Hawaii. The manufacturer will fix the problems, but warned delivery may be delayed as production of new vehicles will be halted.<ref>{{cite news |title=New defect could further stall rail|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/honolulu-star-advertiser/20161216/281479276058340 |author=Honor\u00e9, Marcel |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=December 16, 2016}}</ref>  In March 2017 HART said they would meet the interim opening needs after repair of the defective cars and that full opening would not be affected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Repairs to fix rail car production defects scheduled to start in March|url=http://khon2.com/2017/02/18/repairs-to-fix-rail-car-production-defects-scheduled-to-start-in-march/|website=KHON2|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017 trains were towed on tracks in Honolulu for the first time, to check clearances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu tests rail car on track for first time|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/30/breaking-news/hart-train-makes-first-appearance-on-guideway/|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref>  Testing of trains under their own power commenced in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=In successful test, city rail cars reach 40 mph on its own power|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/36632259/city-rail-cars-reach-40-mph-in-speed-test|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=October 20, 2017|date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of progress==\n* June 2006 - Officials estimate the infrastructure construction cost at estimated at $3&nbsp;billion, $200&nbsp;million more than a previous estimate, for a 24-mile system.  This does not include the cost of the trains.<ref name=\"2006cost3billion\">{{cite web|title=Rail transit system cost estimate: $3 billion|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/23/ln/FP606230364.html|publisher=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=June 23, 2006}}</ref>\n* January 2007 - The General Excise Tax (GET) within Honolulu County is increased by 0.5% with the extra funds earmarked for a mass transit system.  The increase was set to expire on December 31, 2022.\n* February 2007 - The City Council approves the Minimum Operating Segment from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Centre, via Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\" />\n* October 2008 - The Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS) is released to the public.  The projected cost is $3.7&nbsp;billion including $1&nbsp;billion for contingencies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Just the facts on Honolulu transit|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Oct/12/ln/hawaii810120332.html|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=October 12, 2008}}</ref>\n* November 2008 - Fifty three percent of voters support an measures to give the Honolulu City Council authority to proceed with \"establishment of a steel wheel on steel rail transit system\". The estimated cost is $4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |newspaper=Honolulu Star Bulletin |accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* January 2009 - The middle portion of the route between Aloha Stadium and Middle Street is amended to have stations at the Pearl Harbor Naval Base and the Honolulu Airport which had one of the original options.  The previous route followed Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name=\"2009routechange\" />\n* June 2010 - The Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS) is released to the public.  Estimated cost is $5.5&nbsp;billion.  Patronage by 2030 is projected to be 116,300 riders per day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu Rail: The Complete Final Environmental Impact Statement|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2010/06/2009-honolulu-rail-the-complete-final-environmental-impact-statement/|date=June 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=System Figures |work=honolulutransit.org |url=http://honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |accessdate=July 22, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729021514/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |archivedate=July 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n* December 2010 - A report, commissioned by outgoing Governor Lingle, is released which warns the project could cost at least $1.7&nbsp;billion more than the city\u2019s projected $5.5&nbsp;billion price tag.<ref name=\"LingleReport2010\" />\n* March 2012 - Dan Grabauskas becomes Executive Director and CEO of HART on a three year contract. He takes his position in April 2012.<ref name=HonoluluGov2012-03-01/><ref name=\"KHON2016-08-16\">{{cite news|url=https://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/1025883209|title=HART CEO Grabauskas resigns, Formby steps in as interim|date=August 18, 2016|work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Kuriowa|first=Jared|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* May 2012 - Construction workers started pouring concrete on the foundations that will hold the rail columns.<ref>Tim Sakahara, \"[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project],\" ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2012, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref>\n* December 2012 - Honolulu City Council and the Federal Transit Authority (FTA) sign agreement for the project with a budget of $5.12&nbsp;billion including $1.55&nbsp;billion provided by the Federal Government.  Full system revenue service is projected for January 31, 2020.<ref name=\"HartRecoveryPlan2017\">{{cite web|title=HART Recovery Plan|url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-20510/20170428-hart-recovery-plan.pdf|publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation|accessdate=August 31, 2017|page=19|format=PDF|date=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* September 2014 - HART canceled the initial tender for the first nine stations after the bids were higher than budget. The first trips on the railway are expected to be delayed, probably until 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |title=HART cancels bids for first 9 rail stations |newspaper=[[KITV]] |date=September 10, 2014 |accessdate=November 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129163425/http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n* November 2015 - FTA withholds payment of a $250&nbsp;million allotment until the council could show it had sufficient funding to complete the project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Year in Review 2015: Honolulu's rail transit project|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2015/12/15/year-in-review-2015-honolulus-rail-transit-project.html|website=Pacific Business Review|accessdate=September 5, 2017|date=December 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* January 2016 - Five year extension to the General Excise Tax surcharge adopted to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding.<ref name=\"HartRecoveryPlan2017\" />\n* May 2016 - HART chairwoman [[Colleen Hanabusa]] shared a confidential document detailing budget estimates as of March 1, 2016, showing that the rail project is expected to cost $6.9&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/2016/05/honolulu-rail-price-estimate-jumps-to-6-9b/ |title=Honolulu Rail Price Estimate Jumps To $6.9B |work=Civil Beat News}}</ref>\n* April 2016 - An audit of the project by the City criticized HART for using outdated financial figures and budgets, lack of documentation for \"change orders\", and warned the HART estimates of the cost overruns were  unreliable.<ref>{{cite web|title=City audit calls HART\u2019s finances, plans \u2018outdated and unreliable\u2019|url=http://khon2.com/2016/04/15/city-releases-audit-of-honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation/|website=khon2|accessdate=September 4, 2017|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Audit slams Honolulu rail agency over management, costs|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/04/15/breaking-news/audit-slams-honolulu-rail-agency-over-management-costs/|accessdate=September 4, 2017|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref>  HART officials disputed the audit's findings.\n* May 2016 - The FTA revealed that they estimate the total cost as $8.1&nbsp;billion for the {{convert|20|mi|km|abbr=on}} line.  In addition completion of the rail system would be delayed nearly five years until December 2024, versus HART's federal funding agreement stating that full line service from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Center would start in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/hawaii-news/add-5-years-and-1b-for-rail-federal-agency-says/|title=Add 5 years and $1B for rail, federal agency says|date=May 17, 2016|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|access-date=December 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* June 2016 - Report from Jacobs Engineering, the project management oversight contractor, says that under a worst-case scenario the final cost would $10.79&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"Jacobsworstcase\" />\n* August 2016 - Dan Grabauskas resigns as CEO and Executive Director of HART but will be the official CEO until October 2016. From August until October, the Department of Transportation Service Director Mike Formby served as interim CEO.<ref name=KHON2016-08-16/><ref name=\"StarAdvertiser2016-08-16\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/08/18/breaking-news/grabauskas-resigns-as-harts-chief-executive/|title=Grabauskas resigns as HART\u2019s chief executive|date=August 18, 2016|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Honor\u00e9|first=Marcel|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HNN2016-08-18\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32792174/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/|title=Outgoing rail CEO ruffled feathers, struggled with cost overruns|date=August 18, 2016|work=[[Hawaii News Now]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last1=Daysog|first1=Rick|last2=Kawano|first2=Lynn|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* October 2016 - Krishniah N. Murthy named interim CEO and Executive Director of HART and served in this position until December 2017.<ref name=\"PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2016/12/28/former-hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-starts-own.html|title=Former HART CEO Dan Grabauskas starts own consulting firm|date=December 28, 2016|work=[[American City Business Journals|Pacific Business News]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Shimogawa|first=Duane|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* April 2017 - HART sent a \"Recovery Plan\" to the FTA which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable plan. The new project cost given is $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing costs are included it will be over $10&nbsp;billion.  Opening of part of the system, from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium, is scheduled for the end of 2020 with final completion of the full route by December 2025.  The project is reported to be 36 percent complete as of March 2017.<ref name=\"HARTcommitted\" /><ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\" />\n* July 2017 - Andrew Robbins named new CEO and Executive Director of HART replacing interim CEO and Executive Director Krishniah N. Murthy in December 2017.<ref name=PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28/><ref name=\"StarAdvertiser2017-07-31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/07/31/breaking-news/hart-board-selects-new-executive-director/|title=HART board selects new executive director|date=July 31, 2017|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Honor\u00e9|first=Marcel|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* September 2017 - A new law is enacted to extend and increase taxes to raise an additional  $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project.  The GET surcharge is extended by three years to 2030 (generating about $1&nbsp;billion) and a surcharge of one percent is placed on the statewide hotel room tax for 13 years (generating $1.3&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"Sep17taxespassed\" /><ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\" />   HART submits a new recovery plan to the FTA with an estimated final cost of $9.02&nbsp;billion with savings attributed to reduced financing costs given the new taxes.<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commons category-inline|Honolulu Rail Transit}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.honolulutransit.org/}}\n\n{{Hawaii railroads}}\n{{USSubway}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{coord missing|Hawaii}}\n\n[[Category:Transportation in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rail transport articles in need of updating]]\n[[Category:Rail transportation in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Honolulu Rail Transit|*]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:2020 in rail transport]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:Under construction tram and light rail transit systems]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rapid transit system in Honolulu County, Oahu, Hawaii}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width                       = auto\n| name                            = Honolulu Rail Transit Project\n| logo                            = Hart-wordmark.svg\n| logo_width                      = 200px\n| image                           = Honolulu rail project construction in Waipahu near Fort Weaver Road 2015-07-29.jpg\n| image_width                     = 250px\n| caption                         = Project construction in [[Waipahu]], July 2015\n| type                            = [[Light metro]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bogonovich |first1=Mike |title=Automated Light Metro for Honolulu |url=https://ascelibrary.org/doi/abs/10.1061/9780784412862.014 |website=https://ascelibrary.org/ |publisher=[[American Society of Civil Engineers]] |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Sandy |title= Honolulu Negotiates With Feds Over Light Metro Line |url=https://nextcity.org/daily/entry/honolulu-light-metro-line-sydney-adding-metro-twin-cities-light-rail |accessdate=25 September 2019 |agency=Next City}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Light rail? Heavy rail? Subway? Rail transit modes fall on a continuum |url=https://ggwash.org/view/71583/light-rail-heavy-rail-subway-rail-transit-modes-fall-on-a-continuum |accessdate=25 September 2019 |agency=Greater Greater Washington |date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| system                          = \n| locale                          = [[Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n| start                           = [[Kapolei|East Kapolei]]\n| end                             = [[Ala Moana Center]]\n| stations                        = 21\n| routes                          = 1\n| status                          = Under construction\n| open                            = *Phase I: Late 2020 <br/> (East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium)\n*Phase II: 2022 <br/> (Aloha Stadium to Middle Street)\n*Phase III: Late 2025 <br/> (Middle Street to Ala Moana Center)<ref name=NaInoa-2>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22716/20190415-na-inoa-hawaiian-station-names.pdf |title=N\u0101 Inoa |date=April 15, 2019 |publisher=honolulu.gov |accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| owner                           = [https://www.honolulutransit.org/ HART]\n| operator                        = \n| character                       = Almost entirely [[Elevated rail|elevated]]\n| stock                           = [[Hitachi Rail Italy]] [[AnsaldoBreda Driverless Metro|(Driverless Metro)]]\n| linelength                      = {{convert|20|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = 2\n| gauge                           = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on|first=imp}}\n| daily_ridership                 = \n| electrification                 = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]<ref>{{cite web |title=TP -1: Core Systems Description Honolulu High -Capacity Transit Corridor Project |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14720/TP-1CSDescr.pdf |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| map_state                       = collapsed\n| map                             = {{Honolulu Rail Route}}\n| map_name                        = Route diagram\n| website                         = {{URL|www.honolulutransit.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Honolulu Rail Transit''' Project (also known as the '''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project''') is an urban rail [[rapid transit]] system under construction in [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|Honolulu County]], [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]], U.S. The mostly-elevated system features design elements from both [[Passenger rail terminology|heavy rail]] systems and [[light metro]]s,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mangieri|first1=Gina|title=Could light rail help train reach Ala Moana and beyond?|url=http://khon2.com/2016/05/19/could-light-rail-help-train-reach-ala-moana-and-beyond/|accessdate=October 28, 2016|publisher=KHON2|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref> with a [[commuter rail]]-like design incorporated into trains and suburban stations.  It will become the first large-scale publicly run metro system in the United States to feature [[platform screen doors]] and driverless trainsets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansaldohonolulurail.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5&Itemid=5|title=The Honolulu Rail Project - Based on the Copenhagen Driverless Metro System|first=|last=Administrator|website=www.ansaldohonolulurail.com}}</ref> The first phase of the project, linking [[Kapolei, Hawaii|East Kapolei]] and [[Aloha Stadium]], is scheduled to open in late 2020. Its second phase continuing the line across urban Honolulu to [[Ala Moana Center]] is due to open in December 2025.\n\nFor more than 20 \nyears, debate over the development of a rail system in Honolulu has been a major point of contention in local politics, especially leading into the 2008, [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2012|2012]], and [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2016|2016]] election cycles. Proponents of the system say it will alleviate worsening [[traffic congestion]], already among the worst in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"worsttraffic\">{{cite web|title=Honolulu ranked worst in country for traffic|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18599683/honolulu-ranked-worst-in-country-for-traffic|publisher=Hawaii News now|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>  They assert that the urban agglomeration in south Oahu is ideally suited to rail as it is constrained by mountains to a narrow strip along the coast, which will be well served by a single rail line and which has the fourth highest population density in the US. Freeway advocate [[Panos Prevedouros]] has questioned its cost effectiveness compared to alternatives<ref name=\"worsttraffic\"/> and claims that it will have marginal impact on future congestion and that new roads will therefore still be required.<ref>{{cite web|title=What Can We Do About the Rail? Nothing. Tackle Traffic Congestion!|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/01/what-can-we-do-about-the-rail-nothing-tackle-traffic-congestion/|publisher=Honolulu City Beat|accessdate=August 31, 2017|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref> The rest of the rail opponents mostly object to its cost.\n\nThe project is financed by a surcharge on local taxes as well as a $1.55&nbsp;billion grant from the [[Federal Transit Administration|Federal Transit Administration (FTA)]].  After major cost overruns, the tax surcharges were extended in 2016 by five years to raise another $1.2&nbsp;billion; however that additional funding was only sufficient for construction out to Middle Street in [[Kalihi]].  The FTA stated that its contribution is contingent to completion of the line all the way to Ala Moana Center and will not be increased.<ref name=\"CRAIGT.KOJIMA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/fta-says-no-to-stopping-rail-at-middle-street-additional-funding/ |first=Craig T. |last=Kojima |title=Feds to city: No more money for rail, no stopping at Middle Street |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> After much wrangling, the state legislature in 2017 approved $2.4&nbsp;billion in additional taxes to allow the city to complete the project according to the original plan.<ref name=\"Nanea.Kalani\">{{cite news | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/01/breaking-news/rail-bail-out-bill-goes-to-ige-after-house-approves/ |author=Nanea Kalani |title=Rail bail-out bill goes to Ige after House approves|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=September 1, 2017 |accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the final {{convert|4.3|mi|km|adj=on}} section through downtown Honolulu, which is expected to be the most difficult to build, is just starting.  The contractor selection process for this section was restarted in September 2017 and is expected to take eighteen months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rail officials start over on selecting builder for last stretch|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/07/hawaii-news/rail-officials-start-over-on-selecting-builder-for-last-stretch/?HSA=af10a21d7a7762a176d7320f3ad163e48af2b7c4|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=September 25, 2017|date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> The first major contract for that section, a $400 million contract to relocate utilities to clear the path of the line, was awarded in May 2018.<ref name=HSA-180507/>\n\nThe final cost has grown from preliminary projections of $4&nbsp;billion in 2006<ref name=\"2006cost3billion\" /> to between $9&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\">{{cite web|title=The Estimated Cost Of Honolulu Rail Just Dropped By $1 Billion|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/the-estimated-cost-of-honolulu-rail-just-dropped-by-1-billion/|accessdate=September 25, 2017|date=September 18, 2017}}</ref> and $10&nbsp;billion by 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caldwell says state lawmakers\u2019 rail-funding plan falls short|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/08/24/breaking-news/caldwell-says-state-lawmakerss-rail-funding-plan-falls-short/|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref>  Critics have called for a \"forensic audit\" to establish the cause of the increase.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hard Reality Of Honolulu Rail Costs|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/08/the-hard-reality-of-hart-costs/|website=Honolulu Civil Beat|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=City rail audit won\u2019t look for fraud?|url=http://www.grassrootinstitute.org/2017/08/city-rail-audit-wont-look-for-fraud/|website=Grassroot Institute|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rep Tupola Backs Forensic Audit for HART|url=http://www.hawaiifreepress.com/ArticlesMain/tabid/56/ID/20121/Rep-Tupola-Backs-Forensic-Audit-for-HART.aspx|website=Hawai`i Free Press|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=August 15, 2017}}</ref>  The tax increase legislation passed in 2017 also requires the State auditor carry out an audit of the project's accounts<ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\" /> and to consider alternatives for completing the system.<ref name=\"bringdowntoearth\" />\n\n==History==\nPlans for a [[mass transit]] line to connect Honolulu's urban center with outlying areas began in the 1960s,<ref name=\"Blaisdell\">{{Citation |title=Blaisdell hails Oahu mass transit project |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |pages=A12 |date=May 24, 1966}}</ref> but funding was not approved until 2005.<ref name=\"13 years\">{{citation |last=Reyes |first=B.J. |title=Council gives transit go-ahead 13 years after initial rejection |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/story2.html |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  The controversy over the rail line was the dominant issue for local politics leading into the 2008 Honolulu elections,<ref name=\"Referendum\">{{citation |last=Carlson |first=Ragnar |title=Hail to the chief |date=September 3, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |accessdate=October 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928114114/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |archivedate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> and culminated in a city charter amendment which left the final decision to a direct vote of the citizens of Oahu.<ref name=\"Charter\">{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Voters can derail $4B project |date=October 19, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601215930/http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |archivedate=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref>  Construction of the rail line was approved with 53% of voters in favor,<ref name=\"53% S\">{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |date=November 10, 2008 |title=Voters on route drive rail victory |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081110_Voters_on_route_drive_rail_victory |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> and ground broke on project construction on February 22, 2011.<ref name=\"Groundbreaking\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail ready to break ground |date=February 12, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110212_rail_ready_to_break_ground.html |accessdate=February 12, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Ground Broken\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=It's a go! |date=February 23, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=130 |issue=23 |page=A1 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110223_Its_a_go.html |accessdate=February 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Previous projects ===\nFor more than 50 years, Honolulu politicians have attempted to construct a rail transit line.  In 1966, then-mayor [[Neal S. Blaisdell]] suggested a rail line as a solution to alleviate traffic problems in Honolulu, stating, \"Taken in the mass, the automobile is a noxious mechanism whose destiny in workaday urban use is to frustrate man and make dead certain that he approaches his daily occupation unhappy and inefficient.\"<ref name=\"Blaisdell\" />\n\n[[Frank Fasi]] was elected to office in 1968, and started planning studies for a rail project,<ref>{{citation |title=Fasi To Start Rail Transit Study |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser |page=A1 |date=February 16, 1969}} (Note: At this time, the ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin'' and ''Honolulu Advertiser'' published Sunday editions jointly under the name ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser''.)</ref> named Honolulu Area Rapid Transit (HART), in 1977.<ref>{{citation |last=Tune |first=Jerry |title=A Transit Line with a HART |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=July 7, 1977 |pages=A12}}</ref>  After Fasi lost the 1980 reelection to [[Eileen Anderson]], President [[Ronald Reagan]] cut off funding for all upcoming mass transit projects, which led Anderson to cancel HART in 1981.<ref>{{Citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Reagan stops HART in its tracks |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |date=February 19, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Mayor to abandon HART, beef up buses |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |pages=A1 |date=May 5, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Glauberman |first=Stu |title=Mayor Calls HART Study to Abrupt Halt |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1 |date=May 5, 1981}}</ref>  Fasi defeated Anderson in their 1984 rematch and restarted the HART project in 1986,<ref>{{citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Transit system plan revived |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A3 |date=August 14, 1986}}</ref> but this second effort was stopped in a 1992 vote by the [[Honolulu City Council]] against the necessary tax increase.<ref name=\"13 years\" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Mariani |first=Jeanne |title=Rail line dead \u2013 for now |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1 |date=September 23, 1992}}</ref>\n\nFasi resigned in 1994 to run for [[governor]], with [[Jeremy Harris (politician)|Jeremy Harris]] winning the [[By-election|special election]] to replace him.  Harris unsuccessfully pursued a [[bus rapid transit]] project as an interim solution until he left office in 2004.<ref>{{citation |last=Dicus |first=Howard |title=Harris: 'Honolulu must build fixed rail' |newspaper=Pacific Business News |url=http://pacific.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2004/01/26/daily64.html |date=January 30, 2004 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  His successor, [[Mufi Hannemann]], began the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project (HHCTCP), the island's fourth attempt to build a mass transit system operating in a dedicated right-of-way.\n\n=== Studies ===\n[[File:City and County of Honolulu Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor HCTC 63 Survey Marker Honolulu, Oahu, HI.jpg |thumb|right|upright|Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor [[survey marker]] in the sidewalk at the corner of Kapiolani Blvd and Keeaumoku Street in Honolulu]]\nThe City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services released the first formal study related to the HHCTCP on November 1, 2006, the ''Alternatives Analysis Report''. The report compared the cost and benefits of a \"fixed guideway system\", along with three alternatives. The first expanded the existing bus system to match [[population growth]]. A second option called for a further expansion to the bus system, with improvements to existing roads. The third alternative proposed a two-lane [[Overpass|flyover]] above the [[Interstate H-1|H-1 freeway]] between [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]] and Honolulu International Airport, continuing over [[Hawaii Route 92|Nimitz Highway]], and into downtown Honolulu.  The report recommended construction of the fixed guideway, and is considered the city's official justification for building a rail line.<ref name=\"AA Report Released\">{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Council panel backs rail as mass-transit solution |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=November 3, 2006 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/11/03/news/story07.html |accessdate=October 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (November 1, 2006), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Alternatives Analysis Report'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Toc_Chapter1.pdf Chapter 1]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter2.pdf Chapter 2]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter3_to_End.pdf Chapter 3 to 7]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>\n\nA second planning document, the ''Draft Environmental Impact Statement'' (DEIS), studied possible natural and social impacts of the construction and operation of the HHCTCP. The DEIS was completed and cleared for public release by the [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA) on October 29, 2008. After minor changes were made to comply with state law, the document was distributed via the city's official project website four days later.  The DEIS indicated that impacts of the rail project would include land acquisition from private owners on the route, displacement of residents and businesses, aesthetic concerns related to the elevated guideway, and noise from passing trains.<ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/executive%20summary%20drafteis.pdf Draft Environmental Impact Statement Executive Summary]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (PDF), retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>\n\nThe city was criticized for timing the release only two days before the 2008 general election. City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]], running as a mayoral candidate against [[incumbent]] Hannemann, suggested that the city deliberately withheld key information to early voters who had already cast their ballots for the mayoral candidates, and a city charter amendment related to the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City releases portion of rail report |date=October 31, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081031_City_releases_portion_of_rail_report |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Shikina |first=Robert |title=Kobayashi rails against city for timing of report |date=November 3, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081103_kobayashi_rails_against_city_for_timing_of_report |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>  The anti-rail advocacy group Stop Rail Now criticized the report for not further discussing bus rapid transit and toll lanes, options studied earlier by the city in its Alternatives Analysis.<ref>{{citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |last2=Roig |first2=Suzanne |title=Hawaii rail transit cost now at least $4.34B |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |date=November 3, 2008 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/03/ln/hawaii811030342.html |accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (2008-11), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Draft Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/front.pdf Cover to Contents]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf Chapter 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143036/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf Chapter 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103144257/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%203.pdf Chapter 3]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 1)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140420/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-end.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 2)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%205.pdf Chapter 5]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf Chapters 6\u20138] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143502/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf References to Index] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414182019/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf |date=April 14, 2010 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf Appendix A (Conceptual Alignment Plans and Profiles)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_b_1108.pdf Appendix B (Conceptual Right-of-Way Plans)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf Appendix C (Construction Approach)] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5lwKtq3qH?url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf |date=December 11, 2009 }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_d_1108.pdf Appendix D (Record of Agency Correspondence and Coordination)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf Appendix E (Record of Public and Stakeholder Correspondence and Coordination)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103142549/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011 }}, retrieved on January 5, 2009</ref>\n\nThe third and final official planning document, the ''Final Environmental Impact Statement'' (FEIS), was approved and cleared for public release by the FTA on June 14, 2010. The FEIS addresses and incorporates public comments received regarding the DEIS.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Final study for rail line gets feds' OK |date=June 15, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100615_Final_study_for_rail_line_gets_feds_OK.html |accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref>  The FTA subsequently declared the environmental review process complete in a record of decision issued on January 18, 2011.<ref name=\"FTA RoD\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail gets OK to break ground |date=January 19, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110119_Rail_gets_OK_to_break_ground.html |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Impact on Honolulu mayoral elections ===\nThe importance of the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project in the 2008 mayoral election led one observer to describe the vote as a \"referendum on rail transit\".<ref name=\"Referendum\" />  Two challengers emerged as rivals to incumbent [[Mufi Hannemann]]: City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]] and [[University of Hawaii]] professor [[Panos D. Prevedouros]]. Kobayashi supported a \"rubber-tired\" mass transit system, as opposed to the conventional steel-wheel-on-steel-rail system chosen by the Hannemann administration. Prevedouros, on the other hand, opposed any type of mass transit project, favoring construction of a reversible tollway over the H-1, similar to the Managed Lane option which the Alternatives Analysis studied and rejected as unworkable, and reworking existing road systems to ease congestion.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Mayoral debate turns raucous |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 10, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/10/news/story01.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  No candidate won a majority of votes in the September 20 non-partisan primary, forcing a runoff between Hannemann and Kobayashi;<ref>{{citation |last=Borreca |first=Richard |last2=Au |first2=Laurie |title=Hannemann and Kobayashi reset sights for Nov. 4 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 21, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/21/news/story01.html |accessdate=October 20, 2008}}</ref> Hannemann successfully retained his post with 58% of the vote in the November 4 general election.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Hannemann win re-election with 58% |date=November 5, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081105_Hannemann_wins_re-election_with_58 |accessdate=November 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2008, the Stop Rail Now advocacy group announced their intent to file a petition with the city to place a question on the 2008 [[ballot]] to create an ordinance that read: \"Honolulu mass transit shall not include trains or rail\".<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Rail critics utilize power of pen |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/04/22/news/story01.html |date=April 22, 2008 |accessdate=October 20, 2008}}</ref>  Stop Rail Now attempted to submit the petition with 49,041 signatures to City Clerk Denise De Costa on August 5, but was initially denied after De Costa claimed the city charter did not allow the petition to be submitted less than 180 days before a general election, as the wording of the petition called for a special election.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Lawsuit looms over validity of anti-rail petition |date=August 5, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/05/news/story03.html |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/rc030404.pdf Section 3-404] (PDF), [http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ Revised Charter of Honolulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907150738/http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ |date=September 7, 2008 }}, retrieved on February 25, 2009</ref>  Stop Rail Now filed a lawsuit to force the city to accept the petition, and the courts ruled in Stop Rail Now's favor on August 14.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City clerk rushing to certify anti-rail effort |date=August 20, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/20/news/story07.html |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>  Stop Rail Now's petition drive ultimately failed on September 4 when De Costa deemed only 35,056 of the signatures valid, well short of the 44,525 required.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/04/news/story03.html |title=Anti-rail group's effort denied by courts, clerk |date=September 4, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the possibility that Stop Rail Now's petition would fail, the City Council had however voted on August 21 to place a proposed amendment to the city charter on the ballot, asking voters to decide the fate of the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |date=August 21, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |accessdate=November 12, 2008}}</ref> Mayor Hannemann signed the proposal the following day.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |date=August 22, 2008 |title=Mayor vows to put transit on ballot |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/22/news/story04.html |accessdate=November 12, 2008}}</ref> The City Council's proposed amendment was not intended to have a direct legal effect on the city's ability to continue the project, but was meant as a means for Oahu residents to express their opinions on its construction.<ref name=\"Charter\" />  The charter amendment was approved with 53% of votes cast in favor of rail and 47% against. Majorities of voters in Leeward and Central Oahu, the areas that will be served by the project, voted in favor of the amendment, while the majority of those living outside the project's scope in Windward Oahu and [[East Honolulu, Hawaii|East Honolulu]] voted against it.<ref name=\"53% S\" /> In mid-2010, Hannemann resigned as major to run for governor and Kirk Caldwell assumed the position of interim mayor.<ref name=\"Dayton2019-01-11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/01/11/hawaii-news/premature-contracts-increased-rail-cost-by-354m/?HSA=eb247f207a1158b53d1b48d5858ca2997cc4061a|title=Premature contracts increased rail cost by $354M|date=January 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Dayton|first=Kevin|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Honolulu mayoral election, 2016|2016 Honolulu mayoral elections]] the main three candidates again took opposing views on rail. Honolulu City Council Member [[Charles Djou]], former mayor [[Peter Carlisle]], and incumbent [[Kirk Caldwell]] all ran for mayor with the stated goal of finishing rail. However, Republican Djou ran on drastically cutting spending on rail by cutting funding on buying cars on the rail before its completion, and hiring mainland consultants.<ref>Charles Djou, \"Rail\" (http://djou.com/issues/rail/)</ref> Kirk Caldwell also stated that spending on rail should be cut, but instead by shortening the rail to end at Middle Street.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32242522/caldwell-wants-to-shorten-rail-to-15-miles-ending-route-at-middle-street|title=Mayor wants to shorten rail route, ending at Middle Street|last=Mendoza|first=Jim|date=June 16, 2016|work=Hawaii News Now|access-date=March 11, 2017|last2=Lincoln|first2=Mileka|language=en|last3=Davis|first3=Chelsea}}</ref> Carlisle was the only candidate in full support of funding the rail system and stated that rail has gone too far to be stopped.<ref>Grace Lee, \"Mayoral candidate Peter Carlisle says rail project cannot be stopped\" (http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31997123/mayoral-candidate-peter-carl-isle-says-rail-project-cannot-be-stopped)</ref> Kirk Caldwell won the election, and promptly went on to adopt Carlisle's position that rail should be completed.\n\n===Delays and cost overruns===\nConstruction on the HHCTCP rail line was originally scheduled to begin in December 2009 but did not occur on that date owing to delays in the project review process and delays in obtaining federal approval of the environmental impact statement.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Honolulu rail behind schedule, with construction start unclear |date=January 3, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/03/ln/hawaii1030376.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Honolulu Mayor Peter Carlisle at Rail Groundbreaking 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|left|Honolulu mayor [[Peter Carlisle]] speaking at the project's groundbreaking ceremony]]\nIn January 2010, Republican Governor [[Linda Lingle]] publicly recommended that the city alter plans for the rail line after news reports on FTA documents where the federal agency raised issues over declining tax revenues in connection with a [[Late-2000s recession|global economic recession]],<ref>{{citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |last2=Pang |first2=Gordon Y.K. |title=Honolulu's rail costs put state at financial risk, governor says |date=January 9, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/09/ln/hawaii1090342.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> and commissioned a study by the state to review the project's finances in March.<ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Time short for Lingle's call on rail |date=August 26, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100826_Time_short_for_Lingles_call_on_rail.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  The state financial study, publicly released on December 2, 2010, indicated that the project would likely experience a $1.7&nbsp;billion overrun above the $5.3&nbsp;billion projected cost, and that collections from the General Excise Tax would be 30% below forecasts.  Then Mayor Peter Carlisle (Democrat) dismissed the study as \"damaged goods,\" and \"a pre-determined anti-rail rant.\"  He also pointed to several conclusions as \"erroneous\" and \"inaccurate\" before concluding that \"spending a third of a million dollars for this shoddy, biased analysis is an appalling waste of our tax dollars.\"<ref name=\"LingleReport2010\">{{cite web|title=Carlisle dismisses Lingle's rail report|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/2010/12/carlisle-honolulus-rail-project.html|website=Pacific Business News|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=December 3, 2010}}</ref> Lingle's Democratic successor, [[Neil Abercrombie]], publicly stated that the financial analysis would not affect his decision to approve or disapprove of the project, saying that the state's responsibility is limited to the environmental review process, and that decisions regarding the project's finances belong to the city and the FTA.<ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Abercrombie to weigh rail EIS |date=November 5, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20101105_Abercrombie_to_weigh_rail_EIS.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  Governor Abercrombie subsequently approved the project's final environmental impact statement on December 16, 2010.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Governor signs off on review of rail |date=December 17, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20101217_Governor_signs_off_on_review_of_rail.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  The Honolulu City Council held a hearing on January 12, 2011 about the state's financial review, but the hearing was not attended by any state officials, who had been invited to testify.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=State skips hearing on rail finance studies |date=January 13, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20110113_State_skips_hearing_on_rail_finance_studies.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, the FTA issued a \"record of decision\", indicating that the HHCTCP had met the requirements of its environmental review and that the city was allowed to begin construction work on the project.<ref name=\"FTA RoD\" />  The record of decision allowed the city to begin negotiating with owners of land that will be purchased for the project, to begin relocating utility lines to make way for construction of the line and stations, and to purchase [[rolling stock]] for the rail line.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=If they build it, will developers come? |date=February 20, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110220_If_they_build_it_will_developers_come.html |accessdate=February 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=LaFrance |first=Adrienne |title=Rail Groundbreaking: Phony or For Real? |date=February 21, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/02/21/9126-rail-groundbreaking-phony-or-for-real/ |accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>  A ground-breaking ceremony was held on February 22, 2011 in Kapolei, at the site of the future East Kapolei station along Kualakai Parkway.<ref name=\"Groundbreaking\" /><ref name=\"Ground Broken\" />\n\nIn March 2012, [[Daniel Grabauskas|Dan Grabauskas]] was hired on a three year contract as CEO and Executive Director of HART.<ref name=\"HonoluluGov2012-03-01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.honolulu.gov/csd-news-2012/5840-03-01-12-daniel-grabauskas-named-hart-executive-director.html|title=Danial Grabauskas Named HART Executive Director|date=March 1, 2012|work=City and County of Honolulu: Department of Customer Services|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> In 2014 HART CEO Dan Grabauskas blamed lawsuits, launched in 2011, for some of the cost overruns after bids to construct the first nine stations exceeded the budget by $100&nbsp;million.  His claims were disputed by the plaintiffs in one of the cases who said HART could have put the stations out to tender and that HART had deliberately delayed the legal proceedings so a judgement would only be delivered after a significant proportion of the line had been completed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu rail CEO blames cost overruns on legal challenges, but critics say it is incompetence|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-ceo-blames-cost-overruns-on-legal-challenges-but-critics-say-it-is-incompetence|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=August 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Burial issues===\nLike most major infrastructure work in Hawaii, construction of the rail line is likely to uncover historic human remains, notably in its downtown Honolulu section. The Oahu Island Burial Council (part of the State Historic Preservation Division, within the State of Hawaii Department of Land and Natural Resources) refused to sign a programmatic agreement on October 21, 2009, over concerns about likely  burial sites located along the line's proposed route over Halekauwila Street in [[Kakaako|Kaka{{okina}}ako]].  Three construction projects in the area since 2002 have each encountered unforeseen human remains that led to delays, and [[archaeologist]] Thomas Dye stated, \"The council is absolutely right that you should expect to find burials on Halekauwila Street\".<ref name=\"2009-10 Burials\">{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Burial council won't sign rail pact |date=October 20, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/20/ln/hawaii910200360.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Burial Council's core contention is the city's decision to conduct an archaeological survey of the rail line's route in phases, meaning construction on a majority of the line will be complete by the time the survey in the Kaka{{okina}}ako area is performed, which in turn increases the likelihood that any remains discovered will be moved instead of being allowed to remain ''in situ''.<ref>{{citation |last=Conrow |first=Joan |title=grave matters |date=May 26, 2010 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |accessdate=January 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119140503/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |archivedate=November 19, 2011}}</ref> In response to the Burial Council's concerns, the city agreed to begin conducting an archaeological survey of the area in 2010, two years earlier than originally planned.<ref name=\"2009-10 Burials\" /> The state Department of Land and Natural Resources later signed the city's programmatic agreement on January 15, 2011, over the continuing concerns of the Burial Council.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=City plan accounts for problematic burial sites |date=January 16, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110116_City_plan_accounts_for_problematic_burial_sites.html |accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe city's decision to conduct the archaeological survey in phases subsequently led to a lawsuit filed on February 1, 2011, by the [[Native Hawaiian Legal Corporation]] on behalf of cultural practitioner Paulette Kaleikini. The suit, which named both the city and the State of Hawaii as defendants, contended  that state law requires the full length of the rail line to have an archaeological survey conducted before any construction takes place, and seeks to void the environmental impact statement and all construction permits issued for the project.<ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Lawsuit claims rail endangers burial sites |date=February 1, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=129 |issue=364 |page=B1 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110202_Lawsuit_claims_rail_endangers_burial_sites.html |accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Kaleikini's lawyers filed on February 18 a request for an injunction to stop work on the project until the case is resolved.<ref name=\"Ground Broken\" />  The suit was initially dismissed on March 23, 2011, after Circuit Court Judge Gary Chang ruled that state and federal laws allow the archaeological surveys to be conducted in phases.<ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Judge Rejects Suit Challenging Rail Survey |date=March 24, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110324__Judge_rejects_suit_challenging_rail_survey.html |accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref> Kaleikini's lawyers subsequently appealed to the Hawaii Supreme Court, which heard oral arguments in the case on May 24, 2012.<ref>{{citation |last=Hervey |first=Tiffany |title=Buried Truth |date=June 27, 2012 |newspaper=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |accessdate=July 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025223421/http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |archivedate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>  The court ruled on August 24, 2012, that it agreed with plaintiff Kaleikini that the archaeological survey needed to be completed before construction could take place, and that the State Historic Preservation Division did not comply with state law when it approved the project. The case has now been [[Remand (court procedure)|remand]]ed to Circuit Court.<ref>{{citation |last=Grube |first=Nick |title=Rail Derailed? Hawaii Supreme Court Rules Against Honolulu |date=August 24, 2012 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2012/08/24/16937-rail-derailed-hawaii-supreme-court-rules-against-honolulu/ |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>  On December 27, 2012, the [[United States District Court for the District of Hawaii]] granted the plaintiffs' injunction, and ordered that all construction-related activities in segment 4 of the archaeological survey be halted until compliance with the Hawaii Supreme Court decision made earlier this year is met.  This ruling does not affect construction activities in the first three segments, nor does it affect construction planning, design, or engineering in segment 4, which is the final segment to be built. The Phase 4 area encompasses the downtown area and its immediate environs, including [[Chinatown, Honolulu|Chinatown]], Mother Waldron Park, and Beretania Street. Judge Tashima, the only sitting judge on the case, ruled on condition of the injunction that the city is required to file periodic status updates on their compliance with the judgment. The injunction will then terminate 30 days after defendants file a notice of final compliance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schwind |first=Paul |title=Honolulu Rail Remedy \u2013 Phasers On Minimal |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-remedy-phasers-on-minimal/123 |work=Web |publisher=Hawaii Reporter |accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Social impact ===\nThe development of this project has been a major point of contention among environmental, indigenous, and residential interest groups, as the [[United States Department of Transportation]]  is accountable for nationwide compliance with Title VI of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>Lowe, Kate. March 2014. \u201cBypassing Equity? Transit Investment and Regional Transportation Planning.\u201d Journal of Planning Education and Research. vol. 34, no. 1. 30-44. </ref> Specifically, residents of the [[North Shore (Oahu)|North Shore]], [[ Wai\u2018anae Coast]], and Central and East regions of Oahu, home to mostly middle and lower-class communities{{cn|date=January 2020}}, together with those of upper class Hawaii Kai and Windward Oahu, pay a higher excise tax without ultimately reaping the benefits of the Rail Transit project. Indigenous Hawaiians constitute large percentages of the communities scattered along the southwest coast of the island, where residents generally exist under the national poverty line, but the project may possibly serve wealthier, \u201clocal\u201d Hawaiian residents while bypassing the poorer [[Native Hawaiians|indigenous Hawaiian community]].<ref>Trask, Haunani-Kay. From a Native Daughter: Colonialism and Sovereignty in Hawai\u2019i. Common Courage Press, Monroe, ME. 1993. </ref> Numerous studies have identified various benefits, including increased home values and increased median household income, that fall upon residences located near a rail transit station; public transit implementation thus constitutes a measure of public and private investment in a community.<ref>Karner, Alex and Richard A. Marcantonio. April 2018. \u201cAchieving Transportation Equity: Meaningful Public Involvement to Meet the Needs of Underserved Communities.\u201d American Society for Public Administration, Section on Transportation Policy and Administration. Vol. 23, no. 2. 105-126. </ref>\n\n==Financing==\n=== Initial General Excise Tax (GET) surcharge===\n[[File:Mufi Hannemann.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Former Honolulu mayor [[Mufi Hannemann]]]]\n\nAfter winning the 2004 election, Hannemann announced that construction of a rail line was an administration priority.<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Director prioritizes rail transit |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=January 1, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/01/01/news/index5.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>  The following May and upon prompting by the city, the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] passed a bill (Act 247) to allow counties a one-half percent increase in the Hawaii General Excise Tax (GET), from 4% to 4.5%, to fund transportation projects. According to the bill, increased revenue would be delivered to counties implementing the raised tax to fund general public transportation infrastructure throughout Hawaii, and to pay for mass transit in the case of the City and County of Honolulu.<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=City measure touts rail tax |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=May 5, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/05/05/news/index5.html |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\">{{citation|author=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation |date=July 29, 2005 |url=http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |title=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation Announcement 2005-11 |accessdate=June 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lwKtdvx1?url=http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |archivedate=December 11, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Money collected from the initial 4% GET would remain state revenue.\n\nRepublican governor [[Linda Lingle]] initially threatened to [[veto]] the bill, believing that money destined for county governments should be collected by the individual counties.<ref name=\"GET Success SB\">{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Late deal avoids transit veto |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/07/12/news/index1.html |date=July 12, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hawaii Reporter 1\">{{citation |last=Zimmerman |first=Malia |title=Surrounded By Democrats at the Capitol, Hawaii's Republican Governor Rescinds Decision to Veto Tax Increase Measure |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |newspaper=Hawaii Reporter |date=July 12, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809153228/http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |archivedate=August 9, 2007}}</ref> After compromising with legislative leaders and Mayor Hannemann, however, she allowed the bill to become law. On July 12, 2005, the bill was enacted as Act 247 of the Session Laws of Hawaii 2005, without the Governor's signature.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" /><ref name=\"GET Success SB\" /><ref name=\"Hawaii Reporter 1\" /><ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |last2=Dingeman |first2=Robbie |title=Deal puts transit tax back on track |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |date=July 12, 2005 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jul/12/ln/507120343.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>  A month later, the [[Honolulu City Council]] authorized the one-half percent GET increase,<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Transit project to raise taxes |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/index1.html |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref> and Hannemann signed the measure into law on August 24.<ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Mayor signs tax, calls for multi-faceted traffic solutions |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/24/news/index7.html |date=August 24, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref> Act 247 required Honolulu to use the funds only for the construction and operation of a mass transit system, and barred its use for public roads and other existing transit systems, such as [[TheBus (Honolulu)|TheBus]]. Since no other county authorized the excise tax increase before the deadline of December 31, 2005, the Hawaii GET remains at 4% for Hawaii's three other counties.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" /><ref>{{citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Excise tax increase begins tomorrow |date=December 31, 2006 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/12/31/news/story05.html |accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref> The increase went into effect on January 1, 2007, and was due to expire on December 31, 2022.<ref name=\"DoTax 2005-11\" />\n\nThe Legislature considered a bill in the 2009 legislative session that would have redirected income from the half-percent increase back to the state to offset a $1.8&nbsp;billion projected shortfall in the following three fiscal years.<ref name=\"2009 GET\">{{citation |last=Wu |first=Nina |title=Legislature battles to avert $1.8B deficit |date=January 22, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090122_Legislature_battles_to_avert_18B_deficit |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last1=DePledge |first1=Derrick |last2=Boylan |first2=Peter |title=Governor emphasizes Hawaii's deficit woes as Legislature opens |date=June 21, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/22/ln/hawaii901220369.html |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Hawaii State Legislature |title=2009 Regular Session, Senate Bill 1626 Status |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |accessdate=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615111105/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |archivedate=June 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Hawaii State Legislature |title=Senate Bill 1626 Senate Draft 1, Relating to Taxation |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |accessdate=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610135634/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |archivedate=June 10, 2011 }}</ref>  The bill was opposed by Mayor Hannemann and other city leaders who believed that redirecting the money would jeopardize federal funding for the project,<ref>{{citation |last=Nakaso |first=Dan |title=Stimulus could revive Honolulu, mayor says |date=January 24, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/24/ln/hawaii901240322.html |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref> and was eventually dropped after U.S. Senator [[Daniel Inouye]] indicated to the Legislature that he shared the city's concerns.<ref>{{citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Legislature keeping its tax-raising options open |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Mar/11/ln/hawaii903110398.html |date=March 11, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Borreca |first=Richard |title=Lawmakers fear revenue slump |date=March 11, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090311_Lawmakers_fear_revenue_slump |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== GET surchange extensions and \"Hotel Tax\" surcharge===\nIn January 2016 the Council extended the GET for another five years to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding to cover a budget blowout.  The Council also required that the money raised by the extension go into a contingency fund and to pay for disability access to the system.  HART was required to provide quarterly financial reports to the Council.<ref>{{cite web|title=City Council approves tax surcharge extension for Honolulu rail project|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31076942/rail-tax-extension-approved|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=September 2, 2017|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2017 the Legislature, after meeting for a week in a special session on rail financing, approved further taxes to raise $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project.  The taxes include a further three-year extension to the 0.5 percent General Excise Tax surcharge, which will now expire in 2030, and a thirteen-year, 1.0 percent surcharge on the existing 9.25 percent statewide Transient Accommodation Tax (TAT) which is charged to tourists.   Efforts to pass a funding bill in May 2017 had failed and the impetus for the special session was a FTA deadline of September 15 for a funding plan to cover the shortfall.<ref name=\"Sep17taxespassed\">{{cite web|title=$2.4 Billion Rescue Bill For Honolulu Rail Wins Final Approval|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/2-4-rescue-bill-for-honolulu-rail-wins-final-approval/|website=Honolulu City Beat|accessdate=September 2, 2017|date=September 2, 2017}}</ref>  The bill also grants the state government oversight over the project including the appointment of two non-voting representatives on the HART board and calls for an audit of HART by the state auditor.  It was signed into law by the governor on September 5.<ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\">{{cite news|title=Honolulu rail bailout becomes law with Ige\u2019s signature |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/05/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-bailout-becomes-law-with-iges-signature/ |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser |accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Federal Transit Administration's request for recovery plan===\nIn mid 2016 the FTA requested that HART develop a \"recovery plan\" by August 7, 2016.  Also in June a separate report by Jacobs Engineering, the project management contractor, said under a worst-case scenario the final cost would $10.79&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"Jacobsworstcase\">{{cite web|title=New 'worst-case scenario' report reveals full 20-mile rail route could cost $10.79B|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32297303/new-worst-case-scenario-report-reveals-full-20-mile-rail-route-could-cost-1079b|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 group called \"Salvage the Rail\" published a plan, based on Option 2A from six alternatives proposed by the FTA to HART in 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2016/06/a-rail-system-option-that-offers-the-best-fit-for-honolulu/ |title=A Rail System Option That Offers The Best Fit For Honolulu |publisher=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]] |date=June 29, 2016 |author=Ray Tsuchiyama}}</ref> that would terminate the elevated section at Middle Street and run at street level to the terminus along a route one block inland from the HART plan.  The system would need to be reconfigured to use new driver-operated low floor vehicles, lowering the platforms on the stations already constructed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salvage the Rail: Group renews call to bring rail to street level|url=http://www.kitv.com/story/34272479/salvage-the-rail-group-renews-call-to-bring-rail-to-street-level|website=Island News KITV4|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=February 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MODIFYING HONOULU AREA RAPID TRANSIT (HART) FOR STREET LEVEL OPERATION IN DOWNTOWN HONOLULU (January 2017)|url=http://www.salvagetherail.org/uploads/9/7/4/0/97405512/report_modifying_hart_for_street_level_operation_in_downtown_honolulu_january_2017_rev_feb_1.pdf|website=Salvage The Rail|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>  Proponents say it would save $3&nbsp;billion and four years of construction, as well as avoid disturbing burial sites under the downtown area.\n\nAfter a lodgement extension was granted by the FTA, HART submitted its recovery plan in April 2017 which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable option.  An alternative \"Plan B\" to build only 14 stations within the already funded $6.5&nbsp;billion budget, was ruled out because of lower ridership, legal risks, insufficient contingency and other reasons.  The new project cost was $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing charges are included it could be over $10&nbsp;billion.  An updated schedule for opening said the section from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium will open at the end of 2020 and operation of the full route by December 2025.<ref name=\"HARTcommitted\">{{cite news|title=HART committed to rail project\u2019s original route in recovery plan submitted to FTA|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2017/05/01/hart-committed-to-rail-project-s-original-route-in.html|accessdate=August 15, 2017|publisher=Pacific Business News|date=May 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\">{{cite web|title=HART Recovery Plan|url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan|publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation|accessdate=August 15, 2017|format=PDF|date=April 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831140644/http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 HART submitted an updated recovery plan to the FTA with a new estimate price of $9.02&nbsp;billion. The plan still includes $8.165&nbsp;billion in construction costs, but has reduced financing costs of $858&nbsp;million following state legislation granting both prolonged and new taxes to fund the project.<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\" />  The State Auditor has been tasked to consider alternatives for completing the system, as part of its audit of HART.<ref name=\"bringdowntoearth\">{{cite web|title=Bring Honolulu Rail Down To Earth|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/bring-honolulu-rail-down-to-earth/|website=Honolulu Civic Beat|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=September 27, 2017}}</ref> As of January 2018 the FTA has not formally accepted the new recovery plan but has asked HART for more details including how it came up with its tax-revenue forecasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu Rail Recovery Plan Remains A Work In Progress|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2018/01/honolulu-rail-recovery-plan-remains-a-work-in-progress/|publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat|accessdate=January 11, 2018|date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the FTA served HART with two subpoenas.  The first asked the agency to send investigators documents relating to its real estate acquisition program.  HART said some of the documents show it overspent on relocating residents and businesses along the rail route, which may have cost up to $4 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Feds serve Honolulu's rail agency with 2nd subpoena |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/government-issues/news/733170/feds-serve-honolulu-s-rail-agency-with-2nd-subpoena?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M}}</ref> The second sought the minutes from all board of directors meetings from 2011 through 2018, including the board-members\u2019 private discussions in executive sessions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Honolulu rail project subpoenaed by feds for third time |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/news/733197/honolulu-rail-project-subpoenaed-by-feds-for-third-time?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the FTA accepted the recovery plan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/05/breaking-news/fta-approves-honolulu-rail-recovery-plan/ |title=FTA approves Honolulu rail recovery plan |author=Dayton, Kevin |date=September 5, 2019 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Honolulu Rail Project Groundbreaking Dignitaries 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|left|City and state politicians at the project's groundbreaking ceremony]]\n\nThe project constructs an almost entirely elevated rapid transit line from the eastern edge of [[Kapolei]], near the [[University of Hawaii-West Oahu]] campus, to [[Ala Moana Center]] (East of Honolulu downtown).  The line passes through communities along southern Oahu, via [[Honolulu International Airport]] and [[downtown Honolulu]].  It will have twenty-one stations and run from [[Kapolei]] to Honolulu, passing through [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]], [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]], [[Waimalu, Hawaii|Waimalu]], [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], and [[Halawa, Hawaii|Halawa]]. Originally, the line was to fork near [[Aloha Stadium]] into two routes, one passing further south via [[Honolulu International Airport]], and the other through Salt Lake, before reuniting at Middle Street in [[Kalihi]]. The city council initially decided to build the Salt Lake route before the airport route, as a result of horse-trading with City Councilmember [[Romy Cachola]], whose constituents included Salt Lake residents and whose vote was needed to pass the decision.<ref>{{citation |last=Consillio |first=Kristen |title=Rail route changes trigger harsh words |date=November 17, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081117_rail_route_changes_trigger_harsh_words |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Rail Route to Go Via Salt Lake |date=February 22, 2007 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/02/22/news/story01.html |accessdate=January 18, 2008}}</ref> After the city charter amendment on rail transit passed, the City Council reconsidered the decision, and decided to re-route the rail line to pass by [[Pearl Harbor]] and the airport, without a Salt Lake alignment.<ref>{{citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=New rail route OK'd |date=January 29, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090129_New_rail_route_OKd |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"2009routechange\">{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Council changes transit route to serve airport |date=January 29, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/29/ln/hawaii901290352.html |accessdate=January 29, 2002}}</ref> The airport route is 4% more expensive, but is expected to have significantly higher ridership since it will ferry workers to both the [[Honolulu International Airport|airport]] and the [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam|Pearl Harbor military base]]. The only at-grade trackage will be a {{convert|0.6|mi|adj=on}} section near [[Leeward Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sneider |first1=Julie |title=Honolulu transit leaders eye late 2020 start to city's first passenger-rail system |url=https://www.progressiverailroading.com/passenger_rail/article/Honolulu-transit-leaders-eye-late-2020-start-to-citys-first-passenger-rail-system--58258 |accessdate=17 December 2019 |agency=Progressive Railroading |date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|11}}, the western portion of the line ({{stn|East Kapolei}} \u2013 {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}) is scheduled to open in late 2020, and the full line ({{stn|East Kapolei}} \u2013 {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}) is scheduled to open in late 2025.<ref name=RailFAQ>{{cite web |author=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=Rail Facts |url=http://honolulutransit.org/inform/rail-facts?catid=0 |accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref> The project is divided into four segments or sections, with overlapping construction periods and revenue service dates.<ref name=Sections/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:100%;\"\n|+HART Route sections and schedule\n|-\n| colspan=7 | [[File:Honolulu Rail Transit map with extensions.svg|800px]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Section name<ref name=Sections/> !! Length !! colspan=2 | Terminii !! Opening !! Ref.\n|-\n! style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 1 !! style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;\" | ''West Oahu-Farrington''\n| {{convert|6.9|mi}}\n| {{stn|East Kapolei}} || {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-116 |title=West Oahu-Farrington Highway Guideway Contract for Design-Build Construction Contract No. SC-DTS-1000137 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-112 |title=West Oahu Station Group -FD Contract No. SC-HRT-1200116 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-827 |title=West Oahu Stations Group Construction Contract |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-122 |title=Farrington Hwy Station Group Design Contract No. SC-HRT-11H0013 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-526 |title=Farrington Highway Station Group Construction Contract |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-476 |title=Farrington Highway Station Group II |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 2 !! style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;\" | ''Kamehameha Highway''\n| {{convert|3.9|mi}}\n| {{stn|Pearl Highlands}} || {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-123 |title=Kamehemeha ''[sic]'' Highway Guideway Design Build Contract No. CT-HRT-11H00195 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-124 |title=Kamehameha Highway Station Group Design Consultant Contract No. CT-HRT-130022 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-974 |title=Kamehameha Highway Stations Group Construction Contract No. CT-HRT-1600152 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 3 !! style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;\" | ''Airport''\n| {{convert|5.1|mi}} \n| {{stn|Aloha Stadium}} || {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-117 |title=Airport Segment Guideway and Utilities Contract No. SC-HRT-1200038 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-106 |title=Airport Station Group Design Consultant Contract No. SC-HRT-1200038 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-1007 |title=Airport Guideway and Stations Design-Build Contract No. CT-HRT-1600385 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;font-size:150%;\" | 4 !! ! style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;\" | ''City Center''\n| {{convert|4.1|mi}} \n| {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}} || {{stn|Ala Moana Center}} \n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-121 |title=City Center Section Utilities & Guideway Contract No. SC-HRT-1200149 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=7 | <br/>The following extension sections are not funded and have no scheduled completion date:<br/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''West Kapolei extension''\n|  \n| {{stn|West Kapolei}} || {{stn|East Kapolei}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''UH M\u0101noa extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}<br/>or {{stn|Iwilei}} || {{stn|University of Hawaii at Manoa}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/><ref>{{cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16821/20130930-final-supplemental-eis-4f.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project: Final Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation and Amended Record of Decision |date=September 2013 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''Waik\u012bk\u012b extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Ala Moana Center}} || {{stn|Lili\u02bbuokalani Avenue}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#ac2e18;color:#fff;\" | ''Salt Lake extension''\n| \n| {{stn|Aloha Stadium}} || {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}} \n| not funded\n| <ref name=HART-extensions/>\n|}\n\nThe long term plan includes four extensions: two extensions east, from [[Ala Moana Center|Ala Moana Shopping Center]] to the [[University of Hawaii-Manoa]] campus and to [[Waikiki]], one extension west from East [[Kapolei]] to [[Kalaeloa]], and the link through [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]] which was dropped from the initial plans.<ref name=\"Map\">City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%201.pdf Rail Transit Map (Part 1: Kapolei-Ewa)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%202.pdf (Part 2: Waipahu-Aiea)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%203.pdf (Part 3: Stadium-Kalihi)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%204.pdf (Part 4: Kalihi-UH-Manoa/Waikiki)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, retrieved January 5, 2009</ref><ref name=\"RG 2009-10\">{{cite journal |title=First contract awarded for Honolulu light rail |date=October 26, 2009 |journal=[[Railway Gazette International]] |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/first-contract-awarded-for-honolulu-light-rail.html |accessdate=October 26, 2009}}</ref> In 2010 it was estimated the extensions could be completed after the initial four-section project, possibly as early as 2030.<ref name=HART-extensions>{{cite report |chapterurl=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16805/20110701-final-eis-chapter-02.pdf#page=48 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-594 |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project: Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |date=June 2010 |publisher=Department of Transportation Services, City and county of Honolulu |chapter=2: Alternatives Considered |page=2-48 |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> None of these extensions is currently funded, but in November 2017 the rail authority took a first step towards preserving a corridor for the extension between Ala Moana Center and the University of Hawaii at Manoa.<ref name=\"ManoaExtension\">{{cite newspaper |newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/11/18/hawaii-news/rail-authority-looks-to-preserve-corridor-for-uh-manoa-option/ |url-access=subscription |accessdate=December 12, 2017 |title=Rail authority looks to preserve corridor for UH Manoa option |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |date=November 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen complete, the trains will carry more than 6,000 people per hour,<ref name=\"qaa\">{{cite web |author=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/honolulu%20rail%20transit%20brochure.pdf |title=Q&A: Honolulu Rail Transit |accessdate=January 5, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117201255/http://www.honolulutransit.org/pdfs/QA_100808.pdf |archivedate=January 17, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><!--The previous statement was that 20 trains would run per hour, an average 3 minute headway. The cited source states that each train can carry more than 300 passengers each, and more than 6,000 passengers will be carried per hour, which works out to 20 trains per hour via original research.--> from 4&nbsp;am to midnight.<ref name=RailFAQ/> It is estimated the trains will serve 119,600 daily riders.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/94176bf9f55a41d2a272684dede9e8e0/Hawaii-scrambles-to-keep-train-project-from-going-off-rails |title=Hawaii scrambles to keep train project from going off rails |author=Bussewitz, Cathy |date=August 26, 2017 |work=AP News |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\nOn October 21, 2009, the city announced Kiewit Pacific Co. had won the $483&nbsp;million contract to build the first two sections of the line (the {{convert|7|mi|adj=on}} long Farrington and {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} long Kamehameha sections), bidding $90&nbsp;million under the expected price. The stations were tendered separately.<ref name=\"RG 2009-10\"/><ref>{{citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=1st Honolulu Rail Contract Goes to Kiewit Pacific at $483M |date=October 22, 2009 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/22/ln/hawaii910220359.html |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> \n\nThe construction of the rail line started from suburban areas in Kapolei and Ewa, and progresses east towards the urban center in Honolulu. There will be 112 columns from [[East Kapolei station|East Kapolei]] to Ewa.<ref>Tim Sakahara, \"[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project],\" ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2014, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref> The choice to start from Kapolei was made because the first phase must include a baseyard for trains, which is more cheaply built away from the center, and also because the city chose to delay construction in the urban center to later phases of the project due to associated major impacts to existing infrastructure and unpopular traffic delays.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=First phase of rail would end in Pearl City |date=February 25, 2008 |newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Feb/25/ln/hawaii802250354.html |accessdate=March 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TheBus (Honolulu) WP 20150721 17 10 58 Rich.jpg|thumb|left|Precast bridge segments supported by cylindrical piers were used to construct most of the guideway (2015)]]\nTo speed construction, the elevated trackway is built using [[precast concrete]] [[box girder]] [[Segmental bridge|bridge segment]]s.<ref name=Aspire15/> This method was first used for [[MARTA]] in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://aspirebridge.com/magazine/2013Summer/SegTransit_Sum13_Web.pdf |title=Rail Transit Bridges |author=Cox, William R. |date=Summer 2013 |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> The trackway was designed by [[FIGG Bridge Engineers]] (who were responsible for the superstructure, referring to the box girder segmental bridge) and [[HNTB]] (substructure, referring to the columns). It is supported on single piers, each {{convert|6|to|7|ft}} in diameter at the base and {{convert|30|ft}} high, flaring at the top to support the lower section of the box girder; the piers are themselves supported by drilled shafts from {{convert|7|to|8|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=Aspire15>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.aspirebridge.com/magazine/2015Summer/Project-HonoluluRailTransitProject.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (Sgements 1 and 2) |author=Rodriguez, Jose |date=Summer 2015 |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nCasting of the box girder segments began in 2014 at a rate of 13 segments per day; in total, 5,238 segments will be required for the first {{convert|10|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} phase.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.asbi-assoc.org/projects/project.cfm?articleID=3FB7A851-B3D3-C35F-B6CAB78D7E8F50A7&categoryIDs=44A57F74-F1F6-B13E-81940961706FF0A9 |title=The Honolulu Rail Transit Project Honolulu, Hawaii - Construction Update |date=Fall 2014 |volume=59 |magazine=Segments |publisher=American Segmental Bridge Institute |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> The segments are cast locally in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/25280006/rail-systems-new-concrete-casting-yard/ |title=Rail system's new concrete casting yard |author=Daysog, Rick |date=April 18, 2014 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> Each segment weighs {{convert|50|ST|MT}} and measures (L\u00d7W\u00d7H, with length measured along the direction of the rails) {{convert|11|\u00d7|30|\u00d7|7|ft}},<ref name=CoC-presentation>{{cite report |url=http://www.cochawaii.org/wp-content/uploads/Daniel-Grabauskas.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Update |date=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Honolulu Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> and the deck ranges in thickness from {{convert|8|to|15|in}}.<ref name=Aspire15/> Once the piers were erected, a pier bracket ram was placed and a [[launching gantry]] was used to bridge the span between adjacent piers; a deck-mounted crane lifted the precast segments onto the gantry, which supported them while they were tensioned together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://somerseteng.com/project-gallery/honolulu-rail-transit/ |title=Honolulu Rail Transit |publisher=Somerset Engineering |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> In total, 430 of the 438 spans in Phase 1 were assembled using precast box girder segments, at an average rate of 1 to 2 days per span.<ref name=Aspire15/>\n\n[[File:HART Rail Construction (18599627918).jpg|thumb|right|Balanced cantilever construction over [[Interstate H-1]] in 2015]]\nFor the eight long spans required to bridge the {{jct|state=HI|H|1|noshield=1}}/{{jct|state=HI|H|2|noshield=1}} Waiawa interchange in Pearl City, a balanced cantilever construction method was used instead. This covers the segments from Pier 252 to Pier 256.<ref name=CoC-presentation/> Instead of precast segments, Kiewit used segments cast in-place, starting from the piers set in the freeway medians and working towards adjacent piers. The yellow-painted traveling forms at each end were used to cast each segment, then moved to the fresh end to cast the next segment. Each segment required {{convert|8000|lb}} of rebar and {{convert|48|cuyd}} of concrete, and weighed {{convert|105|ST|MT|abbr=on}}. 73 segments were required.<ref>{{youtube |id=Hums3p_LkjY |title=Time Lapse - Balanced Cantelevered Work over H1/H2 Merge}}</ref> The final pour for the balanced cantilever was performed in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-projects-balanced-cantilever-work-over-h-1-in-pearl-city-finishing-up/ |title=Rail project's balanced cantilever work over H-1 in Pearl City finishing up |date=September 17, 2016 |work=KHON 2 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Rail outside of Pearl Harbor (47934029428).jpg|thumb|left|Airport section underway near [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam]] (2019)]]\nThe third section of the route to be completed is the {{convert|5|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} Airport section east from Aloha Stadium to Middle Street that includes four stations, including the [[Honolulu International Airport station]]. [[AECOM]] won the contract to design the Airport section in 2012 with a $38.8&nbsp;million bid.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.aecom.com/press-releases/aecom-announced-today-that-it-has-been-awarded-a-us38-8-million-contract-to-design-the-airport-segment-of-the-honolulu-rail-transit-project-in-hawaii/ |title=AECOM announced today that it had been awarded a US$38.8-million contract to design the airport segment of the Honolulu Rail transit Project in Hawaii. |date=January 27, 2012 |publisher=AECOM Technology Corporation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The construction contract was awarded to a joint venture of Shimmick-Traylor-[[Granite Construction|Granite]] (STGJV) in August 2016, who bid $874.8&nbsp;million;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/hawaiis-8b-hart-project-is-chugging-along/30535 |title=Hawaii's $8B HART Project Is Chugging Along |author=Tobias, Lori |date=August 31, 2016 |work=Construction Equipment Guide |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32484731/hart-awards-airport-rail-construction-bid/ |title=Successful Airport-Middle Street rail segment bid totals $875M |author=Lincoln, Mileka |date=July 19, 2016 |work=Hawaii News Now |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> construction started in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.enr.com/articles/42730-funding-boost-shores-up-troubled-honolulu-rail-project |title=Funding Boost Shores Up Troubled Honolulu Rail Project |author=Parsons, Jim |date=September 13, 2017 |work=Engineering News-Record |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Airport section consists of 214 total spans which are also being constructed using precast concrete box girder bridge segments, like the earlier Farrington and Kamehameha sections, but for the Airport section, the segments are lifted and supported by an overhead [[gantry crane]] while they are tensioned.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://finleyengineeringgroup.com/projects/honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation-hart-airport-guideway-stations/ |title=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) Airport Guideway & Stations |publisher=Finley Engineering Group |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Both a conventional overhead gantry and an articulating gantry are being used during the guideway assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mcnarybergeron.com/portfolio/honolulu-rail-transit-project-hart/ |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (HART) |publisher=McNary Bergeron & Associates |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> More than 2700 precast segments are required for the Airport section, which also includes more than 230 columns for the piers and 5400 permanent [[sound wall]]s. For the pier foundations, shafts up to {{convert|350|ft}} deep were drilled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.traylor.com/projects/airport-guideway-and-stations-design-build-contract/ |title=Airport Guideway and Stations Design-Build Contrat |publisher=Traylor Bros., Inc. |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Where the guideway contacts the supporting piers, custom bearings have been installed to accommodate movement ranging from {{convert|2|to|19|in}} and rotation of 0.015\u20130.03 radians.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rjwatson.com/Projects/hart-airport-guideway-disktron-bearing-installation/ |title=HART Airport Guideway and Stations Project \u2013 Honolulu, Hawaii |publisher=RJ Watson Inc |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth and final segment of the route, the {{convert|4|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} City Center section terminating at {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}, may be completed under a [[public-private partnership]]. It is estimated the City Center section will cost $1.6&nbsp;billion to complete.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/post/hart-looking-private-partners-complete-last-16b-city-center-rail-segment |title=HART Looking For Private Partners to Complete Last $1.6B City Center Rail Segment |author=Yoshioka, Wayne |date=May 14, 2018 |work=Hawai\u2018i Public Radio |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Under the proposed public-private partnership, the City Center section will be procured under a design-build-finance-operate-maintain (DBFOM) contract, which will award the successful bidder the right to operate and maintain the entire system for a period of 25 years after completing the City Center section. The City of Honolulu would retain oversight over operations and maintenance, public information, and responsibility for fare vending and enforcement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://honolulu.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=3&clip_id=1000&meta_id=85914 |title=Public-Private Partnership Development Program {{!}} Program Structure |date=April 16, 2019 |publisher=Executive Matters and Legal Affairs Committee, City and County of Honolulu |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> A contract for $400&nbsp;million was awarded to clear utilities in the City Center section in May 2018.<ref name=HSA-180507>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/07/hawaii-news/hart-awards-400-million-contract-to-relocate-utilities-to-make-way-for-honolulu-rail/ |title=HART awards $400 million contract to relocate utilities to make way for Honolulu rail |date=May 7, 2018 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Stations ===\nLocal construction company Nan, Inc. won contracts to build six of the nine western stations in 2015; the West Oahu Station Group contract (for {{stn|East Kapolei}}, {{stn|UH-West Oahu}}, and {{stn|Ho'opili}}) was worth $56.1&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-18504/20150716-nr-hart-awards-construction-contract-for-west-oahu-rail-stations.pdf |title=HART awards construction contract for West Oahu rail stations |date=July 16, 2015 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> and the Kamehameha Highway contract (for {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}, {{stn|Pearlridge}}, and {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}) was worth $116&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/12/23/hawaii-news/nan-inc-wins-deal-for-last-trio-of-transit-stations/ |url-access=subscription |title=NAN Inc. wins deal for last trio of transit stations |first=Marcel |last=Honor\u00e9 |date=December 23, 2015 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The Farrington Highway Station Group contract (for {{stn|West Loch}}, {{stn|Waipahu}}, and {{stn|Leeward Community College}}) was awarded in 2015 to Hawaiian Dredging for $79&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16596/20150610-fhsgcc-rfb-hrt-798316-award-letter.pdf |title=Farrington Highway Stations Group Construction Contract No. CT-HRT-1500236 |date=June 10, 2015 |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The STGJV were awarded the contract to build the four Airport section stations ({{stn|Pearl Harbor Naval Base}}, {{stn|Honolulu International Airport}}, {{stn|Lagoon Drive}}, and {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}) as part of their $875&nbsp;million contract for the Airport section.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2018/09/20/its-coming-rail-work-kicks-off-airport-leg/ |title=It's coming: Rail work kicks off airport leg |author=Mendoza, Jim |date=October 26, 2017 |work=Hawaii News Now |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Hawaiian Station Naming Working Group (HSNWG), an expert working group, was named by the Honolulu City Council Resolution 09-158 on April 29, 2009 to develop [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] names for each station of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) system.<ref name=NaInoa-1>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21609/20180215-na-inoa-hawaiian-station-names.pdf |title=N\u0101 Inoa |date=February 2018 |publisher=honolulu.gov |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/ride/route-map |title=Honolulu Transit Route Map |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honolulutransit.org/media-center/planning/528-hawaiian-names |title=Hawaiian Names for Rail Stations |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> HSNWG proposed Hawaiian names for the nine rail stations on the [[Ewa District, Hawaii|Ewa]] end of the rail system (stations west of and including Aloha Stadium) in November 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21439/20171122-hawaiian-station-naming-program.pdf |title=Hawaiian Station Naming Program |date=November 22, 2017 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> and HART adopted the proposed names on February 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21921/HART%20New%20Release%20-%20Hawaiian%20Station%20Name%20Approval.pdf |title=HART Board of Directors unanimously approve Hawaiian names for first nine rail stations |date=February 22, 2018 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> On April 17, 2019, HART released a list of Hawaiian names proposed by HSNWG for the remaining 12 rail stations on the eastern end of the rail system, between Pearl Harbor and Ala Moana Center.<ref name=NaInoa-2/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/04/18/hawaii-news/newswatch/honolulu-rail-transit-authority-seeks-feedback-on-hawaiian-names-for-train-stations/ |title=Honolulu rail transit authority seeks feedback on Hawaiian names for train stations |author=Wu, Nina |date=April 18, 2019 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The 12 names were released for public comment, and the HSNWG will review comments before presenting a final list of names to the HART Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22715/HART%20Release%20(Station%20Hawaiian%20Names-Aloha%20Stadium%20to%20Ala%20Moana.pdf |title=Hawaiian names recommended for HART's rail stations |date=April 17, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22717/HSN-Program-Overview-2019.pdf |title=Hawaiian Station Naming Program |date=March 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:125%;\" | List of HART stations\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Name !! rowspan=2 | Section<ref name=Sections>{{cite web |url=https://planning.hawaii.gov/wp-content/uploads/HART-presentation.pdf#page=2 |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Overview |date=October 2016 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17073/20120525-ahupuaa-map.pdf |title=Ahupaa Map |date=25 May 2012 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" | Image !! rowspan=2 | Platform !! rowspan=2 | Opened !! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! Hawaiian !! English\n|-\n! {{stn|Kualaka\u2018i}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/579-kualaka-i-station-1-page |title=Kualaka\u2018i Station #1 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|East Kapolei}}\n| rowspan=7 style=\"background:#8064a2;color:#fff;\" | '''West O'ahu / Farrington'''<br/>{{convert|6.9|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kapolei, Hawaii|Kapolei]], [[Makakilo, Hawaii|Makakilo]], and [[Ewa Beach|\u02bbEwa Beach]]. Designated [[park-and-ride]] station.<ref name=design>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/ride/design |title=Station Design and Features |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! {{stn|Keone\u2018ae}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/580-keoneae-station-page |title=Keone\u2018ae Station #2 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|University of Hawaii West O'ahu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[University of Hawaii\u2013West Oahu|Keone\u2018ae campus]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n! {{stn|Honouliuli}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/581-honouliuli-station-page |title=Honouliuli Station #3 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Ho'opili}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Ewa Villages, Hawaii|Honouliuli]]\n|-\n! {{stn|H\u014d\u2018ae\u2018ae}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/582-hoaeae-station-page |title=H\u014d\u2018ae\u2018ae Station #4 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|West Loch}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[West Loch Estate, Hawaii|West Loch]], [[Ewa Beach|\u02bbEwa Beach]], and [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Pouhala}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/583-pouhala-station-page |title=Pouhala Transit Center Station #5 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Waipahu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]] and [[Waikele, Hawaii|Waikele]]\n|-\n! {{stn|H\u0101laulani}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/386-halaulani-station-6-page |title=H\u0101laulani Station #6 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Leeward Community College}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Leeward Community College]] and [[Waikele, Hawaii|Waikele]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2 | {{stn|Waiawa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/584-waiawa-station-page |title=Waiawa Station #7 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Pearl Highlands}}\n| rowspan=2 | \n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 |  2020 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves Pearl Highlands, Pearl Highlands Center, and [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background:#80643a;color:#fff;\" | '''Kamehameha Highway'''<br/>{{convert|3.9|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Kalauao}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/586-kalauao-station-page |title=Kalauao Center Station #8 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Pearlridge}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2020 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Pearlridge Center]], [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]], [[Waimalu, Hawaii|Waimalu]], and [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | {{stn|H\u0101lawa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/587-halawa-station-page |title=H\u0101lawa Station #9 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Aloha Stadium}}\n| rowspan=2 |\n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 | 2020 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Aloha Stadium]], [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]], and [[Moanalua]]. Designated park-and-ride station.<ref name=design/>\n|-\n| rowspan=5 style=\"background:#2a64a2;color:#fff;\" | '''Airport'''<br/>{{convert|5.1|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Makalapa}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/588-pearl-harbor-naval-base-station-page |title=Pearl Harbor Naval Base Station #10 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Pearl Harbor Naval Base}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor\u2013Hickam]], and [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Lelepaua}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/589-honolulu-international-airport-station-11-page |title=Honolulu International Airport #11 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Honolulu International Airport}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Daniel K. Inouye International Airport]] and [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]]\n|-\n! {{stn|\u0100hua}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/590-lagoon-drive-station-12-page |title=Lagoon Drive Station #12 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Lagoon Drive}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2022 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves Lagoon Drive and [[Mapunapuna, Hawaii|Mapunapuna]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Kahauiki}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/591-middle-street-station-13-page |title=Middle Street Station #13 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! rowspan=2 | {{stn|Middle Street||Honolulu}}\n| rowspan=2 |\n| rowspan=2 | 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| rowspan=2 | 2022 (scheduled)\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Also known as Hauiki. Serves [[Kalihi]] and [[Honolulu Harbor]]\n|-\n| rowspan=9 style=\"background:#b7276b;color:#fff;\" | '''City Center'''<br/>{{convert|4.1|mi|disp=br|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! {{stn|Mokauea}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/592-kalihi-station-14-page |title=Kalihi Station #14 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Kalihi}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kalihi]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Niuhelewai}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/593-kapalama-station-15-page |title=Kapalama Station #15 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Kap\u0101lama}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kalihi]], [[Kap\u0101lama]], and [[Honolulu Community College]]\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u016bwili}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/594-iwilei-station-16-page |title=Iwilei Station #16 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Iwilei}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Iwilei]] and [[Kalihi]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Holau}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/595-chinatown-station-page |title=Chinatown Station #17 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Chinatown||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Also known as H\u014dlau or Ho\u2018olau. Serves [[Chinatown, Honolulu|Chinatown]]\n|-\n! {{stn|Kuloloia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/596-downtown-station-18-page |title=Downtown Station #18 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Downtown||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Downtown Honolulu]], [[Aloha Tower]], and Capitol District\n|-\n! {{stn|Ka\u2018\u0101kaukukui}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/597-civic-center-station-19-page |title=Civic Center Station #19 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Civic Center||Honolulu}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves the Ward, [[Ward Centers]], and Maikiki\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u016bkulu\u0101e\u2018o}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/599-kakaako-station-20-page |title=Kakaako Station #20 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|K\u0101k\u0101\u2018ako}}\n|\n| 2 ([[Side platform|side]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Kaka\u02bbako]], Maikiki, and Ward\n|-\n! {{stn|K\u0101lia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.honolulutransit.org/52-station-information/600-ala-moana-center-station-21-page |title=Ala Moana Center Station #21 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> !! {{stn|Ala Moana Center}}\n|\n| 1 ([[Center platform|center]])\n| 2025 (scheduled)\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-size:90%;\" | Serves [[Ala Moana, Honolulu|Ala Moana]], [[Ala Moana Center]], [[Kapi\u02bbolani, Honolulu|Kapi\u02bbolani]], Mano, and [[Waikiki]]\n|}\n\n===Rail Operations Center===\nThe Rail Operations Center (ROC; also known as the Maintenance and Storage Facility) is the {{convert|43|acre|adj=on}} railyard, operations, and maintenance facility, divided into four buildings. It is in [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]]<!--{{coord|21.390694|-157.988123}}-->, between the campuses of [[Leeward Community College]] and [[Waipahu High School]], just west of {{stn|H\u0101laulani}}. The design has been awarded [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Silver certification.<ref name=SRG>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21774/20180511-hrtp-system-resource-guide.pdf#page=9 |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project: System Resource Guide |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe buildings on the ROC campus are:\n* Operation & Servicing Building (OSB) \u2013 housing primary vehicle maintenance facilities and the Operations and Control Center, where operators will monitor and control vehicle movement\n* Maintenance of Way Building (MOW) \u2013 housing equipment used to inspect and repair tracks\n* Train Wash Facility (TWF) \u2013 an automated facility to clean vehicle exteriors\n* Wheel Truing Building (WTB) \u2013 a maintenance facility for vehicle wheels\n\nThe contract for the ROC was awarded to the Kiewit/Kobayashi Joint Venture in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16112/MSF-Contract%20Package-10A0449.pdf |title=Agreement for Design-Build Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1000449 |date=June 30, 2011 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> The contract was initially awarded at a cost of $195&nbsp;million; when the ROC was completed in July 2016, the actual incurred costs were $274&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-19156/201607-monthly-progress-report-low-res.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Monthly Progress Report |date=July 2016 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\n== Rolling stock ==\n[[File:Honolulu Rail Transit First Trainset 2017-02-18.jpg|thumb|right|First trainset for the rail project on public display in February 2017]]\n\nThe line will use {{convert|256|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} four-car train sets, each with the capacity to carry about 780 passengers, similar in weight to [[light rail]] systems elsewhere in the United States (such as the [[MAX Light Rail|MAX]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]), as opposed to heavier, and thus more expensive, lines found on rapid transit systems like the subways and elevated systems of [[Chicago 'L'|Chicago]] and [[New York City Subway|New York City]].<ref name=\"Rolling Stock 2011\">{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Have a seat |date=March 22, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110322_Have_a_seat.html |page=A1, A6 |volume=130 |issue=50 |accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> However, the stations will be standalone structures and will be substantially bigger than typical light rail stations. Physically, the Honolulu system will have a good deal in common with light rapid transit systems such as [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]] in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]] or the [[Copenhagen Metro]], as well as the [[Docklands Light Railway]] in London. The system will be the first metro system in the United States to feature [[Platform screen doors#Automatic platform gate|platform gates]] and will be driverless.<ref name=\"station-design-offi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx|title=Home|website=www.honolulutransit.org|access-date=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728211528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx|archive-date=July 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRolling stock for the line will initially include 80 cars in 20 four-car train sets.<ref>http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17047/20140218-hart-train-vehicle-fact-sheet.pdf</ref> \nEach car will be {{convert|64|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} long, weigh {{convert|72,000|lb|kg|sigfig=2|abbr=on|adj=on}}, and have 36 seats with a listed total capacity of 195 people.<ref name=\"Rolling Stock 2011\" />  The cars will be powered by a third-rail electrification system.<ref>{{citation |author1=U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration |author2=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |date=June 2010 |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |pages=2\u201330 |url=http://honolulutransit.org/library/files/02.pdf |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Contract and delivery===\nThe contract for the rail cars (named the Core Systems Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services contract) was signed on November 28, 2011 by HART and Ansaldo Honolulu, a joint venture between [[AnsaldoBreda]] and [[Ansaldo STS]].<ref name=CT-DTS-1100194>{{cite web |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14729/Agreement.pdf |title=Agreement for Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1100194 |date=November 28, 2011 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> AnsaldoBreda and Ansaldo STS previously collaborated on the construction and operation of vehicles for the [[Copenhagen Metro]]<ref>{{citation |last=Brown |first=Robert |title=FACT CHECK \u2014 Carlisle: Ansaldo's Copenhagen Line One of World's Best |date=April 15, 2011 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News LLC |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/fact_checks/2011/04/15/10342-fact-check-carlisle-ansaldos-copenhagen-line-one-of-worlds-best/ |accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Brescia Metro]]. Both companies were later purchased by [[Hitachi Rail]] in 2015<ref>{{cite news|title=Hitachi agrees to buy Ansaldo STS and AnsaldoBreda|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/hitachi-agrees-to-buy-ansaldo-sts-and-ansaldobreda.html|accessdate=February 25, 2015|work=Railway Gazette|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> and Ansaldo Honolulu was subsequently renamed to Hitachi Rail Honolulu (HRH). Under the $1.4&nbsp;billion contract, HRH is responsible for designing and fabricating the rail cars ($574&nbsp;million), a test to validate train performance ($167&nbsp;million), and operations and maintenance (O&M) during the first five years of revenue service ($339&nbsp;million), with an option to continue O&M services for HART for an additional five years ($318&nbsp;million) provided the review of the first five years is favorable.<ref name=CT-DTS-1100194/>\n\nThe two unsuccessful bidders for the rail car contract, [[Bombardier Transportation]] and [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo Corporation of America]], filed protests over the award.<ref>{{citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=2 bidders protest city's rail decision |date=April 12, 2011 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110412_2_bidders_protest_citys_rail_decision.html |accessdate=April 12, 2011|volume=130 |issue=71}}</ref>  Both protests were rejected during the administrative process, but Bombardier sought judicial review of their bid protest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |title=Disqualified Honolulu Rail Bidder Bombardier Files New Appeal |date=October 14, 2011 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/10/14/13270-disqualified-honolulu-rail-bidder-bombardier-files-new-appeal/ |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref>  The administrative decision against Bombardier's protest was affirmed by both the state Circuit Court and the Intermediate Court of Appeals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abramson |first=Mark |title=Hawaii Appeals Court upholds ruling in Bombardier rail lawsuit |date=October 17, 2012 |work=Pacific Business News |publisher=American City Business Journals |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2012/10/17/hawaii-appeals-court-upholds-ruling-in.html |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>''[http://www.courts.state.hi.us/docs/opin_ord/ica/2012/oct/CAAP-11-0000756.pdf Bombardier Transportation (Holdings) USA Inc. v. Director, Department of Budget and Fiscal Services, City and County of Honolulu]'', 128 Haw. 413 (App.), {{West |P|289|3|1049|Haw. App.|2012|}}</ref>\n\nThe first two cars arrived in Hawaii in March 2016,<ref name=IRJ-1603>{{cite news |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/metros/first-honolulu-metro-trains-delivered/ |title=First Honolulu metro cars delivered |author=Barrow, Keith |date=March 29, 2016 |work=International Railway Journal |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/03/24/business/business-breaking/first-train-cars-arrive-in-honolulu-for-rail-transit-project/ |title=First train cars arrive in Honolulu for rail transit project |author=Honor\u00e9, Marcel |date=March 24, 2016 |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> and the first train was unveiled to the public at the Rail Operations Center on May 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.hitachi.us/press/honolulu-new-transit-system-rail-cars |title=Honolulu Gets First Look at New Transit System Rail Cars |date=May 2, 2016 |publisher=Hitachi USA |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> To meet \"Buy America\" requirements for federally-subsidized transit projects, the bodyshells are fabricated at the Hitachi Rail Italy plant in [[Reggio Calabria, Italy]], then shipped to HRI's [[Pittsburg, California]] plant for final assembly.<ref name=IRJ-1603/> The Pittsburg factory has since been partially leased to Bombardier Rail, who will assemble cars for [[BART]] there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sf.streetsblog.org/2019/06/14/bart-train-plant-moving-to-pittsburg/ |title=BART Train Plant Moving to Pittsburg, CA |author=Rudick, Roger |date=June 14, 2019 |work=Streetsblog SF |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Hitachi Rail Italy reported defects were discovered in the welds in the extruded aluminum beams of twenty-seven car shells, four of which were already in Hawaii. The manufacturer will fix the problems, but warned delivery may be delayed as production of new vehicles will be halted.<ref>{{cite news |title=New defect could further stall rail|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/honolulu-star-advertiser/20161216/281479276058340 |author=Honor\u00e9, Marcel |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=December 16, 2016}}</ref>  In March 2017 HART said they would meet the interim opening needs after repair of the defective cars and that full opening would not be affected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Repairs to fix rail car production defects scheduled to start in March|url=http://khon2.com/2017/02/18/repairs-to-fix-rail-car-production-defects-scheduled-to-start-in-march/|website=KHON2|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017 trains were towed on tracks in Honolulu for the first time, to check clearances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu tests rail car on track for first time|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/30/breaking-news/hart-train-makes-first-appearance-on-guideway/|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|accessdate=September 8, 2017|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref>  Testing of trains under their own power commenced in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=In successful test, city rail cars reach 40 mph on its own power|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/36632259/city-rail-cars-reach-40-mph-in-speed-test|website=Hawaii News Now|accessdate=October 20, 2017|date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of progress==\n* June 2006 - Officials estimate the infrastructure construction cost at estimated at $3&nbsp;billion, $200&nbsp;million more than a previous estimate, for a 24-mile system.  This does not include the cost of the trains.<ref name=\"2006cost3billion\">{{cite web|title=Rail transit system cost estimate: $3 billion|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/23/ln/FP606230364.html|publisher=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=June 23, 2006}}</ref>\n* January 2007 - The General Excise Tax (GET) within Honolulu County is increased by 0.5% with the extra funds earmarked for a mass transit system.  The increase was set to expire on December 31, 2022.\n* February 2007 - The City Council approves the Minimum Operating Segment from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Centre, via Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\" />\n* October 2008 - The Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS) is released to the public.  The projected cost is $3.7&nbsp;billion including $1&nbsp;billion for contingencies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Just the facts on Honolulu transit|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Oct/12/ln/hawaii810120332.html|accessdate=September 1, 2017|date=October 12, 2008}}</ref>\n* November 2008 - Fifty three percent of voters support an measures to give the Honolulu City Council authority to proceed with \"establishment of a steel wheel on steel rail transit system\". The estimated cost is $4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |newspaper=Honolulu Star Bulletin |accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* January 2009 - The middle portion of the route between Aloha Stadium and Middle Street is amended to have stations at the Pearl Harbor Naval Base and the Honolulu Airport which had one of the original options.  The previous route followed Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name=\"2009routechange\" />\n* June 2010 - The Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS) is released to the public.  Estimated cost is $5.5&nbsp;billion.  Patronage by 2030 is projected to be 116,300 riders per day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honolulu Rail: The Complete Final Environmental Impact Statement|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2010/06/2009-honolulu-rail-the-complete-final-environmental-impact-statement/|date=June 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=System Figures |work=honolulutransit.org |url=http://honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |accessdate=July 22, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729021514/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |archivedate=July 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n* December 2010 - A report, commissioned by outgoing Governor Lingle, is released which warns the project could cost at least $1.7&nbsp;billion more than the city\u2019s projected $5.5&nbsp;billion price tag.<ref name=\"LingleReport2010\" />\n* March 2012 - Dan Grabauskas becomes Executive Director and CEO of HART on a three year contract. He takes his position in April 2012.<ref name=HonoluluGov2012-03-01/><ref name=\"KHON2016-08-16\">{{cite news|url=https://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/1025883209|title=HART CEO Grabauskas resigns, Formby steps in as interim|date=August 18, 2016|work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Kuriowa|first=Jared|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* May 2012 - Construction workers started pouring concrete on the foundations that will hold the rail columns.<ref>Tim Sakahara, \"[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project],\" ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2012, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref>\n* December 2012 - Honolulu City Council and the Federal Transit Authority (FTA) sign agreement for the project with a budget of $5.12&nbsp;billion including $1.55&nbsp;billion provided by the Federal Government.  Full system revenue service is projected for January 31, 2020.<ref name=\"HartRecoveryPlan2017\">{{cite web|title=HART Recovery Plan|url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-20510/20170428-hart-recovery-plan.pdf|publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation|accessdate=August 31, 2017|page=19|format=PDF|date=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* September 2014 - HART canceled the initial tender for the first nine stations after the bids were higher than budget. The first trips on the railway are expected to be delayed, probably until 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |title=HART cancels bids for first 9 rail stations |newspaper=[[KITV]] |date=September 10, 2014 |accessdate=November 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129163425/http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n* November 2015 - FTA withholds payment of a $250&nbsp;million allotment until the council could show it had sufficient funding to complete the project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Year in Review 2015: Honolulu's rail transit project|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2015/12/15/year-in-review-2015-honolulus-rail-transit-project.html|website=Pacific Business Review|accessdate=September 5, 2017|date=December 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* January 2016 - Five year extension to the General Excise Tax surcharge adopted to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding.<ref name=\"HartRecoveryPlan2017\" />\n* May 2016 - HART chairwoman [[Colleen Hanabusa]] shared a confidential document detailing budget estimates as of March 1, 2016, showing that the rail project is expected to cost $6.9&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/2016/05/honolulu-rail-price-estimate-jumps-to-6-9b/ |title=Honolulu Rail Price Estimate Jumps To $6.9B |work=Civil Beat News}}</ref>\n* April 2016 - An audit of the project by the City criticized HART for using outdated financial figures and budgets, lack of documentation for \"change orders\", and warned the HART estimates of the cost overruns were  unreliable.<ref>{{cite web|title=City audit calls HART\u2019s finances, plans \u2018outdated and unreliable\u2019|url=http://khon2.com/2016/04/15/city-releases-audit-of-honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation/|website=khon2|accessdate=September 4, 2017|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Audit slams Honolulu rail agency over management, costs|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/04/15/breaking-news/audit-slams-honolulu-rail-agency-over-management-costs/|accessdate=September 4, 2017|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref>  HART officials disputed the audit's findings.\n* May 2016 - The FTA revealed that they estimate the total cost as $8.1&nbsp;billion for the {{convert|20|mi|km|abbr=on}} line.  In addition completion of the rail system would be delayed nearly five years until December 2024, versus HART's federal funding agreement stating that full line service from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Center would start in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/hawaii-news/add-5-years-and-1b-for-rail-federal-agency-says/|title=Add 5 years and $1B for rail, federal agency says|date=May 17, 2016|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|access-date=December 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* June 2016 - Report from Jacobs Engineering, the project management oversight contractor, says that under a worst-case scenario the final cost would $10.79&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"Jacobsworstcase\" />\n* August 2016 - Dan Grabauskas resigns as CEO and Executive Director of HART but will be the official CEO until October 2016. From August until October, the Department of Transportation Service Director Mike Formby served as interim CEO.<ref name=KHON2016-08-16/><ref name=\"StarAdvertiser2016-08-16\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/08/18/breaking-news/grabauskas-resigns-as-harts-chief-executive/|title=Grabauskas resigns as HART\u2019s chief executive|date=August 18, 2016|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Honor\u00e9|first=Marcel|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HNN2016-08-18\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32792174/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/|title=Outgoing rail CEO ruffled feathers, struggled with cost overruns|date=August 18, 2016|work=[[Hawaii News Now]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last1=Daysog|first1=Rick|last2=Kawano|first2=Lynn|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* October 2016 - Krishniah N. Murthy named interim CEO and Executive Director of HART and served in this position until December 2017.<ref name=\"PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2016/12/28/former-hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-starts-own.html|title=Former HART CEO Dan Grabauskas starts own consulting firm|date=December 28, 2016|work=[[American City Business Journals|Pacific Business News]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Shimogawa|first=Duane|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* April 2017 - HART sent a \"Recovery Plan\" to the FTA which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable plan. The new project cost given is $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing costs are included it will be over $10&nbsp;billion.  Opening of part of the system, from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium, is scheduled for the end of 2020 with final completion of the full route by December 2025.  The project is reported to be 36 percent complete as of March 2017.<ref name=\"HARTcommitted\" /><ref name=\"HARTrecoverplan\" />\n* July 2017 - Andrew Robbins named new CEO and Executive Director of HART replacing interim CEO and Executive Director Krishniah N. Murthy in December 2017.<ref name=PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28/><ref name=\"StarAdvertiser2017-07-31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/07/31/breaking-news/hart-board-selects-new-executive-director/|title=HART board selects new executive director|date=July 31, 2017|newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]|location=[[Honolulu]]|last=Honor\u00e9|first=Marcel|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* September 2017 - A new law is enacted to extend and increase taxes to raise an additional  $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project.  The GET surcharge is extended by three years to 2030 (generating about $1&nbsp;billion) and a surcharge of one percent is placed on the statewide hotel room tax for 13 years (generating $1.3&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"Sep17taxespassed\" /><ref name=\"Sep17Govsignsbill\" />   HART submits a new recovery plan to the FTA with an estimated final cost of $9.02&nbsp;billion with savings attributed to reduced financing costs given the new taxes.<ref name=\"CostDropped1billion\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Honolulu Rail Transit}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.honolulutransit.org/}}\n\n{{Hawaii railroads}}\n{{USSubway}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{coord missing|Hawaii}}\n\n[[Category:Transportation in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rail transport articles in need of updating]]\n[[Category:Rail transportation in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Honolulu Rail Transit|*]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:2020 in rail transport]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:Under construction tram and light rail transit systems]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s) + removeWP:OVERLINKs, replaced: website=www. \u2192 website= (2), [sic] \u2192 {{sic}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honolulu_Rail_Transit"}
{"title_page": "1986 Canadian Professional Championship", "text_new": "{{Infobox Individual Snooker Tournament\n|tournament_name=Canadian Professional Championship\n|logo=\n|dates=August 1986\n|venue=Snooker Centre\n|location=[[Toronto]]\n|country=[[Canada]]\n|organisation=\n|format=Non-[[Snooker world rankings|ranking]] event\n|Total prize fund=\u00a313,000\n|winners_share=\u00a32,900\n|highest_break=129 ([[Jim Wych]])\n|winner={{flagicon|CAN}} [[Cliff Thorburn]]\n|runner_up={{flagicon|CAN}} [[Jim Wych]]\n|score=6\u20132\n|previous=[[1985 Canadian Professional Championship|1985]]\n|next=[[1987 Canadian Professional Championship|1987]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1986 [[Canadian Professional Championship]]''' was a professional non-ranking [[snooker]] tournament, which took place in August 1986 at Snooker Centre, [[Toronto]], [[Canada]].<ref>{{citeweb|title=Other National Professional Championship|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107161810/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/natpro.html|publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SCENE\" />\n\n[[Cliff Thorburn]] won the title for the third year in a row, and fourth overall, by beating [[Jim Wych]] 6\u20132 in the final.<ref name=\"Cuesport\">{{cite book|last=Hayton|first=Eric|title=Cuesport Book of Professional Snooker|page=154}}</ref> Wych compiled the highest break of the tournament, 129, in his quarter-final match against Bernie Mikkelsen.<ref name=\"SCENE\" />\n\nThe [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] funded \u00a313,000 in prize money through its national championship subsidy, a scheme which provided \u00a31,000 per entrant. Thorburn received \u00a32,900 as winner.<ref name=\"SCENE\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Thorburn wins Canadian title \u2026 and Francisco takes South African  |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=14-15 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=September 1986 }}</ref>\n\n==Main draw==\n<ref>{{cite web|titl