{"title_page": "Ream Al-Hasani", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|British neuroscientist and pharmacologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Ream Al-Hasani\n| image             = File:Al-Hasani, Ream Headshot 2017.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = British\n| fields            = Neuroscience, Pharmacology\n| workplaces        = Washington University in St. Louis, Center for Clinical Pharmacology\n| alma_mater        = University of Portsmouth, University of Surrey\n| known_for         = Kappa opioid signalling in the negative affect associated with pain\n| awards            = INRC Young Investigator Awards, Young Investigators Grants from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation, \"Pathway to Independence Award\" from NIDA\n| Institutions      = Washington University in St. Louis, Missouri\n}}\n'''Ream Al-Hasani''' is a British neuroscientist and pharmacologist as well as an Assistant Professor of [[Anesthesiology]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis]], Missouri. Al-Hasani studies the endogenous [[opioid]] system to understand how to target it therapeutically to treat addiction, affective disorders, and chronic pain.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAl-Hasani grew up in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.storiesofwin.org/profiles/2020/4/1/dr-ream-al-hasani|title=Dr. Ream Al-Hasani|website=Stories of WiN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani's family moved from [[Iraq]] to the UK for her father's academic career before she was born.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her parents planned on returning to [[Iraq]] after her birth but decided against it due to war in the [[Middle East]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Al-Hasani was the only [[Muslims|Muslim]] girl in her school, and though there were not many Middle Eastern role models in science, she became fascinated by the effects of drugs on the brain and decided to pursue a career in academia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAl-Hasani completed her undergraduate degree at the [[University of Portsmouth]] in the UK, graduating with a degree in Pharmacology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clinicalpharmstl.org/research/alhasani.html|title=Ream Al-Hasani, Ph.D., Assistant Professor|website=www.clinicalpharmstl.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> After completing her undergraduate degree, Al-Hasani pursued an internship in industry at [[GlaxoSmithKline]] where she studied [[Neurodegeneration|neurodegenerative diseases]] and [[neuroinflammation]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2017/first-faculty-researchers-announced.html|title=Appointment of First Faculty Researchers Announced|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani's year-long internship studying neuroscience in industry inspired her to pursue a PhD in neuropharmacology.<ref name=\":0\" /> She would become the first woman in her family to obtain a doctorate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Graduate work ===\nFunded by the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council]], Al-Hasani was able to pursue her graduate studies at the [[University of Surrey]] in England.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani was interested in exploring the interactions between [[adenosine]] and [[dopamine receptor]]s in morphine addiction for her PhD, so she sought co-mentorship from Ian Kitchen, Professor of Neuropharmacology, and [[Susanna Hourani]], Professor of Pharmacology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Endogenous Opioids ====\nIn 2010, Al-Hasani and her colleagues in the Kitchen Lab published a paper in the [[European Journal of Neuroscience]] exploring the influence of genetic variability on heroin addiction.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bailey|first=Alexis|last2=Metaxas|first2=Athanasios|last3=Al-Hasani|first3=Ream|last4=Keyworth|first4=Helen L.|last5=Forster|first5=Duncan M.|last6=Kitchen|first6=Ian|date=February 2010|title=Mouse strain differences in locomotor, sensitisation and rewarding effect of heroin; association with alterations in MOP-r activation and dopamine transporter binding|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20384817|journal=The European Journal of Neuroscience|volume=31|issue=4|pages=742\u2013753|doi=10.1111/j.1460-9568.2010.07104.x|issn=1460-9568|pmid=20384817}}</ref> When they compared a strain of highly inbred mice to typical control mice, they found differences in the behavioural effects of [[heroin]] and differences in the neurobiological substrates mediating these differences.<ref name=\":2\" /> Specifically, they found that highly inbred mice had much higher sensitivity to the rewarding properties of heroin yet inbred did not display increased location upon administration of heroin unlike control mice.<ref name=\":2\" /> When they looked for the neurobiological substrates of these effects, they found that heroin decreased [[\u039c-opioid receptor|mu opioid receptor]] (MOP-r) density in controls but not in the inbred mice, MOP-r stimulated binding was twofold higher in controls compared to inbreds, and heroin increased expression of dopamine transporters in inbred mice but not in controls.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n==== Adenosingeric and Dopaminergic Signalling ====\nIn 2011, Al-Hasani published a first author paper in [[Neuroscience (journal)|Neuroscience]] exploring the interaction between [[dopamine]] signalling and adenosine signalling in the [[ventral tegmental area]] (VTA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=R.|last2=Foster|first2=J. D.|last3=Metaxas|first3=A.|last4=Ledent|first4=C.|last5=Hourani|first5=S. M. O.|last6=Kitchen|first6=I.|last7=Chen|first7=Y.|date=2011-09-08|title=Increased desensitization of dopamine D\u2082 receptor-mediated response in the ventral tegmental area in the absence of adenosine A(2A) receptors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21669258|journal=Neuroscience|volume=190|pages=103\u2013111|doi=10.1016/j.neuroscience.2011.05.068|issn=1873-7544|pmid=21669258}}</ref> Since adenosine A(2A) receptors have been known to modulate neurotransmitter systems and modulate neural activity in the striatum, she sought to see if this was also true in the VTA.<ref name=\":3\" /> When Al-Hasani knocked out A(2A) receptors and looked the dopamine receptor 2 (D2) mediated inhibition in the VTA, she found that A(2A) knockouts had D2 receptor desensitization leading to reduced maximal inhibition.<ref name=\":3\" /> A follow up to this finding was published in Neuropharmacology in 2013 looking at the ability of A(2A) receptors to modulate cholinergic signalling through interactions with [[nicotinic acetylcholine receptor]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Metaxas|first=Athanasios|last2=Al-Hasani|first2=Ream|last3=Farshim|first3=Pamela|last4=Tubby|first4=Kristina|last5=Berwick|first5=Amy|last6=Ledent|first6=Catherine|last7=Hourani|first7=Susanna|last8=Kitchen|first8=Ian|last9=Bailey|first9=Alexis|date=2013-08-01|title=Genetic deletion of the adenosine A2A receptor prevents nicotine-induced upregulation of \u03b17, but not \u03b14\u03b22* nicotinic acetylcholine receptor binding in the brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0028390813001196|journal=Neuropharmacology|language=en|volume=71|pages=228\u2013236|doi=10.1016/j.neuropharm.2013.03.023|issn=0028-3908}}</ref>\n\n=== Postdoctoral work ===\nAl-Hasani took time to travel after her PhD and then decided to move to America for her postdoctoral work.<ref name=\":0\" /> She joined the lab of Michael Bruchas in the Department of Anesthesiology at [[Washington University School of Medicine]] in St. Louis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruchaslab.org/lab-news|title=Lab News|website=BRUCHAS LAB|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Bruchas, Al-Hasani began to explore the kappa opioid system and associated neural circuitry to understand its role in driving motivated behaviors.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani wrote a first-athour review paper in 2011 discussing the opioid system in the brain and how opioid receptors not only mediate intracellular signal transduction pathways to modulate molecular and cellular responses as well as their role in behaviors associated with analgesia, reward, depression, and anxiety.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=Bruchas|first2=Michael R.|date=2011-12-01|title=Molecular Mechanisms of Opioid Receptor-dependent Signaling and Behavior|url=https://anesthesiology.pubs.asahq.org/article.aspx?articleid=1934470|journal=Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists|language=en|volume=115|issue=6|pages=1363\u20131381|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e318238bba6|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> In 2013, Al-Hasani published a first author paper in [[Neuropsychopharmacology (journal)|Neuropsychopharmacology]] where she investigated the interactions between [[Norepinephrine|noradrenergic]] (NA) and [[dynorphin]]/[[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid systems]] in the forebrain.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Foshage|first3=Audra M.|last4=Bruchas|first4=Michael R.|date=November 2013|title=Locus Coeruleus Kappa-Opioid Receptors Modulate Reinstatement of Cocaine Place Preference Through a Noradrenergic Mechanism|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/npp2013151|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=38|issue=12|pages=2484\u20132497|doi=10.1038/npp.2013.151|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> She found that kappa opioid receptor(KOR)-induced reinstatement of cocaine CPP was potentiated when beta-adrenergic signalling was blocked and that the interactions between adrenergic signalling and KOR signalling occur external to the [[locus coeruleus]].<ref name=\":4\" /> Her findings were novel since the interaction between the KORs and the NA system had not been previously known, and she established its role in the reinstatement of [[cocaine]] drug seeking behavior.<ref name=\":4\" /> Also in 2013, Al-Hasani published a paper exploring the effects of stress on the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] system in the context of drug relapse.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Bruchas|first3=Michael R.|date=2013|title=Exposure to chronic mild stress prevents kappa opioid-mediated reinstatement of cocaine and nicotine place preference|url=https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fphar.2013.00096/full|journal=Frontiers in Pharmacology|language=English|volume=4|doi=10.3389/fphar.2013.00096|issn=1663-9812}}</ref> She found that various stressors cause [[Emotional dysregulation|dysregulation]] of kappa opioid circuitry, but interestingly, mild stressors cause adaptive changes in the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] circuitry that might be protective against drug relapse.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 2015, Al-Hasani helped elucidate the mechanisms by which the [[locus coeruleus]] [[Noradrenergic and specific serotonergic antidepressant|noradrenergi]]<nowiki/>c (LC-NE) system generates stress-induced anxiety in rodents.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=McCall|first=Jordan G.|last2=Al-Hasani|first2=Ream|last3=Siuda|first3=Edward R.|last4=Hong|first4=Daniel Y.|last5=Norris|first5=Aaron J.|last6=Ford|first6=Christopher P.|last7=Bruchas|first7=Michael R.|date=2015-08-05|title=CRH Engagement of the Locus Coeruleus Noradrenergic System Mediates Stress-Induced Anxiety|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(15)00606-6|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=87|issue=3|pages=605\u2013620|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2015.07.002|issn=0896-6273|pmid=26212712}}</ref> They found that activation of the LC-NE neurons increases stress-induced anxiety and aversion and that inhibition attenuates these behaviors.<ref name=\":6\" /> They also found that specifically the [[corticotropin-releasing hormone]] positive neurons in the LC that receive inputs from the central amygdala are the neural subpopulation within the LC responsible for mediating the anxiety-like behaviors.<ref name=\":6\" /> Later in 2015, Al-Hasani published a first-author paper in Neuron describing distinct functions of two different subregions of the nucleus accumbens (NAc) that are mediated by [[dynorphin]]-[[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid receptor]] (KOR) signalling.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Gomez|first4=Adrian M.|last5=Schmitz|first5=Gavin P.|last6=Bernardi|first6=Julio M.|last7=Pyo|first7=Chang-O.|last8=Park|first8=Sung Il|last9=Marcinkiewcz|first9=Catherine M.|last10=Crowley|first10=Nicole A.|last11=Krashes|first11=Michael J.|date=2015-09-02|title=Distinct Subpopulations of Nucleus Accumbens Dynorphin Neurons Drive Aversion and Reward|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(15)00713-8|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=87|issue=5|pages=1063\u20131077|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2015.08.019|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Specifically, she found that stimulating dynorphinergic cells in the ventral shell of the NAc elicits aversive responses via KOR activation while stimulating dynorphinergic cells in the dorsal shell of the NAc elicits appetitive behaviors mediated by\u00a0 KOR signalling.<ref name=\":7\" /> Al-Hasani's work in the Bruchas Lab has helped to elucidate the role of the dynorphin-kappa opioid system in modulating affective states and in mediating drug reinstatement.<ref name=\":7\" /> It also led to her winning an NIH Pathway to Independence Award (K99/R00) which provided her the funding to start her own lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2017/first-faculty-researchers-announced.html|title=Appointment of First Faculty Researchers Announced|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Tool Development ====\nAl-Hasani has also helped create novel technologies in the Bruchas Lab with which to probe neural circuits. Al-Hasani optimized wireless [[Optogenetics|optogenetic]] technologies that allow for neural circuit modulation without animal movement being constrained by tethering.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCall|first=Jordan G.|last2=Kim|first2=Tae-il|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Huang|first4=Xian|last5=Jung|first5=Yei Hwan|last6=Al-Hasani|first6=Ream|last7=Omenetto|first7=Fiorenzo G.|last8=Bruchas|first8=Michael R.|last9=Rogers|first9=John A.|date=December 2013|title=Fabrication and application of flexible, multimodal light-emitting devices for wireless optogenetics|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2013.158|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=8|issue=12|pages=2413\u20132428|doi=10.1038/nprot.2013.158|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Al-Hasani also merged wireless [[Optogenetics|optogenetic]]<nowiki/>s with pharmacology such that various compounds can be administered to the brain while certain neural circuits are being activated or inhibited to explore the effects of these compounds on neural circuit function and behavioral output.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jeong|first=Jae-Woong|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Zhang|first4=Yihui|last5=Al-Hasani|first5=Ream|last6=Kim|first6=Minku|last7=Li|first7=Shuo|last8=Sim|first8=Joo Yong|last9=Jang|first9=Kyung-In|last10=Shi|first10=Yan|last11=Hong|first11=Daniel Y.|date=2015-07-30|title=Wireless Optofluidic Systems for Programmable In Vivo Pharmacology and Optogenetics|url=https://www.cell.com/cell/abstract/S0092-8674(15)00828-4|journal=Cell|language=English|volume=162|issue=3|pages=662\u2013674|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2015.06.058|issn=0092-8674|pmid=26189679}}</ref> In 2018, Al-Hasani published a novel method to be able to detect endogenously released peptides from active neural circuits in vivo.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=Wong|first2=Jenny-Marie T|last3=Mabrouk|first3=Omar S|last4=McCall|first4=Jordan G|last5=Schmitz|first5=Gavin P|last6=Porter-Stransky|first6=Kirsten A|last7=Aragona|first7=Brandon J|last8=Kennedy|first8=Robert T|last9=Bruchas|first9=Michael R|date=2018-09-03|editor-last=Kauer|editor-first=Julie A|editor2-last=Dulac|editor2-first=Catherine|editor3-last=Kauer|editor3-first=Julie A|editor4-last=Evans|editor4-first=Christopher|editor5-last=Mains|editor5-first=Richard E|title=In vivo detection of optically-evoked opioid peptide release|url=https://doi.org/10.7554/eLife.36520|journal=eLife|volume=7|pages=e36520|doi=10.7554/eLife.36520|issn=2050-084X}}</ref> She combined in vivo [[optogenetics]] with [[microdialysis]] so that researchers can stimulate genetically identified neurons and also detect the peptides that are released that might be mediating neural circuit changes and behavioral outputs.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 2017, Al-Hasani was recruited to stay at [[Washington University School of Medicine]], along with her husband Jordan McCall, and take on a primary appointment as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Pharmaceutical and Administrative Sciences at the [[St. Louis College of Pharmacy]] as well as an adjunct appointment as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Anesthesiology at the [[Washington University School of Medicine]] (WUSM).<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani and McCall were the first two researchers to be appointed positions at the new Center for Clinical Pharmacology, formed by a merging of the St. Louis College of Pharmacy and WUSM.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani's lab focuses on understanding the neural circuitry involved in addiction, stress, and chronic pain by specifically focusing on the opioid system to elucidate targets for future therapies.<ref name=\":0\" /> By building and using innovative tools for in vivo neural circuit dissection, Al-Hasani and her team study the role of the kappa opioid system in the generation of negative affective states that might accompany chronic pain, withdrawal, and preclude nicotine cessation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In April 2020, Al-Hasani was awarded the Young Investigator Grant from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation to support her research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2020/ream-al-hasani-wins-young-investigator-grant.html|title=Al-Hasani Receives Young Investigator Grant|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n==== Role of Kappa Opioid System in Affective Component of Pain ====\nIn 2019, Al-Hasani helped dissect physical pain from its emotional affective counterpart in a study published in Neuron.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2019/connection-between-pain-and-emotion-in-the-brain.html|title=Faculty Researchers Uncover the Connection Between Pain and Emotion in the Brain|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani and her colleagues at Washington University sought out to understand how the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] system mediates the emotional response to pain, which can lead to drug overdose and co-morbid psychiatric conditions such as depression.<ref name=\":9\" /> They targeted their investigation to the ventral shell of the nucleus accumbens (NAc), which Al-Hasani had previously shown to be involved in negative affective states.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Massaly|first=Nicolas|last2=Copits|first2=Bryan A.|last3=Wilson-Poe|first3=Adrianne R.|last4=Hip\u00f3lito|first4=Lucia|last5=Markovic|first5=Tamara|last6=Yoon|first6=Hye Jean|last7=Liu|first7=Shiwei|last8=Walicki|first8=Marie C.|last9=Bhatti|first9=Dionnet L.|last10=Sirohi|first10=Sunil|last11=Klaas|first11=Amanda|date=2019-05-08|title=Pain-Induced Negative Affect Is Mediated via Recruitment of The Nucleus Accumbens Kappa Opioid System|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(19)30164-3|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=102|issue=3|pages=564\u2013573.e6|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2019.02.029|issn=0896-6273|pmid=30878290}}</ref> They found that pain recruits the dynorphin-kappa opioid system in the NAc, and that the dynorphinergic cells are more active during inflammatory pain due to a decrease in inhibitory inputs onto these cells.<ref name=\":10\" /> By blocking dynorphinergic kappa opioid receptor signalling in the shell of the NAc, they are able to alleviate the decrease in motivation that results from the experience of pain.<ref name=\":10\" />\u00a0 These findings show that the kappa opioid system modulates the emotional aspects of the experience of pain and could serve as a less addictive target for pain treatment compared to opiates.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n==== Outreach ====\nBeyond her direct contributions to scientific innovation in the WUSM community, Al-Hasani has helped to mentor the younger generation of scientists and create a space for them to enter the pipeline from a young age.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2019/summer-research-scholars-program.html|title=Summer Research Scholars Program Inspires Students to Think Outside the Box|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani and McCall recently created a program for undergraduates to explore research opportunities and advance current research at Washington University.<ref name=\":11\" /> They have both hosted undergraduates in their labs and sent them to conferences to present their findings to the broader scientific community.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* International Narcotics Research Conference Young Investigator Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anesthesiology.wustl.edu/inrc-honors-ream-al-hasani-phd-with-2020-young-investigator-award/|title=INRC Honors Ream Al-Hasani, PhD, with 2020 Young Investigator Award|last=pyursik|date=2020-01-16|website=Anesthesiology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* Young Investigators Grants from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/brain-and-behavior-research-foundation-awards-grants-to-five-researchers/|title=Brain and Behavior Research Foundation awards grants to five researchers|date=2020-02-24|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* \"Pathway to Independence Award\" from NIDA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruchaslab.org/lab-news|title=Lab News|website=BRUCHAS LAB|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Most cited publications ==\n   \n*Al-Hasani R, Bruchas MR. Molecular mechanisms of opioid receptor-dependent signaling and behavior. ''Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists.'' 2011 Dec 1;115(6):1363-81. Cited 608 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS>Google Scholar author page  [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C33&q=Ream+Al-Hasani&btnG=#d=gs_cit&u=%2Fscholar%3Fq%3Dinfo%3AkdxpJnlyrLYJ%3Ascholar.google.com%2F%26output%3Dcite%26scirp%3D0%26hl%3Den] Accessed April 9, 2019  </ref>\n*McCall JG, Al-Hasani R, Siuda ER, Hong DY, Norris AJ, Ford CP, Bruchas MR. CRH engagement of the locus coeruleus noradrenergic system mediates stress-induced anxiety. ''Neuron''. 2015 Aug 5;87(3):605-20. Cited 200 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n*Al-Hasani R, McCall JG, Shin G, Gomez AM, Schmitz GP, Bernardi JM, Pyo CO, Park SI, Marcinkiewcz CM, Crowley NA, Krashes MJ. Distinct subpopulations of nucleus accumbens dynorphin neurons drive aversion and reward. ''Neuron''. 2015 Sep 2;87(5):1063-77. Cited 145 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n*Trang T, Al-Hasani R, Salvemini D, Salter MW, Gutstein H, Cahill CM. Pain and poppies: the good, the bad, and the ugly of opioid analgesics. ''Journal of Neuroscience''. 2015 Oct 14;35(41):13879-88. Cited 122 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n*\n\n== References ==\n{{scholia|author}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{catimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Al-Hasani, Ream}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:British expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:British neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:British pharmacologists]]\n[[Category:British anaesthetists]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American pharmacologists]]\n[[Category:American anesthesiologists]]\n[[Category:Washington University School of Medicine faculty]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|British neuroscientist and pharmacologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Ream Al-Hasani\n| image             = File:Al-Hasani, Ream Headshot 2017.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = British\n| fields            = Neuroscience, Pharmacology\n| workplaces        = Washington University in St. Louis, Center for Clinical Pharmacology\n| alma_mater        = University of Portsmouth, University of Surrey\n| known_for         = Kappa opioid signalling in the negative affect associated with pain\n| awards            = INRC Young Investigator Awards, Young Investigators Grants from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation, \"Pathway to Independence Award\" from NIDA\n| Institutions      = Washington University in St. Louis, Missouri\n}}\n'''Ream Al-Hasani''' is a British neuroscientist and pharmacologist as well as an Assistant Professor of [[Anesthesiology]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis]], Missouri. Al-Hasani studies the endogenous [[opioid]] system to understand how to target it therapeutically to treat addiction, affective disorders, and chronic pain.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAl-Hasani grew up in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.storiesofwin.org/profiles/2020/4/1/dr-ream-al-hasani|title=Dr. Ream Al-Hasani|website=Stories of WiN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani's family moved from [[Iraq]] to the UK for her father's academic career before she was born.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her parents planned on returning to [[Iraq]] after her birth but decided against it due to war in the [[Middle East]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Al-Hasani was the only [[Muslims|Muslim]] girl in her school, and though there were not many Middle Eastern role models in science, she became fascinated by the effects of drugs on the brain and decided to pursue a career in academia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAl-Hasani completed her undergraduate degree at the [[University of Portsmouth]] in the UK, graduating with a degree in Pharmacology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clinicalpharmstl.org/research/alhasani.html|title=Ream Al-Hasani, Ph.D., Assistant Professor|website=www.clinicalpharmstl.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> After completing her undergraduate degree, Al-Hasani pursued an internship in industry at [[GlaxoSmithKline]] where she studied [[Neurodegeneration|neurodegenerative diseases]] and [[neuroinflammation]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2017/first-faculty-researchers-announced.html|title=Appointment of First Faculty Researchers Announced|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani's year-long internship studying neuroscience in industry inspired her to pursue a PhD in neuropharmacology.<ref name=\":0\" /> She would become the first woman in her family to obtain a doctorate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Graduate work ===\nFunded by the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council]], Al-Hasani was able to pursue her graduate studies at the [[University of Surrey]] in England.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani was interested in exploring the interactions between [[adenosine]] and [[dopamine receptor]]s in morphine addiction for her PhD, so she sought co-mentorship from Ian Kitchen, Professor of Neuropharmacology, and [[Susanna Hourani]], Professor of Pharmacology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Endogenous Opioids ====\nIn 2010, Al-Hasani and her colleagues in the Kitchen Lab published a paper in the [[European Journal of Neuroscience]] exploring the influence of genetic variability on heroin addiction.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bailey|first=Alexis|last2=Metaxas|first2=Athanasios|last3=Al-Hasani|first3=Ream|last4=Keyworth|first4=Helen L.|last5=Forster|first5=Duncan M.|last6=Kitchen|first6=Ian|date=February 2010|title=Mouse strain differences in locomotor, sensitisation and rewarding effect of heroin; association with alterations in MOP-r activation and dopamine transporter binding|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20384817|journal=The European Journal of Neuroscience|volume=31|issue=4|pages=742\u2013753|doi=10.1111/j.1460-9568.2010.07104.x|issn=1460-9568|pmid=20384817}}</ref> When they compared a strain of highly inbred mice to typical control mice, they found differences in the behavioural effects of [[heroin]] and differences in the neurobiological substrates mediating these differences.<ref name=\":2\" /> Specifically, they found that highly inbred mice had much higher sensitivity to the rewarding properties of heroin yet inbred did not display increased location upon administration of heroin unlike control mice.<ref name=\":2\" /> When they looked for the neurobiological substrates of these effects, they found that heroin decreased [[\u039c-opioid receptor|mu opioid receptor]] (MOP-r) density in controls but not in the inbred mice, MOP-r stimulated binding was twofold higher in controls compared to inbreds, and heroin increased expression of dopamine transporters in inbred mice but not in controls.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n==== Adenosingeric and Dopaminergic Signalling ====\nIn 2011, Al-Hasani published a first author paper in [[Neuroscience (journal)|Neuroscience]] exploring the interaction between [[dopamine]] signalling and adenosine signalling in the [[ventral tegmental area]] (VTA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=R.|last2=Foster|first2=J. D.|last3=Metaxas|first3=A.|last4=Ledent|first4=C.|last5=Hourani|first5=S. M. O.|last6=Kitchen|first6=I.|last7=Chen|first7=Y.|date=2011-09-08|title=Increased desensitization of dopamine D\u2082 receptor-mediated response in the ventral tegmental area in the absence of adenosine A(2A) receptors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21669258|journal=Neuroscience|volume=190|pages=103\u2013111|doi=10.1016/j.neuroscience.2011.05.068|issn=1873-7544|pmid=21669258}}</ref> Since adenosine A(2A) receptors have been known to modulate neurotransmitter systems and modulate neural activity in the striatum, she sought to see if this was also true in the VTA.<ref name=\":3\" /> When Al-Hasani knocked out A(2A) receptors and looked the dopamine receptor 2 (D2) mediated inhibition in the VTA, she found that A(2A) knockouts had D2 receptor desensitization leading to reduced maximal inhibition.<ref name=\":3\" /> A follow up to this finding was published in Neuropharmacology in 2013 looking at the ability of A(2A) receptors to modulate cholinergic signalling through interactions with [[nicotinic acetylcholine receptor]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Metaxas|first=Athanasios|last2=Al-Hasani|first2=Ream|last3=Farshim|first3=Pamela|last4=Tubby|first4=Kristina|last5=Berwick|first5=Amy|last6=Ledent|first6=Catherine|last7=Hourani|first7=Susanna|last8=Kitchen|first8=Ian|last9=Bailey|first9=Alexis|date=2013-08-01|title=Genetic deletion of the adenosine A2A receptor prevents nicotine-induced upregulation of \u03b17, but not \u03b14\u03b22* nicotinic acetylcholine receptor binding in the brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0028390813001196|journal=Neuropharmacology|language=en|volume=71|pages=228\u2013236|doi=10.1016/j.neuropharm.2013.03.023|issn=0028-3908}}</ref>\n\n=== Postdoctoral work ===\nAl-Hasani took time to travel after her PhD and then decided to move to America for her postdoctoral work.<ref name=\":0\" /> She joined the lab of Michael Bruchas in the Department of Anesthesiology at [[Washington University School of Medicine]] in St. Louis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruchaslab.org/lab-news|title=Lab News|website=BRUCHAS LAB|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Bruchas, Al-Hasani began to explore the kappa opioid system and associated neural circuitry to understand its role in driving motivated behaviors.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani wrote a first-athour review paper in 2011 discussing the opioid system in the brain and how opioid receptors not only mediate intracellular signal transduction pathways to modulate molecular and cellular responses as well as their role in behaviors associated with analgesia, reward, depression, and anxiety.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=Bruchas|first2=Michael R.|date=2011-12-01|title=Molecular Mechanisms of Opioid Receptor-dependent Signaling and Behavior|url=https://anesthesiology.pubs.asahq.org/article.aspx?articleid=1934470|journal=Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists|language=en|volume=115|issue=6|pages=1363\u20131381|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e318238bba6|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> In 2013, Al-Hasani published a first author paper in [[Neuropsychopharmacology (journal)|Neuropsychopharmacology]] where she investigated the interactions between [[Norepinephrine|noradrenergic]] (NA) and [[dynorphin]]/[[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid systems]] in the forebrain.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Foshage|first3=Audra M.|last4=Bruchas|first4=Michael R.|date=November 2013|title=Locus Coeruleus Kappa-Opioid Receptors Modulate Reinstatement of Cocaine Place Preference Through a Noradrenergic Mechanism|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/npp2013151|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=38|issue=12|pages=2484\u20132497|doi=10.1038/npp.2013.151|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> She found that kappa opioid receptor(KOR)-induced reinstatement of cocaine CPP was potentiated when beta-adrenergic signalling was blocked and that the interactions between adrenergic signalling and KOR signalling occur external to the [[locus coeruleus]].<ref name=\":4\" /> Her findings were novel since the interaction between the KORs and the NA system had not been previously known, and she established its role in the reinstatement of [[cocaine]] drug seeking behavior.<ref name=\":4\" /> Also in 2013, Al-Hasani published a paper exploring the effects of stress on the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] system in the context of drug relapse.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Bruchas|first3=Michael R.|date=2013|title=Exposure to chronic mild stress prevents kappa opioid-mediated reinstatement of cocaine and nicotine place preference|url=https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fphar.2013.00096/full|journal=Frontiers in Pharmacology|language=English|volume=4|doi=10.3389/fphar.2013.00096|issn=1663-9812}}</ref> She found that various stressors cause [[Emotional dysregulation|dysregulation]] of kappa opioid circuitry, but interestingly, mild stressors cause adaptive changes in the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] circuitry that might be protective against drug relapse.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 2015, Al-Hasani helped elucidate the mechanisms by which the [[locus coeruleus]] [[Noradrenergic and specific serotonergic antidepressant|noradrenergi]]<nowiki/>c (LC-NE) system generates stress-induced anxiety in rodents.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=McCall|first=Jordan G.|last2=Al-Hasani|first2=Ream|last3=Siuda|first3=Edward R.|last4=Hong|first4=Daniel Y.|last5=Norris|first5=Aaron J.|last6=Ford|first6=Christopher P.|last7=Bruchas|first7=Michael R.|date=2015-08-05|title=CRH Engagement of the Locus Coeruleus Noradrenergic System Mediates Stress-Induced Anxiety|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(15)00606-6|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=87|issue=3|pages=605\u2013620|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2015.07.002|issn=0896-6273|pmid=26212712}}</ref> They found that activation of the LC-NE neurons increases stress-induced anxiety and aversion and that inhibition attenuates these behaviors.<ref name=\":6\" /> They also found that specifically the [[corticotropin-releasing hormone]] positive neurons in the LC that receive inputs from the central amygdala are the neural subpopulation within the LC responsible for mediating the anxiety-like behaviors.<ref name=\":6\" /> Later in 2015, Al-Hasani published a first-author paper in Neuron describing distinct functions of two different subregions of the nucleus accumbens (NAc) that are mediated by [[dynorphin]]-[[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid receptor]] (KOR) signalling.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Gomez|first4=Adrian M.|last5=Schmitz|first5=Gavin P.|last6=Bernardi|first6=Julio M.|last7=Pyo|first7=Chang-O.|last8=Park|first8=Sung Il|last9=Marcinkiewcz|first9=Catherine M.|last10=Crowley|first10=Nicole A.|last11=Krashes|first11=Michael J.|date=2015-09-02|title=Distinct Subpopulations of Nucleus Accumbens Dynorphin Neurons Drive Aversion and Reward|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(15)00713-8|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=87|issue=5|pages=1063\u20131077|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2015.08.019|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Specifically, she found that stimulating dynorphinergic cells in the ventral shell of the NAc elicits aversive responses via KOR activation while stimulating dynorphinergic cells in the dorsal shell of the NAc elicits appetitive behaviors mediated by\u00a0 KOR signalling.<ref name=\":7\" /> Al-Hasani's work in the Bruchas Lab has helped to elucidate the role of the dynorphin-kappa opioid system in modulating affective states and in mediating drug reinstatement.<ref name=\":7\" /> It also led to her winning an NIH Pathway to Independence Award (K99/R00) which provided her the funding to start her own lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2017/first-faculty-researchers-announced.html|title=Appointment of First Faculty Researchers Announced|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Tool Development ====\nAl-Hasani has also helped create novel technologies in the Bruchas Lab with which to probe neural circuits. Al-Hasani optimized wireless [[Optogenetics|optogenetic]] technologies that allow for neural circuit modulation without animal movement being constrained by tethering.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCall|first=Jordan G.|last2=Kim|first2=Tae-il|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Huang|first4=Xian|last5=Jung|first5=Yei Hwan|last6=Al-Hasani|first6=Ream|last7=Omenetto|first7=Fiorenzo G.|last8=Bruchas|first8=Michael R.|last9=Rogers|first9=John A.|date=December 2013|title=Fabrication and application of flexible, multimodal light-emitting devices for wireless optogenetics|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2013.158|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=8|issue=12|pages=2413\u20132428|doi=10.1038/nprot.2013.158|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Al-Hasani also merged wireless [[Optogenetics|optogenetic]]<nowiki/>s with pharmacology such that various compounds can be administered to the brain while certain neural circuits are being activated or inhibited to explore the effects of these compounds on neural circuit function and behavioral output.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jeong|first=Jae-Woong|last2=McCall|first2=Jordan G.|last3=Shin|first3=Gunchul|last4=Zhang|first4=Yihui|last5=Al-Hasani|first5=Ream|last6=Kim|first6=Minku|last7=Li|first7=Shuo|last8=Sim|first8=Joo Yong|last9=Jang|first9=Kyung-In|last10=Shi|first10=Yan|last11=Hong|first11=Daniel Y.|date=2015-07-30|title=Wireless Optofluidic Systems for Programmable In Vivo Pharmacology and Optogenetics|url=https://www.cell.com/cell/abstract/S0092-8674(15)00828-4|journal=Cell|language=English|volume=162|issue=3|pages=662\u2013674|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2015.06.058|issn=0092-8674|pmid=26189679}}</ref> In 2018, Al-Hasani published a novel method to be able to detect endogenously released peptides from active neural circuits in vivo.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Al-Hasani|first=Ream|last2=Wong|first2=Jenny-Marie T|last3=Mabrouk|first3=Omar S|last4=McCall|first4=Jordan G|last5=Schmitz|first5=Gavin P|last6=Porter-Stransky|first6=Kirsten A|last7=Aragona|first7=Brandon J|last8=Kennedy|first8=Robert T|last9=Bruchas|first9=Michael R|date=2018-09-03|editor-last=Kauer|editor-first=Julie A|editor2-last=Dulac|editor2-first=Catherine|editor3-last=Kauer|editor3-first=Julie A|editor4-last=Evans|editor4-first=Christopher|editor5-last=Mains|editor5-first=Richard E|title=In vivo detection of optically-evoked opioid peptide release|url=https://doi.org/10.7554/eLife.36520|journal=eLife|volume=7|pages=e36520|doi=10.7554/eLife.36520|issn=2050-084X}}</ref> She combined in vivo [[optogenetics]] with [[microdialysis]] so that researchers can stimulate genetically identified neurons and also detect the peptides that are released that might be mediating neural circuit changes and behavioral outputs.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 2017, Al-Hasani was recruited to stay at [[Washington University School of Medicine]], along with her husband Jordan McCall, and take on a primary appointment as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Pharmaceutical and Administrative Sciences at the [[St. Louis College of Pharmacy]] as well as an adjunct appointment as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Anesthesiology at the [[Washington University School of Medicine]] (WUSM).<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani and McCall were the first two researchers to be appointed positions at the new Center for Clinical Pharmacology, formed by a merging of the St. Louis College of Pharmacy and WUSM.<ref name=\":1\" /> Al-Hasani's lab focuses on understanding the neural circuitry involved in addiction, stress, and chronic pain by specifically focusing on the opioid system to elucidate targets for future therapies.<ref name=\":0\" /> By building and using innovative tools for in vivo neural circuit dissection, Al-Hasani and her team study the role of the kappa opioid system in the generation of negative affective states that might accompany chronic pain, withdrawal, and preclude nicotine cessation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In April 2020, Al-Hasani was awarded the Young Investigator Grant from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation to support her research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2020/ream-al-hasani-wins-young-investigator-grant.html|title=Al-Hasani Receives Young Investigator Grant|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n==== Role of Kappa Opioid System in Affective Component of Pain ====\nIn 2019, Al-Hasani helped dissect physical pain from its emotional affective counterpart in a study published in Neuron.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2019/connection-between-pain-and-emotion-in-the-brain.html|title=Faculty Researchers Uncover the Connection Between Pain and Emotion in the Brain|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani and her colleagues at Washington University sought out to understand how the [[\u039a-opioid receptor|kappa opioid]] system mediates the emotional response to pain, which can lead to drug overdose and co-morbid psychiatric conditions such as depression.<ref name=\":9\" /> They targeted their investigation to the ventral shell of the nucleus accumbens (NAc), which Al-Hasani had previously shown to be involved in negative affective states.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Massaly|first=Nicolas|last2=Copits|first2=Bryan A.|last3=Wilson-Poe|first3=Adrianne R.|last4=Hip\u00f3lito|first4=Lucia|last5=Markovic|first5=Tamara|last6=Yoon|first6=Hye Jean|last7=Liu|first7=Shiwei|last8=Walicki|first8=Marie C.|last9=Bhatti|first9=Dionnet L.|last10=Sirohi|first10=Sunil|last11=Klaas|first11=Amanda|date=2019-05-08|title=Pain-Induced Negative Affect Is Mediated via Recruitment of The Nucleus Accumbens Kappa Opioid System|url=https://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/S0896-6273(19)30164-3|journal=Neuron|language=English|volume=102|issue=3|pages=564\u2013573.e6|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2019.02.029|issn=0896-6273|pmid=30878290}}</ref> They found that pain recruits the dynorphin-kappa opioid system in the NAc, and that the dynorphinergic cells are more active during inflammatory pain due to a decrease in inhibitory inputs onto these cells.<ref name=\":10\" /> By blocking dynorphinergic kappa opioid receptor signalling in the shell of the NAc, they are able to alleviate the decrease in motivation that results from the experience of pain.<ref name=\":10\" />\u00a0 These findings show that the kappa opioid system modulates the emotional aspects of the experience of pain and could serve as a less addictive target for pain treatment compared to opiates.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n==== Outreach ====\nBeyond her direct contributions to scientific innovation in the WUSM community, Al-Hasani has helped to mentor the younger generation of scientists and create a space for them to enter the pipeline from a young age.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlcop.edu/news/archive/2019/summer-research-scholars-program.html|title=Summer Research Scholars Program Inspires Students to Think Outside the Box|website=www.stlcop.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Al-Hasani and McCall recently created a program for undergraduates to explore research opportunities and advance current research at Washington University.<ref name=\":11\" /> They have both hosted undergraduates in their labs and sent them to conferences to present their findings to the broader scientific community.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* International Narcotics Research Conference Young Investigator Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anesthesiology.wustl.edu/inrc-honors-ream-al-hasani-phd-with-2020-young-investigator-award/|title=INRC Honors Ream Al-Hasani, PhD, with 2020 Young Investigator Award|last=pyursik|date=2020-01-16|website=Anesthesiology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* Young Investigators Grants from the Brain and Behavior Research Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/brain-and-behavior-research-foundation-awards-grants-to-five-researchers/|title=Brain and Behavior Research Foundation awards grants to five researchers|date=2020-02-24|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* \"Pathway to Independence Award\" from NIDA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruchaslab.org/lab-news|title=Lab News|website=BRUCHAS LAB|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Most cited publications ==\n   \n*Al-Hasani R, Bruchas MR. Molecular mechanisms of opioid receptor-dependent signaling and behavior. ''Anesthesiology: The Journal of the American Society of Anesthesiologists.'' 2011 Dec 1;115(6):1363-81. Cited 608 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS>Google Scholar author page  [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C33&q=Ream+Al-Hasani&btnG=#d=gs_cit&u=%2Fscholar%3Fq%3Dinfo%3AkdxpJnlyrLYJ%3Ascholar.google.com%2F%26output%3Dcite%26scirp%3D0%26hl%3Den] Accessed April 9, 2019  </ref>\n*McCall JG, Al-Hasani R, Siuda ER, Hong DY, Norris AJ, Ford CP, Bruchas MR. CRH engagement of the locus coeruleus noradrenergic system mediates stress-induced anxiety. ''Neuron''. 2015 Aug 5;87(3):605-20. Cited 200 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n*Al-Hasani R, McCall JG, Shin G, Gomez AM, Schmitz GP, Bernardi JM, Pyo CO, Park SI, Marcinkiewcz CM, Crowley NA, Krashes MJ. Distinct subpopulations of nucleus accumbens dynorphin neurons drive aversion and reward. ''Neuron''. 2015 Sep 2;87(5):1063-77. Cited 145 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n*Trang T, Al-Hasani R, Salvemini D, Salter MW, Gutstein H, Cahill CM. Pain and poppies: the good, the bad, and the ugly of opioid analgesics. ''Journal of Neuroscience''. 2015 Oct 14;35(41):13879-88. Cited 122 times according to Google Scholar <ref name=GS />\n